INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2080,1,'2013-10-11 17:00:45','2013-10-11 17:00:45','<div>\n\nIn it\'s continuing efforts to advance search results, Google has added yet another algorithm change, also named for an animal. Code-named \"Hummingbird\", the new change rips apart one SEO\'s most sacred pillars: the need for keywords.\n\nYou read that right. Keywords and keyword-stuffed pages are going to be a thing of the past.\n\nHummingbird represents a fundamental shift in search results because it addresses the rapidly-growing shift to voice-based searches (Google Voice, Google Glass, SIRI, etc.) and when we search via voice, well, we search differently.\n\n<strong>Text-Based Searches\n</strong>When we type our searches we use keywords, Boolean operators (AND, OR, NOT, etc.) and tricks to narrow our searches. We also tend to make fairly long queries (for example, cutting and pasting in entire quotations or song lyrics).\n\n<strong>Voice-Based Searches</strong>\n<strong><a href=\"http://www.convinceandconvert.com/content-marketing-2/how-google-is-forcing-your-content-to-get-better/\">According Jay Baer, when we speak our searches, it\'s a whole different ball game</a></strong>. We tend to ask entire questions. Boolean operators? Forget it. How does one speak in all capitals? With question-based searches, the onus is now on Google to comprehend the question and provide accurate answers.\n\n<strong>The Semantic Web. Finally.</strong>\nWe\'ve long discussed the Semantic Web, but it\'s been a nice theory—until now. With Hummingbird, Google has their technology to the point where it can understand your questions and provide answers that make more sense.\n\nGoogle search expert, <strong><a href=\"http://venturebeat.com/2013/10/02/things-not-strings-how-googles-new-hummingbird-algorithm-sets-the-stage-for-the-future-of-mobile-search/\">Matt Cutts put it best</a></strong> when he recently said the Google of the future \"is about things, not strings.\"\n\n<strong>How will Hummingbird affect the way you write copy?</strong> Let us know in the comments below.\n\n</div>','Penguins and Pandas and Hummingbirds, Oh My!','','publish','open','open','','penguins-pandas-hummingbirds-oh','','','2013-10-11 17:00:45','2013-10-11 17:00:45','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2080',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2236,1,'2013-10-17 20:12:16','2013-10-17 20:12:16','<h2>While today’s Marketing Directors have great technology at their disposal, how many of them are actually using their analytics reports to shrink the gap between marketing and revenue?</h2>\n\nIn fact, the problem may not be that CMOs <em>have</em> the tools they need—it’s that they have too many and few of them play well with others. We’ve seen this time and again. An agency wants to have all the best-in-class tools, which is laudable, but ends up with an impressive array of tools that don’t interact or share data with each other.\n\n<strong>As a result, the Marketing Officer is left with at least six different reports:</strong> social media, Web traffic, SEO, CRM, behavioral targeting and paid marketing. Someone has to make sense of several unrelated data formats month after month. Six solid reports but… <strong>where’s THE report?</strong>\n<blockquote>\n<h2>“Half the money I spend on advertising is wasted; the trouble is I don’t know which half.”</h2>\n</blockquote>\nWe prefer to work with an integrated tool (FULL DISCLOSURE: We use <a href=\"http://www.hubspot.com/\">Hubspot</a>) that gives us one report for everything. It’s less time-consuming for our Marketing Director and gives us a holistic view. We actually <em>know</em> what our leads are doing at any time—without making assumptions based on slightly overlapping data points that <em>seem</em> to indicate a correlation.\n\n<strong>We discussed this at length in our last eBook:</strong> An Introduction to Closed Loop Marketing. If you are struggling with this same issue, <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/closed-loop-marketing\"><strong>you should download and read this book</strong></a>—it’s free. We hope you find some useful information in it.\n\n[hs_action]\n\nAre you struggling with too many reports? Lots of analytics but no insights? <strong>Leave a comment and let us know</strong>. We’d love to hear from you.','Lots of analytics, but where’s THE REPORT?','','publish','open','open','','lots-analytics-reports','','','2013-10-17 20:12:16','2013-10-17 20:12:16','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2236',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2361,1,'2013-03-01 15:53:50','2013-03-01 20:53:50','In the last five years mobile devices have rocked our world, and with them have evolved our dependency, fascination and love of mobile apps. Steve Jobs ingeniously created delicious “must have” new technologies which spawned countless new industries and markets. Mobile apps are a perfect example. There is always a new app, a free app, “an app for that” ... always a “must have” app. What did we do before our apps? The ubiquity and obsession makes nearly every marketer and C-level think, “We need an app!”\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_5502\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/?attachment_id=5502\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-5502\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5502\" title=\"PopTech 2009 attendees, day 2 - 24\" alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/4049950966_240f4bd59c-300x254.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"254\" /></a> Photo by <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/yourdon/\">Ed Yourdon</a>[/caption]\n\nThere is no question, the staggering statistics perpetuate the “must have” feeling. The mobile app selection is expanding exponentially, traveling zero to over a million in just five years. When apps hit 10,000 in 2008, it was considered huge news. Little did we know it was just the beginning! The website 148apps.biz features <a title=\"app store mobile app metrics\" href=\"http://148apps.biz/app-store-metrics/\" target=\"_blank\">up-to-date mobile app metrics</a> and estimates that today there are currently nearly 800,000 apps available in the app store, more than 200,000 publishers, and over 800 apps submitted for approval in January alone! As of today, the average price of an app is $1.58; and according to engadget.com, app store downloads hit 40 million in January 2013 with nearly half of the count being accumulated in 2012. Starting to feel like your mobile strategy is behind?\n\nDiving into <a title=\"Ingenex Digital Marketing mobile app development\" href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/services/iphone-and-mobile-applications\" target=\"_blank\">mobile app development</a> requires thoughtful consideration followed by comprehensive strategy. As a digital marketer, we go through this discussion regularly with clients. There are a few basic questions you can ask yourself before you decide to take the next step:\n\n<strong>1. Do you need a responsive website, a dedicated mobile site or a mobile app?</strong> There are reasons good reasons for each. Adobe does a good job of layout out the <a title=\"mobile sites vs mobile apps\" href=\"http://www.adobe.com/inspire/2012/02/mobile-websites-vs-mobile-apps.html\" target=\"_blank\">differences between mobile sites and mobile apps</a>. Once you have decided if you actually need (rather than just want) a mobile app, then comes the fun part. The ideas and strategy!\n\n<strong>2. What will the mobile app do?</strong> The world is your oyster! There are templates to utilize or an invention can be born. Maybe it serves a specific purpose for your organization or maybe it could be repurposed and benefit your industry as a whole. It should fulfill (create) a need or provide a worthwhile service. This will help it become a \"must have\" app.\n\nOf course there are a lot more questions and answers that lead to a successful mobile strategy. The good news is if you are reading this, then you are thinking about mobile, which means you are on the right path! If you are not sure of your next step, ask for help with your <a title=\"mobile strategy\" href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com\" target=\"_blank\">mobile strategy</a>.\n\nTo learn more, download our <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/closed-loop-marketing\" target=\"_blank\">FREE e-book on Closed Loop Marketing</a>.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nOriginally appeared on <a href=\"http://thedigitalbus.com\" target=\"_blank\">The Digital Bus blog</a>.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/dharmasphere/3128330968/\">premasagar</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/2.0/\">cc</a>','The Need for a Mobile App','','publish','open','open','','need-mobile-app','','','2013-03-01 15:53:50','2013-03-01 20:53:50','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2361',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2363,1,'2013-03-06 17:40:04','2013-03-06 22:40:04','<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mobile_search\">Mobile search</a> is the information users can obtain through searches performed on internet-enabled mobile phones or mobile platforms.\n\nMobile search is a significant and growing segment of the mobile marketing industry. It’s been predicted that mobile search marketing will <a href=\"http://www.reportlinker.com/p0131265/Mobile-Marketing-Advertising-Challenges-and-Opportunities.html\">grow</a> significantly by 2015 and will reach around 73 percent by the end of 2013 already. The increasing popularity of mobile search is bringing new challenges for marketers. However, before we jump into them, let’s understand the differences between mobile and desktop search results.\n\n<strong>1. Local searches are more prominent on a mobile device </strong>\n\nAs an example, we searched for a phrase “grocery store” from a laptop and an iPhone.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/optimize-your-mobile-search-results/mobile-search/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-5536\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-5536\" title=\"Mobile-Search\" alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/Mobile-Search.jpg\" width=\"600\" height=\"366\" /></a>\n\nIn the mobile Google search, left, Google Places listing appeared higher than on the search results from the laptop, right. When search comes from a mobile device, Google also tells you how far away the place is located from you (if you allow search engine to recognize your location).\n\nTherefore, mobile search results are more customized and help a mobile user to find out information quicker, especially on the move.\n\n<strong>2. Autocomplete results appear before actual results in mobile search</strong>\n\nWhen you type anything on your mobile device, you can see the autocomplete results first. And only after clicking on one of them are you directed to search results. In contrast, in desktop search, apart from autocomplete options suggested by Google, you also see the actual search results on the same page.\n\nTherefore, it is highly recommended to optimize your mobile search with call-to-action keyword phrases, so users would easily find relevant content.\n\n<strong>3. Rich snippets are displayed differently on a mobile device</strong>\n\n<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knowledge_Graph\">Knowledge graph</a> is a rich snippet used by Google to improve the search engine’s search results with semantic information from different sources. The graph is usually displayed on a right in a desktop search; however, it is among the search results in a mobile device what makes it less visible.\n\nTherefore, when optimizing mobile search, work on improving visibility.\n\n<strong>Mobile Search Challenges</strong>\n\nConstantly growing mobile industry makes it difficult for <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/\">digital marketing agencies</a> to plan a strategy for optimizing search on mobile devices. The variety is always good, but it is a huge challenge for marketers who are dealing with mobile search optimization. Because of increasing amount of different mobile channels and applications it is difficult to measure success of such optimizing.\n\nMobile search, <a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/local-businesses-need-to-focus-on-mobile-seo/\">especially localized search</a>, will be the dominant activity for digital marketers for the next year. Therefore, to increase the customers’ engagement rate, they should not ignore its differences from the desktop search.\n\nOur answer is “Yes!” You should care about mobile search if you want your business to be a successful one.\n\n<em>–By Elena Nadtochiy</em>\n\nTo learn more, download our <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/seo-from-the-experts\" target=\"_blank\">FREE e-book on SEO from the Experts</a>.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nOriginally appeared on <a href=\"http://thedigitalbus.com\" target=\"_blank\">The Digital Bus blog</a>.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/stephangeyer/3501272881/\">Stephan Geyer</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/2.0/\">cc</a>','Optimize Your Mobile Search Results','','publish','open','open','','optimize-mobile-search-results','','','2013-03-06 17:40:04','2013-03-06 22:40:04','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2363',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2366,1,'2013-04-01 17:59:11','2013-04-01 21:59:11','As companies continue to implement mobile elements into their business strategies, one of the most important aspects to consider is the transition of website design between devices. Incorporating responsive web design into your mobile site will ensure that users can access your content on any device they may be using.\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em></em><strong>What is Responsive Web Design?</strong>\n<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Responsive_web_design\">Responsive web design</a>, or RWD, is an approach to website design that assures content is seamless and can be viewed easily across a wide range of devices. The content offered on a website is adapted to each type of screen it is displayed on. Whether it be a laptop, tablet, or smartphone, the information being accessed will have the same look and feel. This offers an optimal viewing experience to users and allows companies to gain maximum exposure for their site.</p>\n<strong>How Does it Work?</strong>\nRWD uses <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Media_queries\">media queries</a> to adapt current CSS to each viewing platform. The media query analyzes the type of device each site is attempting to be displayed on and from there inputs the best optimized stylesheet. The main role of the query is to adjust the width of the browser so that the content can fit in the given screen size. It also scales images and resizes them for the best resolution possible. The way the media queries adjust content style ensures that information is displayed correctly on any given device.\n\n<strong>Why is Responsive Web Design Necessary for Mobile?</strong>\nOne of the most difficult aspects of converting a website to mobile is making sure its viewable on multiple devices. With a new smartphone on the market every few months, its hard to keep up with this wide range of platforms. <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/services/web-site-design\">Implementing responsive web design</a> assures companies that a user will not have trouble viewing and navigating their site. With more and more internet users opting to get their news, shop, and search on their mobile devices, making sure that your mobile website is accessible and responsive is essential.\n\n<em>–By Laura Ene</em>\n\nOriginally appeared on <a href=\"http://thedigitalbus.com\">The Digital Bus blog</a>.','Mobile-Friendly Responsive Web Design','','publish','open','open','','mobile-friendly-responsive-web-design','','','2013-04-01 17:59:11','2013-04-01 21:59:11','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2366',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2374,1,'2013-11-01 18:29:34','0000-00-00 00:00:00','Content is at the heart of all things digital and without content the internet would not exist. Likewise, regularly updated content is at the heart of your online presence, and without it you don\'t exist.\n\nWhy? Because stagnant websites and blogs don\'t rank well in search, and social profiles without posts have almost no way of gaining followers. Therefore even though you are out there on the internet, no one will stumble upon you aren’t pushing out new content. Blogs, websites and social media all feed each other; your <a title=\"Interactive Marketing Agency in Ann Arbor\" href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com\">interactive marketing</a> is a turbine and content is its fuel.\n\nDon\'t worry! This doesn\'t mean you need to dedicate days to penning pages for your website. Here are five ways fun and easy ways to generate new content:\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_5634\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"187\"]<a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/vine1.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5634\" title=\"Vine Video App on iPhone\" alt=\"Vine Video App\" src=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/vine1-187x300.jpg\" width=\"187\" height=\"300\" /></a> Vine App on my iPhone[/caption]\n\n<strong>1. Videos</strong>\n\nToday the creation and sharing of videos couldn’t be easier. Who ever thought you would carry a quality video camera with you at all times right on your phone? Well, you do, so use it! Every business and organization has worthwhile content to share via video. Try interviewing someone at your company or an expert in your field. If you have products, show how they work. You could also do video testimonials about your product or service, these can be very powerful! Check out a <a title=\"Article about Vine \" href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2013/03/06/771378/\">cool new app called Vine</a> allowing users to upload and share six-second videos. It is the Pinterest of video, and it is growing quickly. Think six seconds is too short? Remember the online attention span is less than 10 seconds!\n\n<strong>2. Photos</strong>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_5576\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"187\"]<a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/loupcharmant.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5576\" alt=\"Loup Charmant on Instagram\" src=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/loupcharmant-169x300.jpg\" width=\"187\" height=\"332\" /></a> Instagram App on my iPhone[/caption]\n\nPictures are another fun, easy and captivating piece of content you can create with right with your phone.\n<a title=\"Instagram\" href=\"http://instagram.com\">Instagram</a> (free) and <a title=\"Hipstamatic\" href=\"http://hipstamatic.com\">Hipstamatic</a> ($1.99) are two great options to try. Both are easy and fun ways to transform your picture into a piece of art and share directly to Facebook and Twitter. My friend, owner and lead designer for Loup Charmant, shared this image during her daily routine showing how she is creating beautiful buttons. This simple act gives her instant credibility as a fashionista. Start snapping some pix!\n\n<strong>3. Podcasts</strong>\n\nIf you are a chatty Kathy, then <a title=\"Definition of Podcast\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Podcast\">podcasts</a> might be your thing. Podcast are easy to create and distribute. Services such as Blog Talk Radio, Spreaker and Podbean make recording easy and integrate directly with the iTunes Store. The iTunes Store will get your message out to masses, but you can also put your podcast on your website and link to it from your blog and social pages.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_5622\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"187\"]<a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/pulse.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5622\" alt=\"Pulse News Content App\" src=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/pulse-169x300.jpg\" width=\"187\" height=\"332\" /></a> Pulse App on my iPhone[/caption]\n\n<strong>4. Curated Content</strong>\n\n<a title=\"Articles on Curated Content\" href=\"http://mashable.com/category/content-curation/\">Curated content</a> is a perfect way to portray yourself or your business as an expert. In todays world of endless content, there is no reason not to leverage great existing information. Get a steady flow of information on topics of your choice the \"old fashioned\" way with RSS feeds. I like to use Google Reader because I can easily follow both my subscriptions and hashtags too. To add a hashtag to your RSS reader simply subscribe to \"http://search.twitter.com/search.atom?q=%23hashtag\" and replace \"hashtag\" with the actual one you want to follow. I also love apps like Pulse, Flipboard and Google Currents which allow you to curate and customize your news feed. With any of these options you can share great tid-bits directly to Facebook or Twitter. Just add a comment of brilliance when you share!\n\n<strong>5. Infographics</strong>\n\nSeemingly everybody loves an infographic. You can easily find them by searching Google or you can create your own pretty easily with infogr.am. Another service called Visual.ly which allows for infographic creation, also has a library of nearly 30,000 infographics to browse and share. Whether you create new or share existing, if you think it is interesting so will others.\n\nSo there you go ... five fun ways to quickly and easily create content to <a title=\"Digital Marketing Agency in Ann Arbor\" href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com\">boost your digital marketing</a> efforts! If you do one of these a week, I am sure you will notice a difference in your traffic and brand following. Good luck!','Boost Interactive Marketing With Content','','draft','open','open','','','','','2013-11-01 18:29:34','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2374',0,'post','',0);
