INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2458,1,'2013-03-11 18:15:18','2013-03-11 22:15:18','Content is at the heart of all things digital and without content the internet would not exist. Likewise, regularly updated content is at the heart of your online presence, and without it you don\'t exist.\n\nWhy? Because stagnant websites and blogs don\'t rank well in search, and social profiles without posts have almost no way of gaining followers. Therefore even though you are out there on the internet, no one will stumble upon you aren’t pushing out new content. Blogs, websites and social media all feed each other; your <a title=\"Interactive Marketing Agency in Ann Arbor\" href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com\">interactive marketing</a> is a turbine and content is its fuel.\n\nDon\'t worry! This doesn\'t mean you need to dedicate days to penning pages for your website. Here are five ways fun and easy ways to generate new content:\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_5634\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"187\"]<a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/vine1.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5634\" title=\"Vine Video App on iPhone\" alt=\"Vine Video App\" src=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/vine1-187x300.jpg\" width=\"187\" height=\"300\" /></a> Vine App on my iPhone[/caption]\n\n<strong>1. Videos</strong>\n\nToday the creation and sharing of videos couldn’t be easier. Who ever thought you would carry a quality video camera with you at all times right on your phone? Well, you do, so use it! Every business and organization has worthwhile content to share via video. Try interviewing someone at your company or an expert in your field. If you have products, show how they work. You could also do video testimonials about your product or service, these can be very powerful! Check out a <a title=\"Article about Vine \" href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2013/03/06/771378/\">cool new app called Vine</a> allowing users to upload and share six-second videos. It is the Pinterest of video, and it is growing quickly. Think six seconds is too short? Remember the online attention span is less than 10 seconds!\n\n<strong>2. Photos</strong>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_5576\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"187\"]<a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/loupcharmant.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5576\" alt=\"Loup Charmant on Instagram\" src=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/loupcharmant-169x300.jpg\" width=\"187\" height=\"332\" /></a> Instagram App on my iPhone[/caption]\n\nPictures are another fun, easy and captivating piece of content you can create with right with your phone.\n<a title=\"Instagram\" href=\"http://instagram.com\">Instagram</a> (free) and <a title=\"Hipstamatic\" href=\"http://hipstamatic.com\">Hipstamatic</a> ($1.99) are two great options to try. Both are easy and fun ways to transform your picture into a piece of art and share directly to Facebook and Twitter. My friend, owner and lead designer for Loup Charmant, shared this image during her daily routine showing how she is creating beautiful buttons. This simple act gives her instant credibility as a fashionista. Start snapping some pix!\n\n<strong>3. Podcasts</strong>\n\nIf you are a chatty Kathy, then <a title=\"Definition of Podcast\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Podcast\">podcasts</a> might be your thing. Podcast are easy to create and distribute. Services such as Blog Talk Radio, Spreaker and Podbean make recording easy and integrate directly with the iTunes Store. The iTunes Store will get your message out to masses, but you can also put your podcast on your website and link to it from your blog and social pages.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_5622\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"187\"]<a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/pulse.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5622\" alt=\"Pulse News Content App\" src=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/pulse-169x300.jpg\" width=\"187\" height=\"332\" /></a> Pulse App on my iPhone[/caption]\n\n<strong>4. Curated Content</strong>\n\n<a title=\"Articles on Curated Content\" href=\"http://mashable.com/category/content-curation/\">Curated content</a> is a perfect way to portray yourself or your business as an expert. In todays world of endless content, there is no reason not to leverage great existing information. Get a steady flow of information on topics of your choice the \"old fashioned\" way with RSS feeds. I like to use Google Reader because I can easily follow both my subscriptions and hashtags too. To add a hashtag to your RSS reader simply subscribe to \"http://search.twitter.com/search.atom?q=%23hashtag\" and replace \"hashtag\" with the actual one you want to follow. I also love apps like Pulse, Flipboard and Google Currents which allow you to curate and customize your news feed. With any of these options you can share great tid-bits directly to Facebook or Twitter. Just add a comment of brilliance when you share!\n\n<strong>5. Infographics</strong>\n\nSeemingly everybody loves an infographic. You can easily find them by searching Google or you can create your own pretty easily with infogr.am. Another service called Visual.ly which allows for infographic creation, also has a library of nearly 30,000 infographics to browse and share. Whether you create new or share existing, if you think it is interesting so will others.\n\nSo there you go ... five fun ways to quickly and easily create content to <a title=\"Digital Marketing Agency in Ann Arbor\" href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com\">boost your digital marketing</a> efforts! If you do one of these a week, I am sure you will notice a difference in your traffic and brand following. Good luck!\n\nTo learn more, download our <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/closed-loop-marketing\" target=\"_blank\">FREE e-book on Closed Loop Marketing</a>.\n\nOriginally appeared on <a href=\"http://thedigitalbus.com\" target=\"_blank\">The Digital Bus blog</a>.\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/25541021@N00/4340445558/\">mkandlez</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/2.0/\">cc</a>','Boost Your Interactive Marketing with Content','','publish','open','open','','boost-interactive-marketing','','','2013-03-11 18:15:18','2013-03-11 22:15:18','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2458',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2462,1,'2013-07-15 18:47:36','2013-07-15 22:47:36','<p dir=\"ltr\">The advertising and marketing industry are becoming more visual in the digital landscape. We have seen the most popular social networks, such as Facebook, Twitter, Google+ and Pinterest make adjustments to welcome a lot more visual content from advertisers and users. Why? Campaigns and websites with visual content have been ranked higher in the most popular search engines like Google and Bing. With this in mind, you need to strategize your content <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/\">digital marketing</a> plan.</p>\n\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_5968\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5968\" alt=\"by_mkhmarketing\" src=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/by_mkhmarketing--300x107.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"107\" /> Photo by <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/mkhmarketing/\">mkhmarketing</a>[/caption]\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you are launching a website, creating a blog post or an ad campaign, you must develop quality visual content. In the midst of the volume of content online originality is key. Visual content makes you a lot more interesting and appealing so your audience will more likely want to share with their network.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is easy to find visual content online, but more most ideal approach is to create your own and be original. If you don’t have the know-how, consider investing in an agency that has expertise in this field. At Ingenex, we design pieces that respect the brand, and we develop a strategy that is tailored to achieve the goal of our clients. It is very important that the visual content developed is clear and consistent with the strategy.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Understanding the goal of the client and create a visual content that communicates a compelling story is very important to agency. As we craft the story, we will start selecting the best imagery that will communicate to your audience effectively. There are different types of visuals and techniques in the digital industry: photos, videos, comics, memes, charts and others. After deciding the right visual, it is very important to find the right partners and platforms to disseminate the final product online. These partnerships are vital for the content to receive a high number of views and engagement.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The production of <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?feature=player_embedded&amp;v=wnJzbLZgJzg\">videos</a> is one of specialties Ingenex can help you with. <a href=\"http://www.k-space.com/\">k-Space</a> is one of our clients for who we\'ve successfully launched different videos for their social media presence. A great video has rich content, impeccable visual quality and great sound. Our <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/portfolio\">portfolio </a>also shows other example of work and services we can help you with.</p>\nVisual content allows you to take your presence online to the next level, engaging with your audience to make the relationship sharable. Don’t miss this opportunity to stay “in the zone” of the digital industry. If you need support coming up and developing the best visual content for your marketing strategy, let\'s talk! Call Ingenex today at 1-888-Ingenex.\n\n<em>–By João Mattos</em>\n\nTo learn more, download our <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/closed-loop-marketing\" target=\"_blank\">FREE e-book on Closed Loop Marketing</a>.\n\nOriginally appeared on the <a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Digital Bus blog</a>.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/mkhmarketing/8540717756/\">mkhmarketing</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','Impact Your Content with Visuals','','publish','open','open','','content-visuals','','','2013-07-15 18:47:36','2013-07-15 22:47:36','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2462',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2468,1,'2013-07-09 18:59:41','2013-07-09 22:59:41','Customer testimonials are hands down one of the most effective pieces of marketing content you can use to achieve your business goals and generate sales. So why doesn\'t everybody use them?\n<ol>\n	<li>It takes time or is challenging to gather</li>\n	<li>They need to be positive, real and believable</li>\n	<li>Pushing them live in the right places in a timely fashion takes management</li>\n</ol>\nWell, good news! Today there are several ways to generate and leverage your customers\' positives feedback with very little effort and very big impact! It is critical to include it in your <a title=\"Ingenex Digital Marketing\" href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com\" target=\"_blank\">digital marketing strategy</a>. Here are three ways to solve those challenges and start using testimonials to generate leads right away.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_5934\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\"]<a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/typing1.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-5934\" alt=\"typing\" src=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/typing1.jpg\" width=\"640\" height=\"427\" /></a> Photo by Wiertz Sébastien[/caption]\n\n<strong>Facebook Recommendations</strong>\n<blockquote>“People influence people. Nothing influences people more than a recommendation from a trusted friend. A trusted referral influences people more than the best broadcast message. A trusted referral is the Holy Grail of advertising.”\n– Mark Zuckerberg</blockquote>\nOne of the simplest ways to collect and leverage customer testimonials is with the Recommendations box on your Facebook business page. Just ask your happy customers to “Like” your Facebook page and write a recommendation. You can even send them the link. All they have to do is click and type. This not only helps build your following, it allows the customer to write and submit their own review which makes it very believable and credible to prospective customers. Additionally, it not only goes on your Facebook page, but it also goes into the reviewers feed therefore is seen by all of their friends. Win-Win-Win!\n\n<strong>Video Testimonials</strong>\n\nWhat\'s more believable than reading a testimonial? Watching a testimonial! Statics prove that <a title=\"15 Must Know Stats for Online Video Content\" href=\"http://www.digiday.com/brands/celtra-15-must-know-stats-for-online-video/\">consumers value video content</a>. InternetRetailer.com says that 52 percent of consumers say that watching product videos makes them more confident in online purchase decisions and 92 percent of mobile video viewers share videos with others. Today creating and posting video is so doable. During your sales process when the moment is right, ask your customer to say a few words about their experience or the product for you.\n\nIf you don’t have the funds for a professional video, it’s ok ... just use your phone, tablet or computer to shoot the video. Don\'t stress, the content is invaluable. Once you have the video, simply upload to YouTube, Vimeo, Instagram, Vine, etc ... Any or all ... and share it on Facebook and Twitter. You should also add the link to your website right on your product page. Depending on your website setup, it maybe very easy to add a feed of your YouTube channel right to your site. This would automate the process and enable easy flow of great content to your prospective clients.\n\n<strong>Five Stars!</strong>\n<blockquote>\"Consumer reviews are significantly more trusted -- nearly 12 times more -- than descriptions that come from manufacturers, according to a survey of US mom Internet users by online video review site EXPO\".\n–eMarketer, February, 2010</blockquote>\nGive your customers what they want ... reviews! It is just another proven form of testimonial. It can easily be added to your website with a plugin or widget enabling your customers to add reviews or feedback and choose a star rating. This takes the management out of your hands and delivers quality believable content to your visitors. It can also be leveraged in your SEO efforts with <a href=\"http://support.google.com/webmasters/bin/answer.py?hl=en&amp;answer=99170\">rich snippets</a>. What looks more convincing than a five star review?\n\n<strong>Maximize Your Testimonials:</strong>\n\nFollow these six steps to get the most out of your customers\' positive comments:\n<ol>\n	<li>What is your business goal? Be specific.</li>\n	<li>Decide what testimonial content will help you achieve that goal.</li>\n	<li>Ask for the testimonials at the right (happy) moment and be specific.</li>\n	<li>Make entry or submission easy.</li>\n	<li>Review, comment and thank your happy customers.</li>\n	<li>Direct offline and online leads to view your customers testimonials</li>\n</ol>\nThere are loads of other options out there ... depending on your type of business and your digital properties, you may want to consider recommendations on LinkedIn profiles, and localized pages such as Google Places, Yahoo Local, and Yelp. Use technology and digital marketing to drive leads!\n\nTo learn more, download our <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/closed-loop-marketing\" target=\"_blank\">FREE e-book on Closed Loop Marketing</a>.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nOriginally appeared on the <a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Digital Bus blog</a>.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/owenwbrown/4857593259/\">owenwbrown</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','How to Leverage Customer Testimonials','','publish','open','open','','leverage-customer-testimonials','','','2013-07-09 18:59:41','2013-07-09 22:59:41','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2468',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2471,1,'2013-06-20 19:16:38','2013-06-20 23:16:38','In January 2013, nearly three months before the actual event, tickets for the infamous music festival <a href=\"coachella.com\">Coachella</a> were sold out in a record 20 minutes. One year prior, it had taken two hours, while two years before, it had taken almost two weeks. So what can Coachella attribute their great success to? Two words: event marketing.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_5886\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"600\"]<img class=\"size-large wp-image-5886\" alt=\"coachella\" src=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/coachella-600x177.png\" width=\"600\" height=\"177\" /> Screenshot of <a href=\"coachella.com\">coachella.com</a>[/caption]\n\nNot only does Coachella do great <a href=\"ingenexdigital.com/services/social-media-marketing\">social media event marketing</a> for their event, but their campaign is also unparalleled by any other. Here are a few ways in which even small businesses can learn from Coachella’s massive social media reach.\n\n<strong>Use Multiple Channels</strong>\n\nCoachella has an amazing social media campaign because they use multiple channels. On the bottom of their main website, there is a line of different social media sites through which concert attendees can interact with. Aside from their official website, they are also on Twitter, Facebook, Youtube, Instagram, Tumblr, Foursquare, and Google+.\n\nBy using multiple channels, Coachella is able to reach a broad spectrum of people with different preferences of social networks. Their vast social networking presence helps them to reach a large number people in a matter of minutes. In addition, concert goers can join the conversation by adding their own pictures or thoughts. This adds an even more important aspect of marketing through word of mouth.\n\n<strong>iPhone and Android apps</strong>\n\nIn addition to using different social media sites, Coachella noted the coming importance of smartphones in their audiences. By creating apps for both the iPhone and Android phones, Coachella is able to consolidate and disseminate official information to festival goers. Information such as lineup schedules, maps, and a way to check out what’s going on at Coachella in the social media world made the app an essential tool for a great festival experience.\n\n<strong>Pictures and Videos</strong>\n\nAlthough Coachella often gets sold out, through eye catching pictures and video, people who were unable to attend could feel like they were a part of the experience and get excited to attend the next year. Through different social media sites, fan produced content is an important way through which people can connect and endorse the event as a good time. In addition, hashtags are a creative way for Coachella to consolidate different images and information throughout social media sites, such as Twitter and Instagram. Being photo-centric is vital, because it is the most attractive and effective way for fans to absorb information.\n\nAlthough Coachella is a massive business with thousands of people who attend from all corners of the earth, these <a href=\"ingenexdigital.com\">digital marketing</a> tips are essential and can even be utilized by smaller businesses. Different shows and events can better capture their attendee’s attention if they are socially engaging with them through a variety of channels.\n\n<em>–By Stephanie Hur</em>\n\nTo learn more, download our <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/closed-loop-marketing\" target=\"_blank\">FREE e-book on Closed Loop Marketing</a>.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nOriginally appeared on The <a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Digital Bus blog</a>.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/daniel_iversen/5440123139/\">daniel_iversen</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','Learning from Coachella\'s Social Marketing Strategy','','publish','open','open','','coachellas-social-marketing','','','2013-06-20 19:16:38','2013-06-20 23:16:38','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2471',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2474,1,'2013-05-31 19:25:43','2013-05-31 23:25:43','If you work for an <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com\">internet marketing agency</a> that offers SEO services, you are undoubtedly concerned about how recent changes might effect your business. Whenever the big search engines push changes that profess to shake up results, many digital marketers get in a frenzy about what they can do to keep their high positioning. Unless you are one of the few that is still looking to employ black hat techniques, you really need not be worried. It is in their best interest to support well-maintained sites that provide relevant content to users.\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"212\"]<img alt=\"\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" width=\"212\" height=\"300\" /> <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/dirkgrund/\">Photo by Dirk Grund</a>[/caption]\n\nIn May of 2013, prospective changes to the Google algorithm were announced by Matt Cutts, one of the most highly held engineers on their search quality team. As with most of these updates, his underlying message was that people offering black hat <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com\">search engine optimization services</a> should keep a keen eye on their search visibility. Anyone playing the game by the book should not worry about anything and should keep going about their work as they have. He clearly states that these changes are tailored to reflect his company\'s best interests of supporting user-friendly websites with strong content.\n\nThe specifics of the algorithm change have not all been uncovered. However, Cutts did reveal certain categories of search issues that will be addressed. Spam issues with linking, paid advertorials on other sites, and the perceived authority of your own site will all be taken into further consideration when determining pagerank. Alongside that, <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com\">digital marketing</a> companies can expect to see a change in the abundance of clustered results from one website. Finally, Google will be putting forth more of a concerted effort to mark hacked sites and help webmasters determine how to avoid finding themselves in these situations.\n\nTo learn more, download our <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/seo-from-the-experts\" target=\"_blank\">FREE e-book on SEO From the Experts</a>.\n\nOriginally appeared on The <a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Digital Bus blog</a>.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/seoplanter/7460433450/\">SEOPlanter</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','It\'s All In The Algorithm','','publish','open','open','','all-in-the-algorithm','','','2013-05-31 19:25:43','2013-05-31 23:25:43','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2474',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2477,1,'2013-05-13 19:33:04','2013-05-13 23:33:04','<p dir=\"ltr\">Social media and search are continuously being tied together lately. Understanding how to connect the two within your brands digital marketing strategies is essential for creating great campaigns and engaging users. There are certain aspects of <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/services/social-media-marketing\">social media marketing</a> that must be complementary to search strategies. Making sure that elements work well together will produce better results for users and higher engagement for your company.</p>\n\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_5783\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"600\"]<a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/social-search-ingenex-blog.jpg\"><img class=\"size-large wp-image-5783\" alt=\"Photo by t_buchtele\" src=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/social-search-ingenex-blog-600x398.jpg\" width=\"600\" height=\"398\" /></a> Photo by <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/people/t_buchtele/\">t_buchtele</a>[/caption]\n\n<strong>Content</strong>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As social search evolves, so does the need to create valuable content to complement these types of searches. Without the right content within social media, searches can become non-relevant and produce results that aren\'t what users were initially looking for. Content such as social media posts, blogs, and landing pages must be written and internally linked correctly to reach the right consumers. Adjusting a brand’s tweets or posts to social media so they are relevant to what their users might be searching should be a standard. Keeping up to date with recent news topics, trends, or other types of popular media are some ways to go about this. For example, a viral video from two weeks ago would already be old news and the wrong type of content to market. Looking at recent news postings, friends tweets, or other outlets might be a better way to get relevant content. People are searching for what is popular at the moment, not three days ago. Making sure that strategies for content and search are complementing each other should always be part of a company\'s process.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Keywords</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Separate from content, keyword usage also plays a huge factor in how search and social are combined. Keywords play a big role in not only search engine optimization but also social media. Users that search certain keywords are most likely also using those keywords in their Facebook or Twitter posts. Making sure that the keywords and language in a brand\'s social media is similar and relevant to that used throughout the search strategy will make for a better brand voice and positive user experience.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Location Pages</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Finally, one of the more recent topics of interest for social and search is <a href=\"http://www.insidefacebook.com/2013/04/22/graph-search-optimization-the-new-seo-and-what-it-means-for-social-advertisers/\">the rise of Facebook’s Graph Search</a> feature. Many people are using this platform as a way to search for certain topics or places rather than the typical search engine. This being said, it will no longer be sufficient to have one Facebook page for a company or brand; expanding to different locations around the country will become necessary. If someone searches a brand’s company or store name in a specific city, they will want the information relevant to their location to come up as a result. Adjusting social media strategies to fit a variety of brand locations and pages will be something to begin implementing. More engagement with the brand via social media will be an outcome of this. Users will feel more obligated to comment or share a post about a store that is close to their relevant location.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">While there are many other areas of search and social that are necessary to restrategize or adjust, making sure that content, keywords, and location are consistent and relevant is at the top of the list. A <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com\">digital marketing agency</a> will see maximized benefits to implementing these ideas into both their social and search plans for the future.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>–By Laura Ene</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To learn more, download our <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/closed-loop-marketing\" target=\"_blank\">FREE e-book on Closed Loop Marketing</a>.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Originally appeared on The <a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Digital Bus blog</a>.</p>\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/bmevans/4432897287/\">bmevans80</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.0/\">cc</a>','Adjusting Brands to Social Search','','publish','open','open','','social-search','','','2013-05-13 19:33:04','2013-05-13 23:33:04','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2477',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2482,1,'2013-04-26 19:41:59','2013-04-26 23:41:59','Search engine results are under constant scrutiny from the <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com\">digital marketing</a> community. As the largest player in the game, Google feels the vast majority of this heat, which tends to be driven by the question mark surrounding their protection of privacy. One of the most recent additions to this discussion is their integration of social search results, quickly becoming one of the hottest topics in the industry.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_5765\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/Social-Search-Graph.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5765\" alt=\"Photo by brewbooks\" src=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/Social-Search-Graph-300x238.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"238\" /></a> Photo by <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/brewbooks/\">brewbooks</a>[/caption]\n\n<strong>Leveraging Social Networks for Realtime Results</strong>\nThe goal of Google has always been to provide its users with the most relevant search results possible. As connectedness is becoming one of the primary aspects of Internet usage, it seems that search engines cannot ignore the potential power that stems from the insights of social networks. Around 2008, countless start-up companies attempted to tackle the inclusion of social graphs in search results. Google decided to step into the equation with their Realtime Search service. This brought a variety of new tools into the picture, including realtime alerts for new social content and the ability to view full conversations from the biggest social networks. On top of that, a newly formed partnership between two internet juggernauts opened the door for Google users to access Twitter archives when searching for information on specific topics.\n\n<strong>Search Results Coming from Your World\n</strong>Upon expiration in July of 2011, the two companies decided not to renew their contract. This put Twitter\'s wealth of information back on the market and set Google\'s sights on a new social search solution. The emergence of Google Plus allowed the company to seize the opportunity for collecting and leveraging its own social information into its results. (Twitter, along with Facebook, has since partnered with Bing.) Deemed \"Search, plus Your World\", Google\'s new service intertwines normal search results with those derived from users\' social circles, determined by their activity within Google\'s suite of products. Now, contact lists and blog subscriptions can be tapped for figuring out which links are most appropriate for one\'s search results.\n\nWhat does this all mean? Social search is not something that should be ignored by anyone that offers <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/search-marketing\">search engine optimization services</a>. Although users have the opportunity to eliminate their social circle from implication in their search results, many of them do not even know that this is happening whenever they are signed in to their account. Ultimately, it seems that every time a digital agency is on the brink of \"figuring out\" <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com\">internet marketing</a>, a new development is announced that must be taken into consideration. Social search is certainly one of those.\n\nTo learn more, download our <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/seo-from-the-experts\" target=\"_blank\">FREE e-book on SEO from the Experts</a>.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nOriginally appeared on The <a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Digital Bus blog</a>\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/tigerpixel/3185410319/\">Tiger Pixel</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/2.0/\">cc</a>','Google\'s Stance on Social Search','','publish','open','open','','google-social-search','','','2013-04-26 19:41:59','2013-04-26 23:41:59','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2482',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2485,1,'2013-04-25 19:49:18','2013-04-25 23:49:18','Any good journalist will tell you <a title=\"Content Marketing Needs People\" href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/content-marketing-needs-people/\" target=\"_blank\">journalism is people centric</a>. What, where, when, why’s all are support for the most important piece of any story - the WHO. People look to the news and mass-media to find out about other people as a basic human drive to be social. We seek out stories, and every good story needs characters.\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5762 aligncenter\" alt=\"Digital Marketing &amp; social search - people\" src=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/8500837838_5eea19c124_c-300x199.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo by: <a title=\"Ashlie Forchione photo - social search\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/ashlieforchione/\" target=\"_blank\">Ashlie Forchione</a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">In a world where the internet has become so completely integrated with everyday life, members of the public crave non-filtered access to information and stories that are specifically relevant to them by people they can trust -- people like them. Mass media is seen by many to have an inherent bias. Reporters only pick up select “newsworthy” stories. Political slants have become associated with some reporting stations and papers. Everyone seems to have one reason or another not to “buy-in” to what these channels are saying.</p>\nSocial search is the result of the desire to connect with other people. It is the newest model of crowdsourcing. A way for people to find out what’s happening with other people in a non-filtered way and rely on the expertise of other average civilian-journalists for this information. Social search is one of the most important upcoming trends in digital marketing.\n\nAccording to an <a title=\"Experian internet use survey - social networks\" href=\"http://press.experian.com/United-States/Press-Release/experian-marketing-services-reveals-27-percent-of-time-spent-online-is-on-social-networking.aspx\" target=\"_blank\">Experian survey</a>, the typical American internet user spends 27% of their time on-line engaging on social platforms. This was the largest portion of time spent on any one segment of usage.\n\nSo what does social search mean for marketers? It means it is more important now than ever before than ever for any <a title=\"Ingenex Digital Marketing Agency\" href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com\" target=\"_blank\">digital agency</a> and companies of all sizes to have a social presence and engage in reputation monitoring. Mentions of your company matter beyond what is said in mass-media channels. What matters now is what people are saying about it in the media of the masses. Monitoring tools like Radian 6, SocialMention, and Twitter’s Advanced Search can help you aggregate sentiment towards your brand across social channels.\n\nEven major search engines like Google and Bing have incorporated social results into search results and social platforms like <a title=\"Using Facebook Graph Search for Marketing\" href=\"http://mashable.com/2013/04/04/how-small-businesses-can-take-advantage-of-facebooks-graph-search/\" target=\"_blank\">Facebook</a> are making it easier to search socially. Be aware - the public is shifting its attention from traditional mass media to social, the media of the masses. They are writing their own stories. The tools above make it easy to stay aware and on top of social search results for your business and understand how they relate to your customer’s story. What monitoring sites do you use to stay aware of what’s happening in your company’s digital sphere?\n\nTo learn more, download our <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/closed-loop-marketing\" target=\"_blank\">FREE e-book on Closed Loop Marketing</a>.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nOriginally appeared on The <a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Digital Bus blog</a>.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/ansik/4425771596/\">ansik</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/2.0/\">cc</a>','Social Search: Mass Media to Media of the Masses','','publish','open','open','','social-search-2','','','2013-04-25 19:49:18','2013-04-25 23:49:18','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2485',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2488,1,'2013-04-01 20:01:16','2013-04-02 00:01:16','Google publicly announced their introduction of Enhanced Campaigns to AdWords in February of 2013.  This was very important news for anyone offering pay per click marketing services.  The announcement featured a glowing account of the improved targeting, measuring, and reporting opportunities that were being made available.   Alongside all of the benefits, though, was a hint at the complete transition to enhanced campaigns that is (allegedly) in store for the summer.\n\nIn the ensuing months, numerous digital marketing professionals are put to the task of determining whether or not to make the switch early.  This is a decision that does not necessarily translate seamlessly from client-to-client.  Thus, marketers need to consider the positives and negatives that enhanced campaigns will offer each of the accounts that they are managing.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_5696\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/Ingenex-Digital-Search-Marketing.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5696\" alt=\"Photo by Malcolm Murdoch\" src=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/Ingenex-Digital-Search-Marketing-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a> Photo by <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/mildswearwords/\">Malcolm Murdoch</a>[/caption]\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>ADVANTAGES\n</strong>\n\n<strong>Location Targeting</strong> - Statistics are now being provided on a per-location basis.  Campaigns that have multiple locations can now view information on each of these targets and are offered the opportunity to adjust bids accordingly.  Thus, if certain locations are performing better than others, marketers can make sure they are gaining a higher share of those impressions.\n<strong></strong>\n\n<strong>Ad Extensions</strong> - Certain ad extensions can now be applied to ad groups, rather than campaigns.  On top of that, sitelink extensions can now have their own ad scheduling settings.  Overall, this provides marketers with far more flexibility in determining how to structure their accounts, given their heightened ability to apply these extensions.\n<strong></strong>\n\n<strong>Call Tracking</strong> - Upgraded call extensions now provide advertisers with extensive call tracking information.  As a dimension of their advertising campaigns, marketers can view details on the calls that they have produced for their clients.  Accounts will be charged the standard cost-per-click for click-to-call extensions on mobile devices, and will not be charged anything for the manual dialing of a Google forwarding number.\n\n<strong>DISADVANTAGES\n</strong>\n\n<strong>Mobile Targeting</strong> - Mobile-only campaigns are becoming a thing of the past.  Enhanced campaigns only offer the ability to adjust mobile bids.  Thus, although you can effectively create a campaign that targets everything BUT mobile, you will not be allowed to target only mobile users.  Mobile segmentation--e.g. device model, carrier--will also be highly restricted compared to the past.\n<strong></strong>\n\n<strong>Tablet Targeting</strong> - Tablets are now bundled in with desktops and cannot be targeted separately.  This will be problematic for anyone whose original strategy was to send tablet visitors to specified-tablet-URLs.  Enhanced campaigns require that websites detect whether or not a visitor is coming from a tablet and adjust to show them the proper webpage, accordingly.\n\n<strong>CONCLUSION</strong>\nIf you are going to make the switch to enhanced campaigns, get ready to spend some more money.  Improve the quality of information provided on each advertising campaign is intended to improve the ability to offer optimal online marketing services.  Unfortunately, this will likely come at a price.  Introducing bid adjustments for locations and mobile devices may steadily drive up the average cost-per-click across the board, especially for the most fruitful visitor demographics.  Similarly, setting ad extensions on a per-ad-group basis will likely also increase advertising competition. Ultimately, there are many things for any internet marketing firm to consider when making the decision to switch; extra time and effort will be needed to ensure the smoothest transition.\n\nTo learn more, download our <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/closed-loop-marketing\" target=\"_blank\">FREE e-book on Closed Loop Marketing</a>.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nOriginally appeared on The <a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Digital Bus blog</a>.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/hugovk/9520350808/\">hugovk</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.0/\">cc</a>','How Much Better Are Enhanced Campaigns?','','publish','open','open','','enhanced-campaigns','','','2013-04-01 20:01:16','2013-04-02 00:01:16','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2488',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2491,1,'2013-03-22 20:09:14','2013-03-22 20:09:14','<p style=\"text-align: left;\" align=\"center\">A few days ago I read somewhere that if you\'re not content marketing you\'re not marketing. And I must say, it\'s 100 percent true.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/elenamarchdigitabusblogimage.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter  wp-image-5685\" alt=\"elenamarchdigitabusblogimage\" src=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/elenamarchdigitabusblogimage.png\" width=\"283\" height=\"377\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo by <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/idovermani/\" target=\"_blank\">idovermani</a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><b>Design for Real People</b></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">In order to be a successful company you have to become a master of communication. Good content marketing delivers information that makes your customer more intelligent. In other words, you have to create and deliver relevant and valuable content to your target audience without forcefully selling it. Forget pitching your products or services because people don\'t want to listen to cliché sales speeches. People want something engaging and want it from someone they can trust.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><b>Account for the Robots</b></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><b></b>Companies can <a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/boost-interactive-marketing-with-content/\" target=\"_blank\">boost their content</a> through various sources like photographs, videos, podcasting, infographics, etc. They\'re all great ways to engage with customers and build a stronger relationship with them. However, engaging content is only useful if people can find it. Remember that you have to optimize your content, make it sharable and account for the robots - search engines.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><b>How?</b></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><b></b>There are many well-known content optimization techniques. Use <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Google_Searchology#Rich_Snippet\" target=\"_blank\">rich snippets</a> to make your content stand out so search engines \"engage\" with it. Snippets are microdata and microformats attached to search results and are often displayed as text or a precise and to the point description of the link above.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/elenablogmadonna.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter  wp-image-5686\" alt=\"elenablogmadonna\" src=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/assets/elenablogmadonna-600x239.png\" width=\"480\" height=\"191\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><b>Search Results for “Madonna”</b></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">There are different types of rich snippets. Traditional snippets are displayed in the form of a simple text description. Other snippets contain more robust data (see Madonna snippet example above). Other snippets contain additional information, like a YouTube rich snippet, which makes your content more visual and robust. In the Madonna rich snippet example above, people can listen to the artists\' songs directly from the search results. As a result customers are more engaged with your content which can improve the number of song downloads.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><b>What\'s in it for me?</b></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Now think like a content marketing strategist. Imagine the positive effect applying rich snippets would have on engaging content. Rich snippets could greatly improve the number of clicks, views or downloads of your content! According to a number of <a href=\"http://searchengineland.com/how-to-get-a-30-increase-in-ctr-with-structured-markup-105830\" target=\"_blank\">case studies</a> in the U.S. and abroad, rich snippets in search results can increase Click Through Rate (CTR) by 30 percent. Search engines, like people, engage with structured content. As a result this type of content ranks higher in search listings. To be successful marketers should <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/services\" target=\"_blank\">start structuring and optimizing their content</a>  to “engage robots” and make it easier for people to find.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em>– By Elena Nadtochiy</em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">To learn more, download our <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/closed-loop-marketing\" target=\"_blank\">FREE e-book on Closed Loop Marketing</a>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Originally appeared on The <a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Digital Bus blog</a>.</p>\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/eloqua/4690626051/\">Eloqua</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','Design for Real People, Account for the Robots','','publish','open','open','','design-for-real-people','','','2013-03-22 20:09:14','2013-03-22 20:09:14','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2491',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2503,1,'2013-11-21 20:20:24','2013-11-21 20:20:24','<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Start your SEO efforts by asking if you are doing the simple things first.</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Too often, SEO experts will offer thousands of sophisticated ideas requiring investments of time, personnel, and - of course - big money when often simple solutions can make the most immediate difference.  There are times when a big solution is necessary, but before you make top line investments see if you have done the simple things first.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>1.</strong> <strong>Have you linked all of your online identities to your web site?</strong>  Every single place that your business exists online should be linked back to your businesses website. Every single social network and business network has a means of connecting your profile back to your main website - SO USE THEM!.  These connections matter and matter to search rankings.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>2.</strong> <strong>Have you audited your content?</strong>  Every single piece of information on your website should serve a specific business purpose and also answer a need that a typical site visitor might have.  Make sure nobody will get a bad first impression by coming into contact with information that is not what they are looking for.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>3</strong>. <strong>Have you signed up for <a href=\"https://plus.google.com/110108719833340604840/posts\" target=\"_blank\">Google+</a>?</strong>  Do you have a Google + profile?  Join Google +, create a Google + profile (fill it out accurately and completely), Add the Google plus icon to your website and link it back and forth to your business website.  Fill out the Google +  authorship information.  Add a picture that is consistent across your online presence.  There is a good deal of evidence to suggest that Google + makes a difference in rankings and that authorship is a means Google uses to determine your sites authority (a key indicator in rankings).</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>4</strong>. <strong>Have you signed up for Linkedin?</strong>  Have you filled out a Linkedin profile?  Have you linked your business website to your Linkedin profile? Have you made a<a href=\"http://www.linkedin.com/company/ingenex-digital-marketing\" target=\"_blank\"> Linkedin profile</a> for your company?  The most significant business social network is Linkedin and fully connecting your business through your Linkedin presence is a critical step in boosting how search engines look at your site.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>5.</strong> <strong>Have you had all of your employees connect their social network presence through your business website?</strong>  As the world becomes more connected, the more connections to the world that your site has the better.  You hired your staff, be proud of them, welcome their connections into your business world.</p>\nI certainly am not suggesting that these simple steps will solve your SEO issues, but you should certainly make sure that all of these things are done up front to make sure you are doing the simple and cheap things first.\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If this helps, but you want to explore more ways to increase your SEO, feel free to try this free ebook, <strong><a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/seo-from-the-experts\" target=\"_blank\">Overcoming Your SEO Challenges.</a></strong></p>\nI hope these tips help you! If you have any SEO questions, any questions about this post, or stories to share please add your voice to the comment section below!\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/wwworks/1431384410/\">woodleywonderworks</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','5 Simple Steps to Increased SEO','','publish','open','open','','5-simple-steps-increased-seo','','','2013-11-21 20:20:24','2013-11-21 20:20:24','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2503',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2510,1,'2013-11-25 13:35:36','2013-11-25 18:35:36','<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Sales have changed, customers have changed, Marketers might be your best solution! </strong></p>\n<strong>The key to selling</strong> in a world where consumers are already educated, know the options, and know the costs, is creating disruptive insights and ideas that could solve customers problems. Nobody has more experience injecting innovation into customer solutions than marketing professionals. It might be time to include your marketing team (or firm) in all aspects of your sales efforts.\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>In a recent Harvard Business Review article</strong> by <a href=\"http://hbr.org/2013/11/dismantling-the-sales-machine/ar/5\" target=\"_blank\">Adamnson</a> et al (November 2013, p.103) the authors suggest that sales departments used to organize around a \'Process Focus\' where a customer, \"expressed a defined need, the sales team identified stakeholders with authority to spend, and then the sales team would demonstrate the value of your solution relative to the solution of your competitors.\"</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The article next suggests that sales has changed because customers are so much better educated. This education reduces the sales process to a Kayak.com style side-by-side set of comparisons.. The only solution, aside from simply competing on price, is what they call \'judgement oriented\' sales.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Judgement Oriented Sales\' suggests that, \"competing against a customer\'s ability to learn requires superior teaching skills,\" and \"a talent for revealing novel and important information about the business that the customer has overlooked.\" The key now is, helping them see the solutions that they never imagined or considered..</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Harvard article goes on to argue for a change in the very conception of what a sales manager does (this might very well be a valid suggestion). But, what they really seem to be  describing is a Digital Marketing Professional.  As you well know, what strategic digital marketers every single day, is find ways to apply innovations and disruptive ideas and technologies to the selling of brands and the solving of customer problems.</p>\nYour marketing team (or the marketing professionals at the firm that you work with) are already used to brainstorming ways to apply innovative and non-obvious solutions to customer problems.  Your marketing team or your marketing firm is already well-versed in strategically educating customers to see solutions beyond the obvious.\n\n<strong>When your company confronts the vast changes in the sales environment</strong>: You could reconfigure and re-educate your whole sales division.  You could hire or retrain your sales management team.  Or, Instead of trying to reinvent the sales division, it might make more sense (and cost less money) to build your marketing team or the marketing firm you work with into the entire loop of what your brand is trying to accomplish from the customer pitch, through product development and solutions. <strong>We find this approach works well.</strong>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you are thinking about sales in general, please help yourself to this free ebook:</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/30-lead-gen-tips\" target=\"_blank\">30 Greatest Lead Generation Tips, Tricks, and Ideas</a></p>\nIf you have any thoughts about the changes in the sales environment at your business please leave your comments in our comment section.  We would love to hear from you!\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/wwworks/4612188594/\">woodleywonderworks</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','Can your marketing revolutionize sales?','','publish','open','open','','can-marketing-revolutionize-sales','','','2013-11-25 13:35:36','2013-11-25 18:35:36','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2510',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2513,1,'2013-11-26 14:52:21','2013-11-26 19:52:21','<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>The real key to making Closed Loop Marketing work</strong> is the creation of a virtuous circle: your company, an integrated marketing tool, and a full-service digital marketing company like Ingenex.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Closed Loop Marketing is made possible by using an Integrated Marketing Tool (for, instance, we use Hubspot): but Closed Loop Marketing only really takes flight when you combine that tool with a content marketing and web development company like Ingenex.  What does a company like Ingenex bring to the table?</p>\nIt is true that your company should filter all of its search strategies, social media activities, email marketing activities, referral link strategies, paid search, organic search etc. through your web site, but to do so effectively requires a marketing vision and the application of innovation and designs to make that vision come to life.  Without this vision, how will your social efforts become inbound? <strong> Ingenex excels at turning the arrows from outbound back inbound toward your website so that every visitor becomes a trackable/convertable lead.</strong>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is important to track and identify all the traffic that comes through your website but it takes an inbound marketing company like Ingenex to turn \"follows\" to \"leads.\"  Having a million \'followers\" means very little if none of those \"followers\" ever enter into conversion behaviors. Without a vision, how will the people following you on Facebook become buyers on your website?  <strong>Ingenex excels at converting \"follows\" into \"leads.\"</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is very important to have an integrated tool that directs website visitors to a landing page with a submission form.  But it requires a vision of how to induce visitors to want to share personal  information through such forms.  Without such a vision, how will you overcome peoples resistance to sharing their personal information.  Ingenex has years of experience creating landing pages that convert visitors from interested into evangelists.</p>\nIf you really want to <strong>make your Closed-Loop Marketing system take off,</strong> you need to create a virtuous circle: combine your business, the integrated tool, and a firm like Ingenex.\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you want to learn more about how to create a Closed-Loop Marketing system please feel free to download this free ebook:</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/closed-loop-marketing\" target=\"_blank\">An Introduction to Closed Loop Marketing</a></p>\nIf you have experiences with, or questions about Closed-Loop Marketing we would love to hear your voice or answer your questions.  Thanks so much for checking us out!\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/vox_efx/2912195591/\">Vox Efx</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','The Marketing Trifecta: Ingenex, an Integrated Marketing Tool, and Closed Loop Marketing','','publish','open','open','','marketing-trifecta-ingenex-integrated-marketing-tool-closed-loop-marketing','','','2013-11-26 14:52:21','2013-11-26 19:52:21','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2513',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2518,1,'2013-12-02 14:51:34','2013-12-02 19:51:34','<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Bad content is worse than no content at all.  </strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Search engines care a great deal, in a semantic search world, about how useful your content is to your site visitors.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Given how you were likely taught about SEO this seems like \'crazy-talk,\' but its true.  No matter how often you hear that you should load your pages with nonsensical keywords, that you should produce hundreds of pages of barely relevant content, or that you should pay external sources to produce random piles of blog articles - the key to optimization is satisfied users.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>In other words, does your content satisfy what your customers came to your site looking for?</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">How should you approach the creation of content faced with the pressure to publish or perish?</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>1. Ask what needs your visitors come to your site to fill.</strong> Write and post content that directly satisfies those needs.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Bad content is worse than no content at all. Bad content is content that does not satisfy the needs of your visitors.  You have to know why they are coming to your site before you write. The most important thing you can do when you start working on content is to figure out what your visitors want and make sure your content directly addresses those needs (\'keep it simple stupid\' doesn\'t just work in the world of Apple designs).</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Many people mistakenly look at their <a href=\"http://thedigitalbus.com\" target=\"_blank\">business blog</a> as a vanity project, as a way to share things they find entertaining with their friends and/or customers. But, people come to a business site because they have specific business questions and needs, and they will not stay long enough to find out about your taste for chocolate covered cherries unless they have their needs satisfied first.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>2. Never post content for content\'s sake</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The entire shift in Google\'s algorithm was designed to reward content that satisfies visitors needs immediately.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Placing content just to seem active to search engines, especially in the world of semantic search algorithms, is more likely to backfire than help your position improve.  The more time people spend questioning the point of your posts the less likely they will be to engage in conversion behaviors.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There was a time when search engines cared much more about the words that appeared randomly throughout your content than they did about if users were interested at all.  That time is past and that kind of SEO is mostly dead.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>3. Get rid of old, bad, dead content</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">You want quality over quantity.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Cruelly and emotionlessly go through your site and get rid of content that does not help visitors meet their needs.  Get rid of  content that serves no meaningful business purpose.  Get rid of content that is dated.  Get rid of vanity content.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Do not think of your web site as a museum or historical repository for your companies documents.  If you cannot think of why anyone but you would care - they probably won\'t. <strong>Trash it!</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Do housecleaning on a regular basis.  Do not let visitors accidentally end up on pages that will annoy, frustrate, or turn them off from your business.</p>\n<strong>4. You can spark new kinds of engagement through content - but be careful</strong>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Put need satisfaction first, but, If your visitors have had their immediate needs satisfied you can be an opinion leader and try to move people to new interactions with your brand.  Please remember, however, that people do not read online like they read real books or watch television shows.  People online are scanning quickly and only looking for information that satisfies their needs..</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Think of immediate satisfaction as the price you have to pay to get customers to browse deeper on your site.  Remember all those times that you visited a site and could not find what you wanted.  If you stuck around, most wouldn\'t,, each minute you spent looking probably increased your frustration and turned you gradually against the brand.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you decide to go beyond simple satisfactions of immediate search needs, remember there is a thin line between business purpose and vanity project.  Question yourself about how each thing you post serves your business and leads someone toward conversion behaviors.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>5. Hire writers who can serve your strategic purposes</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Do not hire people who have no understanding, connection, or stake in your success.  Have strategic discussions with anyone you hire and make sure that the people you hire understand your needs.  For too long content providers have relied on peppering posts with SEO tricks and repetitive themes and charged simply to regurgitate tired content..</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Make sure that anyone you hire is up-to-date on the changes to Semantic SEO, understands your brand, and is at least familiar with the needs of your site visitors.  The importance of a good strategic discussion prior to hiring a writer cannot be overemphasized.  If you find good writers pay premium prices, that will allow you to ask for more engaged responsible content.</p>\nI am certainly not saying that you should not hire writers for your sites content.  I am saying that being smart about hiring to serve your brand and your business is as important in the world of content provision as it would be in any other area of your business.\n<p dir=\"ltr\">You will hear over and over that \'content is king\' and feel the pressure to find ways to willy-nilly get more content out on your website.  Resist this pressure.  Follow these tips and you should maximize the impact your content has on your sites SEO.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If this is the kind of problem you find yourself confronting.  Or you find the sheer volume of things you are trying to improve on your companies website and digital marketing overwhelming, <strong>I think you will find this free ebook really helpful:</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong><a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/10-step-redesign-checklist\" target=\"_blank\">10 Step Checklist for Website Redesign.</a></strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you are struggling with content provision and need to ask a question or have stories to share, leave a comment and let us know.  We would love to hear from you!</p>\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/mckln/3450127192/\">Wootang01</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nd/2.0/\">cc</a>','Is Bad Content King?  Five Suggestions for getting your content creation balance right','','publish','open','open','','bad-content-king','','','2013-12-02 14:51:34','2013-12-02 19:51:34','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2518',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2525,1,'2013-12-13 17:07:03','2013-12-13 22:07:03','<strong>Creating great customer experience is the essence of marketing.</strong>\n\nIf your marketing is not focused on adding value to your customers’ lives, it is not best serving your needs.\n\nThe last time you ordered from Amazon.com, did you order because you saw an Amazon advertisement?  Or, did you order, because Amazon.com satisfied your needs every single time and added value to your life?\n\n<strong>The most important thing you can do</strong> to market your company digitally is to make sure everything you do online is designed to create more meaningful customer experiences.\n\nThere is a great story in the book <a href=\"http://www.youtilitybook.com/\" target=\"_blank\">‘Youtility’</a> about a cab driver named <a href=\"http://www.taximike.com/\" target=\"_blank\">‘Taxi-Mike,’</a> who decided to market himself by writing – and putting online – “Taxi-Mike’s Dining Guide: Where to eat in Banff.”\n\n‘Taxi-Mike’s’ book was a moment of pure marketing genius that greatly expanded Mike’s business.  Why? ‘Taxi-Mike’ – through his dining guide - greatly contributed to the experience that his customers had when visiting Banff.  Taxi-Mike added value to his customers’ life through his marketing.\n\nYou might think social media - and other online activities - act as a megaphone that you can use to cut through customer—centricity and get attention on your brand.  <strong>But the focus on customer experience has to come first</strong>!  Jonah Berger and Catherine P. Taylor both see today’s environment as similar to the period television advertisers faced after the golden age.  Today’s environment is one of too many messages and not enough attention.\n\nBerger thinks, “’Liking’ something is a passive action, what you really want is engagement, where people are authentically sharing your brand with others…on a good day, your Tweet might get out to 1 to 2 percent of your followers (Jonah Berger is over Twitter, Strategy + Business, Winter 2013 p. 12).”\n\nAnd Taylor concludes, “Winners in the twenty-first century won’t be distinguished by how fast they master buzzwords or how many faddish new digital marketing campaigns they undertake.  Those <strong>winners will be organizations whose main focus is their customers’ journey</strong> and who possesses a relentless drive to understand and improve their journey from beginning to end (Strategy and Business, Winter, 2013).\n\n<strong>The megaphone-model might not have the impact it once did.</strong>\n\nYou could say that this means the end of advertising but the problem is more complicated.  As Taylor notes, “The vast majority of the interactions most of us have with brands are still going to be through advertising.  The problem is…the vast majority of those interactions will not enable or encourage consumer interactions with the brands they purport to be building.  Taglines be damned, it’s time to address how customers experience your brand (Strategy and Business, Winter, 2013).”\n\nWhat these distinguished authors are suggesting is that we should all take a laser-like focus and figure out how each message we send out impacts the consumer experience; how each page adds value to the customers’ experience with your website; how each tweet responds to consumer needs; how each snapchat serves to show how the brand wants to make each customers’ life better.\n\nWhat they are suggesting is that the key to everything in this new environment is creating a meaningful relationship with each customer.  Instead of adding to the noise, use your marketing to be seen as a haven from the noise.\n\nDigital Marketing agencies can best serve their customers by being focused on the customers experience through each message, on every platform, and with every page.  Brands can best be served by giving customers a reason to care about their relationship with your brand – not just a reason to spend a coupon etc.\n\nTaxi Mike helps his customers, many of whom are tourists, find great places they can go to enjoy a meal. And maybe, if he is lucky, they will have this meal while taking a ride in his cab. This synchronicity will happen because his marketing created relationships between his brand and his potential customers. This synchronicity is co-production at its best.\n\nTaxi-Mike shows he cares about peoples’ experience in his city, that he knows the terrain better than most, and that he wants to help them have a great meal.\n\n<strong>Be like Taxi-Mike</strong> – be involved in creating experiences that your customers care about!\n\nIf you are interested in more marketing information please help yourself to our free ebook: <strong><a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/30-lead-gen-tips\" target=\"_blank\">30 greatest lead generation tips.</a></strong>\n\nIf you have a story about ‘experience marketing’ like Taxi-Mike’s please leave it in our comment section or reply to the hashtag -<strong> #LikeTaxiMike</strong>\n\nBaer, <a href=\"http://www.youtilitybook.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Youtility, Why Smart Marketing is About Help not Hype</a>, 2013\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/thomasleuthard/5630775728/\">Thomas Leuthard</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a> (That is not Taxi Mike in the photo.)','‘Experience Marketing’ – Be Like Taxi-Mike!','','publish','open','open','','experience-marketing-like-taxi-mike','','','2013-12-13 17:07:03','2013-12-13 22:07:03','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2525',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2535,1,'2013-12-16 20:59:30','2013-12-17 01:59:30','<strong>1. Spend on digital</strong>\n“Money spent within the digital creative sector represents more return on investment than any other medium (Advertising Association, Advertising, 2013).”\nTraditional media buys are declining in return on investment (as people spend more and more time online and specifically, tethered to mobile devices). The goal is to reach people with the information they want, when they want it, and where they are at. Today, people are on mobile devices. Even if you believe in traditional media, people are increasingly viewing their traditional media through mobile devices or are using their mobile devices at the same time they interact with traditional media.\n\n<strong>2. Focus on experience</strong>\n‘Experience marketing’ means that you tailor your marketing approach to focus specifically on the experience each customer has with your brand. Don’t just make an offer, don’t just say something funny, don’t just brag about your accomplishments’ - try to use your marketing to add value to your customers’ lives. Charmin, for instance, created an app that let people share ratings for public restrooms. This app showed people that the brand cared about their customers - beyond just creating an experience with their product - and built loyalty\n\n<strong>3. Social media matters – as long as you use it to drive business back to your hub</strong>\nHaving a storefront on every single social media platform isn’t practical or effective. You want to use your social media efforts to drive business back through your hub (your website).\n\nDon’t fall in love with getting ‘likes’ or ‘followers’ – these markers only matter as far as they drive conversion behaviors in your customers or create new customers for you. Find ways to tie your social media likes and followers back to your website and through your brand.\n\n<strong>4. Social proof matters</strong>\nPeople tap 5.8 sources of information before deciding if they want to eat at even the most basis restaurants (Taylor, Strategy + Business, Winter 2013 p.12).” If you are going to put money into social media, try to curate social proof of the popularity of your brand. Try to find ways to drive public sharing of information that evangelizes your brand and products.\n\n<strong>5. Have a content philosophy</strong>\nThis is a subject I return to over and over again. Since you know most of your customers are coming into contact with your brand on a large number of possible devices – and you know that they have different attention spans and different screen sizes. Make sure you have a content philosophy that creates a uniform experience across devices and attention spans. At Ingenex, we believe in a philosophy of ‘Responsive Design’ that revolves around content being ‘device agnostic.’ In other words, the design starts with a baseline that communicates perfectly regardless of device.\n\nAlso, remember that certain products work better for mobile ads than others – the more utilitarian a product that requires an investment the more likely mobile ads will be successful. This is especially true when the mobile ad reinforces information from your longer form content and advertising.\n\nAdvertising is still a very important part of getting your customers from visitors to conversion, if you follow these simple tips – and think about your whole campaign as an integrated whole – you should spend your advertising dollars more wisely!\n\n<strong>If you want to know more about this, we would love for you to read this free ebook: <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/30-lead-gen-tips\" target=\"_blank\">30 greatest lead gen tips, tricks, and ideas.</a></strong>\n\nIf you have any thoughts about this post or have stories to share about this subject – please join in the conversation by commenting on this post.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/tracy_olson/61056391/\">Tracy O</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.0/\">cc</a>','5 Tips on getting the most from your marketing','','publish','open','open','','5-tips-on-get-the-most-from-marketing','','','2013-12-16 20:59:30','2013-12-17 01:59:30','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2535',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2545,1,'2013-12-20 15:45:30','2013-12-20 20:45:30','<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.firefighternation.com/article/news-2/national-firefighters-endowment-mobilizes-national-assistance-effort-detroit-fire-department\">Detroit Firefighters</a> respond to the <strong>highest number of structure fires in the USA</strong> but, “lack many of the basic equipment and tools they need to protect their neighbors and return home safely to their families.”</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">You can help provide support to these heroes through either the <a href=\"http://www.detroitmutualaid.com/\">Detroit Mutual Aid</a> Initiative or through the <a href=\"http://www.detroitpublicsafetyfoundation.org/donate/\">Detroit Public Safety Foundation</a>.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Make this a special holiday season for those that selflessly protect so many.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Why does the Detroit Fire Department need help?</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Everyone knows that Detroit is bankrupt.  What many do not know is the consequences for people doing one of the hardest and most thankless jobs in the world – fighting fires.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Around 800 Detroit Firefighters have to handle more than 30,000 calls a year, fight about 12,000 fires annually, and around 20-35 fires a day.</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Many of these firefighters have been demoted, not because they failed, because there is no money to pay them what they are worth.</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Departments budget was cut 20% in 2012 and many firefighters had to take a 10% cut in pay last year.</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Many of these firefighters chip in money from their own paychecks for basic necessities from toilet paper to bandages to food.</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Many of them work second jobs just to make ends meet.</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They deal with some of the worst neighborhoods and most dangerous situations imaginable.</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Virtually all of these firefighters are dealing with substandard and worn out equipment and respond in broken down fire-trucks needing all kinds of repairs.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\nAnd they endure all of this – by choice – so that they can save lives, protect property, and make a difference in their community.  .\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>How to help the Detroit Fire Department</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is the season of giving.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Donating to the Detroit Fire Department maximizes the impact of your giving – it has a multiplier effect – making sure firefighters have good equipment protects them which helps them to save more lives.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It’s a gift that keeps on allowing these great people to continue giving.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If the city doesn’t have the money to ensure these men and women are safe – we must do what we can to ensure that they are safe.  We have to do for them what they do for our larger community day and night 365 days (and nights) a year.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">You can help by going to <a href=\"http://www.detroitmutualaid.com/\">Detroit Mutual Aid</a> – where you can:</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Purchase a limited edition Detroit Mutual Aid shirt – all proceeds go to purchasing the items that the fire fighters have requested</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">You can donate or purchase actual items that have been requested by browsing the website</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">You can add the <a href=\"http://www.detroitmutualaid.com/pass-it-on.html\">Detroit Mutual Aid logo</a> to your social media to help get the word out</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">You can also donate money or pledge to purchase equipment or items at the <a href=\"http://www.detroitpublicsafetyfoundation.org/donate/\">Detroit Public Safety Foundation</a>.  You can also visit the main page and see all of the items that are being requested.</p>\n<strong>Help Ingenex Marketing help these heroes continue to do their incredible work!</strong>','Help the Detroit Fire Department this holiday season','','publish','open','open','','help-detroit-fire-department-holiday-season','','','2013-12-20 15:45:30','2013-12-20 20:45:30','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2545',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2550,1,'2014-01-02 20:03:58','2014-01-03 01:03:58','<strong>It\'s time to start looking into reading the tea leaves to divine what will be the most prominent trends in 2014.</strong>  <em>First up: short and perishable messaging – represented most popularly by the platform Snapchat.</em>\n\n<strong>Snapchat?</strong>\n\nSnapchat is one of the first ‘perishable’ messaging and social media platforms (meaning that the messages self-destruct after viewing.\n\nSnapchat effectively capitalized on two trends –<strong> perishability and short length</strong> – to capture a huge audience.  Reading the rest of this post will introduce you to Snapchat, explain why you should care, and introduce Snapchat’s new ‘Stories’ function – giving marketers a new way to tell stories.\n\n<strong>Is short the new long?</strong>\n\n<a href=\"http://www.entrepreneur.com/article/229806\">Anne Handley</a> wrote in Entrepreneur, “The new word in content marketing is small.  Increasingly, brands are marketing themselves in short-form social media like Vine, Twitter, Instagram, and Snapchat.”\n\nOne important lesson given the proliferation and popularity of short-form social networking platforms – it is going to become increasingly important to learn to compress our storytelling to distil each brands’ story quickly. Not only do we need to consider shorter storytelling but we also should think about the perishability of messaging.One platform that is entirely based around short messages in a perishable format is Snapchat.\n\nSnapchat allows users to send ‘snaps’ (pictures/messages) that permanently ‘self-destruct’ 10 seconds after they are opened by their intended target – they are, by design, temporary messages of temporary duration.\n\n<strong>Why should you care about Snapchat?</strong>\n\nWell the first reason is – trends do matter, as <a href=\"http://sethgodin.typepad.com/seths_blog/2013/12/heroes-of-the-revolution.html\">Seth Godin</a> said on his blog last week, “Rapid change exposes the work of outsiders, neophytes, and most of all those attracted to the chance to grow fast – Rapid change sweeps aside the status quo and those that defend it (the stuck formal geniuses and the stuck bureaucrats).  It replaces them with those willing to leap.”\n\nLots of people seem to believe that ‘short messaging’ and Snapchat have legs – in separate ‘end-of-year-prediction’ articles bloggers Mike Saunders, Fredrick Gonzales highlighted this trend and there are articles all over the net about using Snapchat for marketing (from ‘Mobile Marketer’ to ‘Tech Crunch’, even ‘AdWeek’).  <a href=\"http://thinkhouse.ie/blog/view/great-things-small-packages-a-snapshot-of-some-key-marketing-trends-in-2014\">Emily Cramp</a> of ‘Thinkhouse’ says in the Guardian UK that, “Brands that want to connect with youth audiences in a credible way will focus more than ever on…clever and bite-sized content.”\n\nA second reason is that Snapchat is becoming incredibly popular across the board (it’s not just for kids).  <a href=\"http://issuu.com/franj.glez/docs/the_wired_uk_-_world_in_2014\">Saul Klein</a> of Index Ventures says, “Snapchat…was barely known a year ago.  In June 2013 its estimated 150 million monthly users sent 200 million pictures and videos a day. There are currently four times as many images shared on Snapchat a day as on Instagram.”\n\nIn addition, with all the privacy concerns created by Big Data and the ongoing and rolling NSA challenges (apparently, the NSA is now spying on World of Warcraft – not kidding) people are starting to backlash against the long-life-social networking post.  <a href=\"http://www.theverge.com/2013/3/1/4049592/the-age-of-the-brag-is-over-why-facebook-might-be-losing-teens\">Some are arguing</a> that it will compete with Facebook directly in a relatively short-time.\n\nSnapchat also has what <a href=\"http://issuu.com/franj.glez/docs/the_wired_uk_-_world_in_2014\">Saul Klein</a> calls, ”A highly disruptive counter-meme.  It’s a service that’s more intuitively human than Google’s ‘store everything’ approach.  It’s all about the fleeting ephemeral moments that we share before they disappear.”\n\n<strong>Snapchat Marketing?</strong>\n\nSo, now that you care, can you market successfully on Snapchat? Depending on your business model, Snapchat offers unique and interesting functionality that creates opportunities for one-on-one marketing between customers and brands.\n\nHow is this possible?  How can a platform based on messages with a limited shelf life create opportunities for marketers?\n\nEven at the launch of Snapshot, inventive companies were using Snapchat to send one-time ten second coupons to be cashed in as they were opened at the register – giving new meaning to the limited time offer.  Obviously, the perishable nature of the messages can also add a sense of drama to your marketing effort.\n\nBut, in October, Snapchat added two new functions that promise much richer prospects for marketers:\n\n<strong>First, ‘Snapchat stories.’</strong>  ‘Stories’ allows a user (or business) to cobble together a string of ‘Snaps’ into what they call a ‘story.’  Each ‘story’ has privacy controls (as to who can see it) but is available for 24 hours after its posting.   From 10 seconds to 24 hours and from one ‘Snap’ to a string of ‘Snaps’ adds great potential for brands to utilize Snapchat to tell stories to customers.\n\nMany have suggested using Snapchat as a marketing tool to give users exclusive offers, sneak peeks of prototype testing, coupons, cheat codes for games, treasure hunts (users identifying items or places in pictures) within the time limit of the 24 hours etc.\n\n<strong>Second, after you finish a story</strong> there is a ‘double tap to x’ function.  In other words, when you finish seeing the story – a marketer or user could create a link that takes the watcher to a new place if they simply double tap.  On the Snapchat version of iTunes, double tapping is set to take the listener to the iTunes page of the band you were listening to.  Imagine your ‘snaps’ getting interested viewers back to your home or landing pages and through the purchase funnel.\n\nIt is a good idea to use every tool available to you to connect in every way possible with your potential customers.  Snapchat offers some really unique possibilities and in a way that could create much more personal advertising than was traditionally possible.\n\n<strong>2014 could be the year of Snapchat marketing!</strong>\n\nIf this post interests you, we would love to have you subscribe to our blog so you will know when new posts go live <strong><a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/blog/\" target=\"_blank\">http://ingenexdigital.com/blog/</a></strong>.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/davelawler/7370505166/\">DaveLawler</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nd/2.0/\">cc</a>','2014: Snapchat might be 2014’s best short-marketing platform','','publish','open','open','','2014-snapchat','','','2014-01-02 20:03:58','2014-01-03 01:03:58','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2550',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2560,1,'2014-01-06 16:39:22','2014-01-06 21:39:22','This is the second in my series of posts about interesting trends that could be huge in marketing for 2014.\n\n<strong>Today’s subject, Google +</strong>\n\n<strong>Google+ has legs in 2014.</strong>  More and more businesses will be turning to this network for the SEO benefits, the Authorship benefits, and the +Post advertising platform.\n\nWhat is Google+?\n\n<strong>Google+ is a social network</strong> that tries to create firewalls between global and selected sharing.  In other words, social sharing occurs between circles of pre-selected friends and you choose to whom you send all of your content.  In this manner, Google+ is an attempt to bridge the gap between peoples desire to share and peoples desire to protect their informational privacy.\n\nFor the first few years, Google+ struggled to find a consistent customer base and had not been considered a real threat to Facebook or even Twitter.  Recently, however, the numbers have shifted due to a number of recent pivots by Google, and 2014 very much could be the year of Google+.\n\n<strong>Why should you care about Google+?</strong>\n\n<a href=\"http://www.fathomdelivers.com/google-plus-for-business-2014/\">Melissa Matthews</a> gave numbers as a reason, “As of October 30<sup>th</sup>, Google+ had 300 million users and that number continues to grow.”\n\nThere are a number of explanations for the increase, but <strong>one key reason is that membership in Google+ has real SEO benefits</strong> – <a href=\"http://moz.com/blog/google-plus-correlations\">Cyrus Shepard</a> quotes an in-house study and concluded, “Not only is the correlation for +1s higher than for Facebook activity, but the Google+ platform has qualities that make it a far superior platform for SEO.”\n\n<a href=\"http://moz.com/blog/google-plus-correlations\">Shepard</a> also gives the following as SEO advantages of Google+ - Posts are crawled and indexed almost immediately, Google+ posts pass on link equity, and that Google+ is optimized for semantic relevance.\n\nMany others suspect that merely signing up for Google+ authorship will help search ranking.  And everyone believes that Google Author Rank and Authorship will become larger SEO features into the future.\n\nGoogle also did a major redesign in 2012, created vanity URLs, and started to make Google+ membership a part of the design of many of its features (so that Google products all become linked through Google+).  Google also has really focused on making Google+ more integrated into the rest of social networking – especially across Google’s platforms (like YouTube).\n\nFor all these reasons, numbers are up at Google+ and brands are paying attention, <a href=\"http://hotinsocialmedia.com/2014-social-media-marketing-trends-to-watch-for/\">Florent LeMens</a> notes that, “According to the Content Marketing Institute, B2B marketers are using social media to promote content more frequently than they did in 2012.  Google+ is the social media platform that had the biggest increase in use from last year to this year:  55% of B2B marketers use Google+ to distribute content.”\n\nAnd of course, keeping up with changes is critical to keeping on track and businesses understand this as <a href=\"http://moz.com/blog/future-of-content-upcoming-trends-in-2014\">Stephanie Chang</a> mentioned, “As competition for attention increases, companies will be increasingly willing to experiment with content in new mediums to reach their intended audiences… As marketers, having the ability to quickly adapt and scale to new trends/opportunities is critical.”\n\n<strong>Are you willing to leap? +Post Ads is a good reason</strong>\n\nA key motivation for these posts has been what <a href=\"http://sethgodin.typepad.com/seths_blog/2013/12/heroes-of-the-revolution.html\">Seth Godin</a> said on his blog recently, “Rapid change exposes the work of outsiders, neophytes, and most of all those attracted to the chance to grow fast – Rapid change sweeps aside the status quo and those that defend it (the stuck formal geniuses and the stuck bureaucrats).  It replaces them with those willing to leap.”\n\nThere are some good and interesting reasons to leap in to Google+, for instance, on December 9<sup>th</sup> Google+ unveiled the beta for it’s new ad platform +Post Ads.  <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2013/12/09/google-starts-testing-paid-post-ads-for-google-content-with-launch-partners-toyota-and-cadbury/\">Darrell Etherington</a> did the best job of explaining how this release works, “Brands can take any photo, video, or even Hangout that they create as publicly visible piece of content on Google+, and then pay Google to turn that ad for its network, which is used by over 2 million sites worldwide…Essentially, +Post ads expand to become full-screen lightboxes, which is going to appeal to those looking to do more with design and media in their online advertising.”\n\n<strong>And, +Post ads allow people viewing the ads to interact with them in real-time</strong> according to <a href=\"https://plus.google.com/+eranarkin/posts/al3u1z3a82o#+EranArkin/posts/AL3u1z3A82o\">Eran Arkin</a>, “+Post ads will allow advertisers to start conversations right from the ad – consumers can re-share a video, leave a comment or a question for the brand, or even join a live hangout.  These conversations create a valuable community around a brand where people can talk about each other and with the brand itself.”\n\nOne of the really exciting potential benefits of +Post ads is instead of the customer encountering your brand on a social network when they are thinking about anything other than buying your product - +Post Ads adds social functionality to ads that appear when people are actually searching for products like yours.  You can actually connect to your customers socially when they are looking for your products – as they enter the sales funnel.  The whole web starts to act – and look - like a social network.\n\nRegardless of if you jump in on +Plus Ads, Google + is a must join for businesses (for the SEO benefits alone).  Having a Google+ presence, filling out a profile, linking your business website to Google+, and participating in the authorship rich snippet are critical steps.\n\nIf this post interests you, we would love to hear your thoughts and comments. <strong>Please join in the conversation below.</strong>\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/purplesherbet/10926716484/\">Purple Sherbet Photography</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','2014: Finally, Google+ Really Takes-Off','','publish','open','open','','2014-google-plus-takes-off','','','2014-01-06 16:39:22','2014-01-06 21:39:22','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2560',0,'post','',3);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2576,1,'2014-01-15 08:07:11','2014-01-15 08:07:11','<p dir=\"ltr\">This is the third post in my series of interesting trends that could be huge in marketing for 2014.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Parallax design is a hot trend in the UX and web dev world. Turns out, the interactive Parallax view has been evolving for a lot longer than you’d think.</p>\n\n<h2>What is Parallax Design?</h2>\nWalt Disney distinguished his animation from all other animation of his time period by using side-scrolling techniques. He later used a multi-plane camera that conveyed motion and depth. The introduction of side-scrolling and multi-plane cameras changed how we viewed animation forever. Nearly a century later, we are still continuing the pursuit for even better interactive animation. A relatively new web dev trend, called Parallax design, creates a similar transformation in how we view websites.\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Parallax design layers images and uses motion to draw attention to the most important components of the screen, manipulating the eye to see more two dimensional images.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The<a href=\"http://www.r2integrated.com/blog/index.../parallax-scrolling-seo-debate/\"> R2I blog</a> explains the intricate, infamous scrolling motion of Parallax design stating, “background images move the camera slower than foreground images, creating an illusion of depth in a 2D website.”</p>\n\n<h2>A Richer User Experience</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As of current, it’s one of the most interactive and realistic computer graphics available in web design. Not only is Parallax design cutting-edge, but also it provides a rich user experience—especially in image-heavy sites. According to the Missouri University of Science and Technology, it takes less than 2 tenths of a second for an online user to form an opinion about a brand. This puts pressure on companies, especially in the digital and tech industries, to have a site that is not only relevant to their audience, but provides a digital experience that is unique and visually appealing. Parallax can do wonders for a site in need of graphic interest, energy, or movement. Here are some examples of Parallax design:</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.madwell.com/\">http://www.madwell.com/</a></li>\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.whitehouse.gov/iraq\">http://www.whitehouse.gov/iraq</a></li>\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.dementialab.org/discovery-lab/\">http://www.dementialab.org/discovery-lab/</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">People make decisions very quickly online. Giving a visitor an unexpected experience that redefines how they look at a brand could be priceless. Mark Sherbin of the Content Marketing Institute says the marketing potential for Parallax rests in its “ability to turn static content into interactive experiences” (<a title=\"Content Marketing Institute\" href=\"http://contentmarketinginstitute.com/2013/10/visual-content-potential-pitfalls-parallax-design/\" target=\"_blank\">Content Marketing Institute</a>, 10/7/2013).</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Walt Disney’s “Snow White,” was so successful because it immediately had an immersive effect; it made viewers see the previously flat animated world as a tangible three-dimensional place. The illusion of depth created a closer and more personal experience for the viewers.</p>\nWith Parallax design, you get the same illusion of depth, but also can create a space for interaction with a potential customer. Sherbin continues, “Animations, color, text, and video all interact to give readers a gripping sensation – and help them feel like they are part of the story” (<a title=\"Content Marketing Institute\" href=\"http://contentmarketinginstitute.com/2013/10/visual-content-potential-pitfalls-parallax-design/\" target=\"_blank\">Content Marketing Institute</a>, 10/7/2013).\n<h2>What’s the bad news?</h2>\n<h3>SEO</h3>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Interaction and immersion is great—but what about other important website factors, like SEO? Early Parallax sites tended to compress the entire website design into one very complicated page. This is bad for SEO as it dilutes important keywords and makes linking to other pages difficult. Parallax generally has very little copy included in the design, potentially affecting the SEO’s quality score in alignment with Google’s new algorithm, Hummingbird.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, there are several options to ensure Parallax design doesn’t crush your site’s SEO. According to MMarley.com, Parallax design can be used without funneling all of your site pages into a single folder (<a title=\"Synavista\" href=\"http://www.synavista.com/parallax-scrolling-can-hurt-seo-but-it-doesnt-have-to/\" target=\"_blank\">Synavista</a>, 8/22/2013).</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Other solutions are to have a Parallax home page combined with Parallax independent pages, such as a blog that generates dynamic content (ensuring search engines see that your site is still dynamic). You can also have Parallax elements on an otherwise static site.</p>\n\n<h3>Mobile and Load Times</h3>\nTwo of the most persistent criticisms of Parallax design are that the sites are clunky and slow on mobile devices. Because of the media-rich content in Parallax design, load time will likely increase. “It’s possible to create Parallax sites that are also friendly to mobile devices,” according to <a title=\"Content Marketing Institute\" href=\"http://contentmarketinginstitute.com/2013/10/visual-content-potential-pitfalls-parallax-design/\" target=\"_blank\">Sherbin</a>. One easy solution to a clunky mobile site is a responsive design.\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Responsive design starts with building versions of content that can be viewed on any platform then adding versions that only appear when the correct device is present. By building your site in a responsive manner, you can add graphic features that are visually appealing and functional.</p>\n\n<h2>Willing to Leap into the Future?</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As Seth Godin said, “Rapid change exposes the work of outsiders, neophytes, and most of all those attracted to the chance to grow fast–rapid change sweeps aside the status quo and those that defend it (the stuck formal geniuses and the stuck bureaucrats). It replaces them with those willing to leap.”</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Brands and marketers should certainly think about whether or not they have the kind of products or potential customer base that would be best served by high-end graphics and immersive storytelling. Don’t be replaced by those willing to leap! If you’re looking to make your website more successful for 2014 and beyond, contact us today at hello@ingenexdigital.com or <a title=\"Ingenex Web Development\" href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/services/website-development/\">learn more about the web development services we offer</a>.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Would your company benefit from this 2014 web design trend? Too trendy? Leave your thoughts and comments below!</p>\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/kylesteeddesign/3724074594/\">kylesteed</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/2.0/\">cc</a>','2014: Creating a Parallax View','','publish','open','open','','parallax-web-design','','','2014-01-15 08:07:11','2014-01-15 08:07:11','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2576',0,'post','',4);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2593,1,'2013-12-18 14:32:15','2013-12-18 19:32:15','<p dir=\"ltr\">Facebook Apocalypse?  With some tweaks, and maybe paying a bit more money – you can survive the changes to Facebooks algorithm.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">What is the crisis?</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Recent changes to the algorithm formerly known as “Edgerank’ has many marketers treating Facebook like Scrooge this Christmas.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">While many are still smarting over technical elements of the algorithm update most are furious that Facebook seems to be moving to a ‘pay to play’ model of prioritizing business messages on ‘news feed.’</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As you likely know, the Facebook algorithm determines what pieces of content actually make it from the business to the news feeds of potential customers.  Traditionally, a business could count on around 15% of its followers seeing the content it posted through “Newsfeed.”  After the changes, it seems that 15% is dropping off a proverbial cliff (some say to below 2%).</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">And news feed is critical – as <a href=\"http://searchenginewatch.com/article/2291146/EdgeRank-is-Dead-Long-Live-Facebooks-EdgeRank-Algorithm)./”\">Jessica Lee</a> quoted, “if you’re not successful in the news feed, you’re not going to be successful on Facebook.”</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">So, it’s the apocalypse for organic Facebook efforts.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://searchenginewatch.com/article/2317757/Facebook-Admits-Expect-Organic-Reach-for-Pages-to-Continue-Declining\">Jennifer Slegg</a> puts it bluntly, “Businesses that rely on Facebook for promotion are going to have to pay if they want greater than 1-2 percent “seen” rates on their posts.  It’s also become clear that simply getting people to ‘like’ a business page doesn’t mean the business will have any shot at engaging them in the future, even with great content.  With Facebook admitting they will be delivering fewer and fewer organic liked pages in user newsfeeds, each like becomes less and less valuable…The future of business on Facebook looks grim for those who don’t want to pay to play.”</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is not only speculative gnashing of teeth, <a href=\"http://www.ignitesocialmedia.com/facebook-marketing/facebook-brand-pages-suffer-44-decline-reach-since-december-1/\">Jim Tobin</a> and Ignite Social Media, “reviewed 689 posts across 21 brand pages…and found that, in the week since December 1, organic reach and organic reach percentage have each declined by 44% on average, with some pages seeing declines as high as 88%...a year ago a brand could expect to reach 16 out of 100 fans and now that brand is lucky if they get 3 out of 100.  Chilling news for brand pages who have invested resources to ‘build’ a large following of fans.”</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Has the sky fallen?</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Not everyone thinks the house is burning.  <a href=\"http://www.huffingtonpost.com/sunil-rajaraman/human-search-vs-algorithm-search_b_4428611.html\">Sunil Rajaraman</a> writes about how many companies are forgoing Google entirely to focus on optimizing Facbook sharing.  And <a href=\"http://simplereach.com/blog/facebook-continues-to-be-the-biggest-driver-of-social-traffic/\">Erin Scottberh</a> reports that Facebook still drives, “more traffic than any other social network.”</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.jonloomer.com/2013/12/10/increase-facebook-organic-reach/\">Jon Loomer</a> believes this new algorithmic change can still result in meaningful organic results, “if you listen to those protesting the loudest, you’d think that you can’t reach anyone who cares about your content anymore without paying for ads, while ads should be part of your strategy, this claim simply isn’t true.  Evidence of this was found in my News Feed experiment that showed I saw over 100 organic brand stories in my news feed covering a 24 hour period.”</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Are there viable options for survival?</p>\n\n<ol>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">You can pay to play – while it stinks to have invested in building fans and then be charged for the privilege of reaching them, one option is to pay the price, pony up, and pay the social network.  The odds are it will be expensive and get more expensive…but this is what Facebook is going for.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">You can also try a mix of organic and paid advertising and see if the investment in ads spills-over to organic.</p>\n\n<ol start=\"2\">\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Optimize everything you can</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">So, how can you optimize your organic posts?  Some options include:</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Have great compelling and share-worthy content – this is the inevitable inclusion for every list of suggestions but it’s almost always true.  Of course, this is also one of the real problems businesses face.  As Facebook’s UK creative strategist <a href=\"http://www.marketingweek.co.uk/news/think-of-your-facebook-content-strategy-like-the-tv-series-friends/4008708.article\">Alastair Cotterill</a> said, “Most brands have historically only needed to produce 10 to 12 bits of content a year and now are needing to produce hundreds of different types of content day in day out – as a result, the quality has dropped through the floor.”</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There are many solutions – write more, hire content people, outsource your content creation, optimize your current employees and do content audits and have a content strategy.  In the current web world, content will be a consistent problem searching for a solution.</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Have timely content and post frequently.  There is evidence to suggest that Facebook rewards newsworthy content and people who post frequently…as long as the content is share-worthy.  While this is more easily said then done, it is an important goal.</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Focus on great headline writing.  <a href=\"https://developers.facebook.com/docs/showcase/upworthy/\">Upworthy</a> claims that, “a good headline can be the difference between 1,000 or 1,000,000 people reading or viewing a story.”  They feel it’s a great idea to A/B test multiple headlines for every post you write and apply all the lessons you learn to future posts.</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Use analytics to find out the best times to post and when your most likely fans are most likely to be online</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Know and try to utilize all the new changes in the algorithm.  One of the main changes has been what is called “Story Bump” which allows stories that get more sharing and attention to stay in the news feed longer.  “Last Actor” gives greater weight to people who have been involved with your last 50 Facebook actions.  Finally, “Chronological by Actor” tries to chronologically arrange posts on a subject from a poster – so that the most recent post on a particular subject always gets precedence.  As these features mature, organize your content strategy around them.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Tying it all together</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There is no doubt that Facebook has made it more challenging for businesses to get organic results through “News Feed” but it is still possible to see good results from your organic efforts. The most important thing is not to take your ball and leave Facebook - learn what you can, apply it to the best of your ability, and become a Facebook survivalist.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you want help managing Facebook for your business, contact the social media professionals at <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com\" target=\"_blank\">Ingenex Digital Marketing</a>.</p>\n photo credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/philhearing/5310002921/\">PhotKing ♛</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','Surviving the Facebook Algorithmic-Apocalypse','','publish','open','open','','surviving-facebook-algorithmic-apocalypse','','','2013-12-18 14:32:15','2013-12-18 19:32:15','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2593',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2600,1,'2013-05-20 18:16:08','2013-05-20 22:16:08','In today’s digital age, job seekers and businesses alike are learning to adapt to a changing professional networking environment. Though it may seem unnatural at first to familiarize yourself with the Internet and social media in a professional way, these venues open up doors to connect with people unlike before.\n\n<strong>Professional Networking for Job Seekers</strong>\n\nFrom Facebook to Twitter to LinkedIn, users are changing and developing these social media giants, as well as other sites, to meet their professional networking needs in an evolving business world. With a tight job market and an uncertain outlook for the future, job seekers are becoming more creative with their networking tactics, as well as their resumes.\n\nOne notable site is <a href=\"https://www.vizify.com/about\">Vizify</a>, which essentially creates an infographic out of a person’s resume and online profile. Displayed on a set of eye-catching pages, Vizify generates a profile made up of work history, social profiles, education history, and more. Similarly, a local Ann Arbor startup called <a href=\"http://seelio.com/about-us\">Seelio</a> is a service for students that helps them to showcase their extracurricular activities and experiences through videos, photos, and testimonials. The appeal of these sites are that they make people more than just resumes and businesses, but create them into real human beings who are interested in .\n\n<strong>Professional Networking for Businesses</strong>\n\nBusinesses also need to be able to adapt to the change of marketing and advertising into a digital scene. With standard marketing practices seen as stale and boring, businesses can <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/\">utilize social media</a> sites to their advantage. Businesses are already using social media to connect with jobseekers and clients, while research from trending topics on Twitter can help businesses to forecast for the future.\n\nTo keep businesses from seeming merely “corporate” and to really connect with customers and clients, they have to be savvy with digital tactics. According to a <a href=\"http://www.intuit.com/websites/small-business-social-media-infographic/\">Zoomerang </a>survey of more than 1,000 small businesses, many responded that they used social media to connect with customers, for visibility and self-promotion, and to get news out quickly. Businesses can use the Twitter search function to find and strategically connect with influencers in your market or niche. Followers also want to keep up to date with businesses, so post periodically in order to let clients know what’s going on. Additionally, with Facebook, businesses’ posts and profiles are important for disseminating important information to their clients. By responding to comments, businesses can help increase Likes, engagement and visibility to their customers. The inclusion of Twitter and Facebook accounts in social media marketing campaigns adds an important level of communication between businesses and their clients.\n\nWith the climate of the <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/\">professional networking</a> evolving, it is essential for job seekers and businesses to adapt in order to get the most out of the resources that are out there. As different sites and apps develop, it is pertinent for people to keep up to date. You never know what can help your business, but <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/\">Ingenex Digital Marketing</a> delivers digital marketing solutions for businesses that may be a right fit for your needs.\n\n–<em>By Stephanie Hur</em>\n-<em>Photo by <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/people/21986855@N07/\">greyweed</a></em>','Professional Networking in a Digital Age','','publish','open','open','','professional-networking-digital-age','','','2013-05-20 18:16:08','2013-05-20 22:16:08','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2600',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2604,1,'2013-05-30 18:34:27','2013-05-30 22:34:27','<p dir=\"ltr\">One of the hardest aspects of professional networking, aside from making quality connections, is maintaining relationships with your connections. It might seem simple to stay connected in a <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com\" target=\"_blank\">digital marketing</a> driven society filled with countless social networks – when really the adverse is often true.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Like other job related items, professional social networking requires persistence. Luckily, LinkedIn provides useful <a href=\"www.thedigitalbus.com/linkedin-redesigns-jobs-tool-and-improves-search-and-usability/\" target=\"_blank\">tools for professionals </a>to create online resumés, build and maintain  professional relationships. The following examines five ways to utilize new LinkedIn features to improve and maintain relationships with your professional network.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>1. LinkedIn Today</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The LinkedIn Today news feature allows users to “Follow a Channel” and “Follow Influencers.” This results in a news feed customized to a user\'s interests, industry and people he or she may admire. Sharing relevant information from your industry with your connections can help increase your chances of your connections interacting with you on a professional level on LinkedIn.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/newlinkedinblogpost.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-2606\" alt=\"newlinkedinblogpost\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/newlinkedinblogpost-1024x556.png\" width=\"604\" height=\"327\" /></a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>2. Visual Profile Enhancements</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">LinkedIn now allows you to <a href=\"http://blog.linkedin.com/2013/05/01/visually-enhance-your-professional-story-on-your-linkedin-profile/”\" target=\"_blank\">add visual elements</a> like images, videos and presentations to your profile. So go ahead, show off your skills! Use visual elements as a conversation starter with your connections.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>3. Usability improvements</strong></p>\n<p class=\"alignleft\" dir=\"ltr\">LinkedIn recently announced that its navigation bar would receive a few layout adjustments and upgrades to help you find what and/or who you’re looking for with ease. Essentially you’re presented with information and updates from your network that are most relevant to you. This update is currently being rolled out to users.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>4. LinkedIn Contacts</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This feature takes professional networking to the next level by integrating your address book, email and calendars with your <a href=\"http://www.linkedin.com/company/ingenex-digital-marketing\" target=\"_blank\">LinkedIn</a> network. LinkedIn Contacts make it even easier to maintain meaningful professional relationships by integrating previous interactions with connections and alerting you to events. Contacts is available on LinkedIn.com and with a new iPhone app.</p>\n\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_5848\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"202\"]<a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/phoneimage.png\"><img class=\" wp-image-5848\" alt=\"linkedin iphone app view\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/phoneimage.png\" width=\"202\" height=\"290\" /></a> LinkedIn Contacts iPhone App[/caption]\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>5. Mention</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A simple way to connect with your network or a <a href=\"http://www.thedigitalbus.com/optimize-linkedin-company-page/\" target=\"_blank\">LinkedIn Company Page</a> is to like and share their updates. Try taking it to the next level and use the mention feature. Create updates that mention and are specifically targeted to a connection or company. Mentions help increase engagement by interacting on a more personal level with your connections.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">TIP: To mention simply type name or @ to mention someone or a company.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There isn’t a substitute for face-to-face networking. LinkedIn’s new features can help you capitalize on and build meaningful professional relationships. <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/social-media-marketing\" target=\"_blank\">Social media marketing agencies</a> can help you market yourself online and, use social networks like LinkedIn, to create meaningful relationships. For more information please visit: <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com\">http://ingenexdigital.com</a>.</p>','Five Ways to Improve Professional Networking','','publish','open','open','','five-ways-improve-professional-networking','','','2013-05-30 18:34:27','2013-05-30 22:34:27','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2604',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2610,1,'2014-01-21 22:04:08','2014-01-21 22:04:08','<p dir=\"ltr\">This is the fourth entry in my series of posts about what’s coming in 2014. So far, we have talked about social networks (<a title=\"Snapchat\" href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/2014-snapchat/\" target=\"_blank\">Snapchat</a> and <a title=\"Google+\" href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/2014-google-plus-takes-off/\" target=\"_blank\">Google+</a>) and <a title=\"Parallax design\" href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/parallax-web-design/\" target=\"_blank\">Parallax design</a>, but what about the 2014 consumer trends that impact each of those trends?</p>\n\n<h2>The Mobile Consumer</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">One thing is for certain, customers are becoming more and more mobile. According to <a title=\"socialmediatoday.com\" href=\"http://www.google.com/url?q=http%3A%2F%2Fsocialmediatoday.com%2Fstephen86%2F1946926%2Fwhat-will-be-trending-social-marketing-2014)&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AFQjCNEMqroV-08g1dtXvXuZDVKnEK4VvA\" target=\"_blank\">socialmediatoday.com</a>, “75% of people living on earth have at least one mobile device…and that is going up rapidly.” The sophistication of the devices, larger screen sizes and pervasiveness are changing the way people interact with them.</p>\nIn Tim Kadlec’s book, <a title=\"Implementing Responsive Design\" href=\"http://www.implementingresponsivedesign.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Implementing Responsive Design</a>, he talks about how the mobile user and mobile platforms are maturing, “The traditional view of the mobile user goes something like this: He’s in a hurry and on the go…That’s often not the case anymore. The capabilities of smartphones have improved so much that the browsing experience on a mobile is no longer unbearable…on the right device, the mobile browsing experience is quite enjoyable…what the user wants is not a crippled experience, but the full one.”\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Good point, Mr. Kaldec. We need to design sites and the content on them for the dynamic, mobile user. Instead of designing sites for one experience (like sitting in front of a computer), we need to design for many different scenarios. A user on their phone could want to reach specific content quickly, or perhaps a user is perusing an “About” page. Content and design need to be able provide many unique experiences at all times.</p>\n\n<h2>The New Essential Skill Set</h2>\nThe way we process information and interact with the world is changing in fundamental ways. We’re moving toward being online 24 hours a day, having computer information integrated into every aspect of our lives with screens dividing and layering everything that we see. We’re becoming more collaborative and willing to share information instantly.\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Tom Cheshire of Wired magazine writes about how skills and values are changing, “The essential skills will be those of rapidly searching, browsing, accessing quality, and synthesizing the vast quantities of information. In contrast, the ability to read one thing and then think about it for hours will not be of no consequence, but it will be of far less consequence for most people.”</p>\nRapid attention switching – long considered a symptom of ADD – has become a valuable skill and at some level a normal state of being for most people. From the digital marketing perspective, it’s become a challenge to grab the user’s attention thanks to crowded digital spaces and ever-increasing digital content.\n\nNiraj Dawar, a professor of Marketing, says, “Establishing and nurturing linkages in the marketplace creates stickiness – that is, customers’ unwillingness or inability to switch to a competitor when it offers equivalent or better value.”\n<h2>So What Does This Mean for Marketing?</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To break from the herd, create relationships. Build engagement between your brand and followers. Instead of saying. “LOOK AT MY PRODUCT!” start proving you care about making your customer’s life better.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Present content that works on mobile. Mobile content and design should be quick, digestible and purposeful. It should allow your customer to directly connect with your brand to help create linkage and loyalty in every digital environment.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The motivation for this series of posts was Seth Godin’s comment about being ‘willing to leap’ and sometimes it’s just as important to leap into what is changing with people as the technologies that people use. As technology becomes more advanced, customers are becoming more mature, sophisticated, capable of multitasking, and conflicted about privacy. Thinking about how our messaging works in this world can will make your content more effective in the long run. Understanding your buyer is, after all, the first step in developing <a title=\"Closed Loop Marketing eBook\" href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/closed-loop-marketing\" target=\"_blank\">an effective closed loop marketing strategy</a>.</p>\n<span class=\"hs-cta-wrapper\" id=\"hs-cta-wrapper-ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216\"><span class=\"hs-cta-node hs-cta-ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216\" id=\"hs-cta-ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216\"> <a href=\"http://cta-redirect.hubspot.com/cta/redirect/308833/ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216\"><img class=\"hs-cta-img aligncenter\" id=\"hs-cta-img-ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216\" style=\"border-width: 0px;\" alt=\"\" src=\"https://no-cache.hubspot.com/cta/default/308833/ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216.png\" /></a></span></span> <!-- end HubSpot Call-to-Action Code -->\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If this post interests you, subscribe to our blog so you can get the scoop on all the latest digital marketing trends and standards.</p>','2014: Who Is the Customer Today?','','publish','open','open','','2014-customer-today','','','2014-01-21 22:04:08','2014-01-21 22:04:08','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2610',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2619,1,'2013-01-11 13:08:45','2013-01-11 18:08:45','The Internet is the new schoolyard sandbox. Share your toys, your information, and everything else you can. In 2013,<a href=\"http://www.fastcompany.com/most-innovative-companies/2012/industry/social-media\"> businesses who actively share</a> and engage with their customers will prosper.\n\nMarketing has caught up with the digital revolution. Business can now offer better apps, better content and have the chance to truly give back to their audiences. We now know how important cost, or lack thereof, is to social sharers. People <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/services/social-media-marketing\">share on social media</a> for many reasons - to help, give insight, or offer a laugh. Creating a monetary cost to this information inhibits its sharability. If businesses in 2013 acknowledge this and integrate it into their marketing model as early as possible they will set themselves apart from competitors.\n\nOwnership isn’t what it used to be; sharing is the new standard. In the 1950’s, or heck, the ‘90s, if someone wanted to buy a music album, they went to the store and bought a physical copy of it. They owned it. Now, someone looking for the same album might upload the data from a physical album their friend shared or simply download it. And tada! The consumer feels like they own the music, despite its lack of physicality, because they have access to it at their leisure.\n\nWith information mostly digitized, consumers already have access to data they didn’t purchase (free apps, free books, downloaded music, bit-torrent sharing). Now, not all of these methods are legal, but that doesn’t mean they aren’t happening. The modern zeitgeist involves collaboration, community and sharing. In 2013, companies who truly embrace the digital revolution’s mindset will be embraced by their customers. Even a moderate cost for apps or content is unreasonable for many modern consumers; if they can find it for free, they will. Why not just give it to them? This promotes<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reciprocity_(social_psychology)\"> the goodwill attitude</a> social media is all about.\n\nIf businesses embrace the attitude the social revolution has inspired and give their customers great content, prizes, etc. and reward them freely, modern customers are more likely to become loyal return customers. Once a business creates an attitude about helping their customers in this way, customers are more likely to positively engage back with the brand. So, businesses who choose make better apps and give more away are going to find they like it.\n\nLeading the pack businesses engaging in a new social, giving model of marketing is Amazon. They now offer <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/b/ref=amb_link_1?ie=UTF8&amp;node=5946775011\">free mp3s of Amazon-bought albums</a>. Since their customers are predispositioned to be tech-friendly, they will likely upload the album anyway. Offering a digital copy of music free allows Amazon’s customers instant access to their purchase that will not arrive for about a week. This way, Amazon can still make money and simultaneously eliminate the “instant gratification” hurdle their business inherently faces.\n\nThe consumer digital-social revolution has happened and if the business model adapts, as Amazon’s have, we will see a whole new and more social business model in 2013, one much more inclined to share its toys.\n\nPhoto by <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/cogdog/\" title=\"Cogdog on Flickr\" target=\"_blank\">cogdogblog</a>.','Make Sharing Easy for Success in 2013','','publish','open','open','','make-sharing-easy-success-2013','','','2013-01-11 13:08:45','2013-01-11 18:08:45','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2619',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2624,1,'2014-01-24 12:13:00','2014-01-24 17:13:00','<p dir=\"ltr\">If a picture is worth 1000 words and content is king, we should probably make sure that our websites and blog posts have great images. Unless you’re a professional photographer or have lots of extra time and a great camera you’re going to need to use compelling stock photos. We’re always looking for great stock photo sites, so we did a bit of the leg work for you. Here’s a list of a few great places to get royalty-free stock images for your website and blog posts. I know the word free can be a little scary, as it should be, but using this list and some creative search terms, you can find great images without having to spend a dime.</p>\n\n<h2>Public Domain Images (no copyright)</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In layman’s terms, these images have no copyright and are distributed under the<a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/\" target=\"_blank\"> public domain license</a>. Meaning, you can use the images in any way you see fit. I will warn the less technically savvy: most of the sites listed below have a small section in the search results of images that are actually for purchase on other stock sites. These sections are normally labeled so just be careful and make sure you double-check which images you’re looking at. I’d hate for you to find an image you just can’t live without, only to find out you would have to pay for it.</p>\n <a title=\"Little Visuals\" href=\"http://littlevisuals.co/\" target=\"_blank\">Little Visuals</a>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Little Visuals offers 7 hi-res images every 7 days zipped to your email. They also have archives of past images on the site. This is a fun way to collect some really awesome hi-res stocks for commercial use.</p>\n <a title=\"UnSplash\" href=\"http://unsplash.com/\" target=\"_blank\">UnSplash</a>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">UnSplash has tons amazing hi-res images and uploads 10 more every 10 days. I love looking through the images, the only downside is there isn’t a way to search them.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a title=\"PublicDomainPictures.net\" href=\"http://www.publicdomainpictures.net/\" target=\"_blank\">PublicDomainPictures.net</a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">PublicDomainPicture.net is huge free repository of public domain stock images. At the time of posting this blog post they have over 60,000 free images available on-site.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a title=\"Wikimedia.com\" href=\"http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Images\" target=\"_blank\">Wikimedia.com</a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Wikimedia might seem like an unlikely place to find good stock images but I can assure you there are some hidden gems amongst the pictures of old maps and screenshots.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a title=\"Public-Domain-Photos.com\" href=\"http://www.public-domain-photos.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Public-Domain-Photos.com</a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Public-Domain-Photos.com has 5000 categorized images to search from as well as 8000 clipart images.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a title=\"Stock.XCHNG\" href=\"http://www.sxc.hu/\" target=\"_blank\">Stock.XCHNG</a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">What would a free stock image list be without Stock.XCHNG. It is one of the most well known for a reason. Stock.XCHNG has over 400,000 free stock images. To get the full res images it requires a login but is well worth it. I have been using sxc.hu for sometime now for personal and business use; it’s always one of my go-tos for stock images.</p>\n\n<h2>Attribution Images (must attribute the photographer)</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Images that fall under a<a title=\"Creative Commons license\" href=\"http://creativecommons.org/\" target=\"_blank\"> Creative Commons license</a> are free to use but the end result must credit the owner. This just means you can use these images as long as you provide a link to the original image giving the owner credit. This as easy as adding a small link in the footer of your site or at the end of your blog post, and formatted properly can be unobtrusive to the viewer.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There are six different types of Creative Commons licenses. Half of them allow for commercial use while the other half do not. When using images that are posted under a Creative Commons license it is important that you fully understand which license it uses. Here’s what each of the 6 types of Creative Commons licenses mean for how you can use them:</p>\n\n<h2>Good for Commercial Use</h2>\n<ul>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Attribution: You can remix images and use them commercially, as long as you credit the original. This is the loosest license.</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Attribution-ShareAlike: You can use and adapt images commercially, as long as you give your adapted version the same license and credit the original.</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Attribution-NoDerivs: You can use images for any purpose, as long as it’s unchanged and credited.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Good for Personal Use Only</h2>\n<ul>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Attribution-NonCommercial: You can adapt images, but you must credit them and can’t use them commercially.</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike: You can remix images, but can’t use them commercially and must give the new version the same license as the original.</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivs: You can download and share images but can’t remix them or use them commercially, and you must credit the photographer. This is the most restrictive license.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\nThere are some great sites out there that host images and offer repositories strictly for images under Creative Commons licenses.\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a title=\"Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/search/advanced/\" target=\"_blank\">Flickr</a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Flickr has a great advanced search to find Creative Commons images that you can use for commercial use as long as you show credit. Just make sure you adjust your advanced search to only include images for commercial use. If you don’t want to use Flickr’s advanced search there are some sites that will do some of the heavy lifting for you:</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a title=\"PhotoPin\" href=\"http://photopin.com/\" target=\"_blank\">PhotoPin</a></p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a title=\"FlickrCC\" href=\"http://flickrcc.bluemountains.net/flickrCC/index.php\" target=\"_blank\">FlickrCC</a></p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\"><a title=\"Compfight\" href=\"http://compfight.com\" target=\"_blank\">Compfight</a></li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a title=\"Google Advanced Search\" href=\"http://www.google.com/advanced_search\" target=\"_blank\">Google Advanced Search</a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">You can use Google Advanced Search to find images as well. Just make sure you adjust the usage rights to the correct type you are looking for.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a title=\"CreativeCommons.org\" href=\"http://search.creativecommons.org/\" target=\"_blank\">CreativeCommons.org</a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">CreativeCommons.org now has its own search engine to help you find the images you are looking for. Enter your search term, select the site you want to search and hit the search button.</p>\n\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When designing an optimized webpage it’s important to engage the visitor within the first few seconds they are on the page. One of the easiest way to do this is with eye catching images. With the links I have provided above you should be able to find a stock image that does just that, and the best part is it will cost you nothing. If you feel I missed any or if you have one that you use on a regular basis make sure to leave it in the comments and I’ll gladly add it to the list.</p>\nphoto credit: Ilham Rahmansyah via <a title=\"UnSplash\" href=\"http://unsplash.com/\" target=\"_blank\">UnSplash</a>','Best Stock Image Sites','','publish','open','open','','best-stock-image-sites','','','2014-01-24 12:13:00','2014-01-24 17:13:00','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2624',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2667,1,'2014-01-31 14:54:14','2014-01-31 19:54:14','Every social platform has it’s own unique challenges when it comes to reaching your customers. It all boils down to an over-arching issue most businesses face on social media: the people they want to reach miss their posts. What if happens when your followers’ friends are getting married, their kids get sick, and so on? What if they just happen to have a really busy week?\n\nIf people aren’t using the platform when you send your message (or close to it), they’ll miss it. Creating massive amounts of content on such a short-lived platform can be extremely time consuming. Maybe more time than you have to spare, especially with the chance it may be be missed by your audience.\n\nI’m not saying social isn’t valuable. Each social platform has unique advantages for different situations and add value to your marketing mix if your customers are there. But. <b>If you’re trying to deliver an important message–one you don’t want your customers to miss– you should send an email.</b>\n\nContacts, followers, friends, customers, leads– it all comes down to people. People who want to engage with your brand. With email, people have self-identified that they’d like to learn more about your company, not just followed you on a whim. Email marketing is one of the best ways to communicate with your customers. According to Exact Target, 77% of customers reported that they prefer to receive permission-based marketing communications via email. (via <a title=\"Exact Target Email Marketing Stats\" href=\"http://www.exacttarget.com/email-marketing/best-practices/consumers-prefer-email-marketing\" target=\"_blank\">Exact Target</a>) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?via=ingenex&amp;related=ingenex&amp;source=webclient&amp;text=77+percent+of+customers+prefer+permission-based+marketing+via+email%20http://bit.ly/1fu5yea\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"Tweet This\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/bird_blue_32.png\" width=\"23\" height=\"18\" /></a>\n\n<b>Why, you ask?</b>\n<h3>Personal Messaging</h3>\nEmail allows for more personal communication. It enables you to segment the people interested in your brand. It gives you a chance to speak directly to their interests and send messages tailored to their needs. Email allows you to take advantage of personalization, too, which can work wonders when done properly. You can craft a message that makes the reader feel like you took the time to sit down and write them a note. You begin to develop a relationship and rapport with the person. When was the last time you accomplished that on social media?\n<h3>Ability to Develop Rapport</h3>\nBuilding a relationship is a key aspect of lead nurturing. Some folks might give you their email expecting a sales pitch or specifically to get more information on your product, but not everyone is immediately ready to buy. You need to warm them up. They’ll want to get to know your business a bit before you give them the hard sell. That’s OK, and completely achievable with the right email strategy and proper segmentation.\n<h3>They\'re Highly Interested</h3>\nWhether people contact you and are ready to buy or they’re just curious and need nurturing to develop them to the point of sale, your email list is a group of people who are highly engaged with your product or brand. As a matter of fact, when compared to popular channels like PPC and Banner ads, email marketing has the highest CTR and ROI. (via <a title=\"Search Engine Marketing Email Stats\" href=\"http://www.searchenginepeople.com/blog/10-email-marketing-stats-that-will-blow-you-away.html#ixzz2rzysS3No\" target=\"_blank\">Search Engine People</a>) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?via=ingenex&amp;related=ingenex&amp;source=webclient&amp;text=When+compared+to+popular+channels+like+PPC+and+Banner+ads,+email+marketing+has+the+highest+CTR+and+ROI%20http://bit.ly/1fu5yea\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"Tweet This\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/bird_blue_32.png\" width=\"23\" height=\"18\" /></a>\n<h3>Availability</h3>\nThe best part about email? Your message will be there for them. It’s not going anywhere. Yes; you might have a customer with a cluttered inbox, but your message will still exist it it, waiting for them. It won’t “decay” like social platforms do. And when they do open they email, your personal message will be there. Don’t get me wrong, email marketing has specific challenges too. Writing an email that speaks to people takes a degree of finesse. There are challenges you’ll need to understand and overcome, and best practices to adhere to, but email is an essential aspect of a strong <a title=\"Closed Loop Marketing eBook\" href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/closed-loop-marketing\" target=\"_blank\">inbound marketing campaign</a> once you’ve got it down pat.\n\n<span class=\"hs-cta-wrapper\" id=\"hs-cta-wrapper-ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216\"><span class=\"hs-cta-node hs-cta-ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216\" id=\"hs-cta-ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216\"> <a href=\"http://cta-redirect.hubspot.com/cta/redirect/308833/ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216\"><img class=\"hs-cta-img aligncenter\" id=\"hs-cta-img-ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216\" style=\"border-width: 0px;\" alt=\"\" src=\"https://no-cache.hubspot.com/cta/default/308833/ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216.png\" /></a></span></span> <!-- end HubSpot Call-to-Action Code -->\n\nWhat are your thoughts on email marketing? What are your challenges? What kinds of success have you had? Leave a comment below, I’d love to hear your take.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/jayfresh/3388253576/\">jayfreshuk</a> via photopin <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','Why Your Business Needs to Send Emails','','publish','open','open','','your-business-needs-send-emails','','','2014-01-31 14:54:14','2014-01-31 19:54:14','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2667',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2695,1,'2014-02-05 11:15:54','2014-02-05 16:15:54','After reading an article on <a title=\"Wearable Tech Article - Bill Wasik\" href=\"http://www.wired.com/gadgetlab/2013/12/wearable-computers/\" target=\"_blank\">the future of wearable technology</a> by Bill Wasik, I started thinking about what wearable tech can mean for marketing.\n<p dir=\"ltr\">I know almost every tech magazine and site out there says that digital marketing is changing; I hate to dwell on the subject, but it truly is. Mobile created a whole new landscape for digital strategies (not to mention a whole new set of challenges), but wearable computation has the ability to turn advertising and marketing industry on its head. Wearable tech opens the ability to reach the customer you want at exactly the right moment for purchase.</p>\n\n<h2>Think of Accessibility</h2>\nGoogle engineers have concluded that a blink of an eye is even too long to wait for technology these days. While we love our mobile phones, they require us to fumble, dig, find, press, then swipe (and sometime enter a code) to get them up and working. One study on smartphone users suggests that on average we unlock our gadgets more than 100 times a day. That’s a lot of time spent looking, swiping, and opening a gadget. Queue accessible, wearable tech.\n\nWearables crush smartphones in accessibility. Do you ever notice how your smartphone screen makes simple things like walking, reading, eating, or even just having a conversation with a person difficult? That’s because the screen that pulls us away from whatever we are doing. Wasik notes, “Wearables, by contrast, are a gateway to augmented reality…and keeps our attention grounded in that world.”\n<h2>Consider the Opportunities</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Wearables gel screen with world, replacing the need to glance away. They create an enhanced reality rather than a secondary landscape. This augmented reality presents a whole new challenge to marketers and advertisers. <a href=\"https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?via=ingenex&amp;related=ingenex&amp;source=webclient&amp;text=Augmented+reality+presents+a+whole+new+challenge+to+marketers+and+advertisers%20http://bit.ly/1at2b7s\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"Tweet This\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/bird_blue_32.png\" width=\"23\" height=\"18\" /></a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Imagine as you shop, coupons for products you’re viewing become visible. Imagine the corner of your screen becomes an ever-changing billboard for whatever is nearby.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Search engines like Google, have been investing like crazy in technologies that anticipate what you will search before you actually search. The idea is to use semantic principles of context and geo-location to figure out what you want to know and then provide you the information as you need it. Imagine being able to see endless information about a building or restaurant, simply by walking past it.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Augmented reality and geo-location will create an opportunity for marketers to reach consumers at exactly the time when a purchase is possible—with no distractions. This proposes huge opportunity for marketing; if your content provides the right answers in real time, it creates a more personal relationship between your brand and the person looking for information, who may be a potential customer. A connection like this is exactly what creates long-term customer relationships.</p>\n\n<h2>Imagine the Future</h2>\nIf wearable tech becomes widespread, marketing to consumers has the opportunity to be more personalized than ever before. The gelled and augmented reality along with geo-location presents an exciting and unique opportunity to digital marketers to not just think like the consumer, but as the consumer. Until then, we can only imagine the opportunities.\n\nWhat are your thoughts on wearable technology? Do you think it presents an opportunity for digital marketing? Feel free to leave a comment below.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/thomashawk/9980010036/\">Thomas Hawk</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/2.0/\">cc</a>','An Opportunity in Marketing—Wearable Tech','','publish','open','open','','opportunity-marketing-wearable-tech','','','2014-02-05 11:15:54','2014-02-05 16:15:54','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2695',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2775,1,'2014-02-06 16:59:51','2014-02-06 21:59:51','<p dir=\"ltr\">Let’s talk about snippets. Aside being a fun word to say aloud, snippets are the preview text provided in the Search Engine Results Page (SERP). Typically, a snippet is constructed with title, url and brief description of the page.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The snippet space and the text within is a direct representation of your company, site, site page, or blog post. Remember, with SERPs you\'re fighting a battle to both appear on the page and to win the page when you appear. A snippet should be constructed in a manner to attract a searcher and entice them to click your content.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Snippet Space is free SEO real estate, and you want to dominate this tiny web space. So, how can you dominate SERP snippet space?</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Fortunately, there are guidelines you can follow to create a search result that is not only SEO-friendly, but understandable, eye-catching and relevant to the user’s search. Listed below are our 4 tips to create better snippets, which in turn, will help you increase your click through rate on SERPs. <a href=\"https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?via=ingenex&amp;related=ingenex&amp;source=webclient&amp;text=Our+4+tips+to+create+better+snippets,+which+in+turn,+will+help+you+increase+your+CTR+on+SERPs%20http://bit.ly/1l82h5U\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"Tweet This\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/bird_blue_32.png\" width=\"23\" height=\"18\" />\n</a></p>\n\n<h2>1. Add Meta Title Tags</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The most important part of your markup, and something people often forget to fill out, is the meta title tag. Meta title tags are the title of the page and snippet (it shows up in search results in blue). Title tags also appear in browser tabs, browser bookmarks and social links on many networks.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As the first text the user will read on the search page, the meta title tags give you the opportunity to write something more enticing than the title tags of your competitors and be more relevant or interesting to the searcher.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">“A title tag is the most important single tag in your page. It tells the search engines what your page is about.  It is still vitally important to your SEO Strategy,” according to <a title=\"an article from searchenginewatch.com\" href=\"http://searchenginewatch.com/article/2154469/How-to-Write-Title-Tags-For-Search-Engine-Optimization\" target=\"_blank\">searchenginewatch.com</a>.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There is an SEO helper or plug-in available on most blogging platforms to help you with markup. Different CMS platforms and document templates have different ways to enter or modify your title tags, and if you have the ability you can always do this manually in the code of the page.</p>\n\n<h2>2. Add Meta Description Tags</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The meta description tag is a critical area for dominating snippet space. As <a title=\"Google Snippets Team\" href=\"http://googlewebmastercentral.blogspot.com/2007/09/improve-snippets-with-meta-description.html\" target=\"_blank\">Raj Krishnan of the Google Snippets Team</a> says, “The quality of your snippet…can have a direct impact on the chances of your site being clicked on. We use a number of strategies for selecting snippets, and you can control one of them by writing an informative meta description for each URL.”</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Where the meta title tag is restricted to 70 characters, the meta description tag is a bit more spacious, giving you the opportunity to attractively package what a searcher will find when they click on your link.</p>\nMeta description tags are instrumental in increasing click thru rate (CTR) from the search result to your website. Where the title is shorter and can’t be as detailed, the meta description provides a bit more context for the searcher to see what information they will get on the page.”\n<h2>3. Join Google+</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There is significant data showing <a title=\"Google+ SERP research\" href=\"http://www.jeffalytics.com/google-plus-search-authorship/\" target=\"_blank\">Google+ accounts positively affect SERP rankings</a>. A recent article on <a href=\"http://socialmediatoday.com/steve-rayson/1796646/10-ways-googles-hummingbird-will-shape-future-seo-and-content-marketing\" target=\"_blank\">socialmediatoday.com</a> referenced Google+ has the “social spine” of search, warning users if you \"do not have a Google Plus profile or page or you are not active on the platform…now is the time to get going.”</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">You might be wondering how Google+ wound up being regarded as the virtual backbone of search. Great question. It’s because Google+ is more than a social network. In the last year, Google has organized its search algorithms with the social network in mind– Google+ is factored in to search results to a degree.</p>\nSo, what does this have to do with snippets? Another great question. Think of Google+ as a prerequisite. Google+ is the beginning to establishing authorship in search, which can add credibility to a result and even enhance a listing with the use of a rich snippet.\n<h2>4. Sign up for Google Authorship</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The second important step in using Google+ to your SEO advantage is to apply for authorship. Google wants to make sure it\'s rewarding authors who are real people, with real expertise and a track record in writing honest, satisfying content.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://oursocialtimes.com/the-future-of-online-marketing-in-one-word-authority/\">Google rewards authors</a> that are reputable and have claimed authorship as an effort to provide quality results to searchers. If you\'re approved for authorship and add a bit of code to your site (like the title and description tags) your listing has the potential to appear with your Google+ picture next to it.  The photo adds credibility to your link, making users more likely to select your listing compared to others.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There are many types of rich snippets, like ones used for e-commerce pricings, quantity, availability, and other consumer-friendly details. Each provides a unique advantage to the results that appear on a SERP.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 30px; line-height: 1.3; color: #141412;\">Tying It All Together</span></strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The whole purpose of SEO is to get people to your site. Snippet space is a critical part of winning click-through traffic from search space to your website.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Writing great content that no one can find, or appearing in search results without achieving the click-through rate you need are the nightmare scenarios. You can avoid by actively managing SEO on your site and doing everything you can to increase the click through rate on your results. To get the specifics on how you can master SEO for your business and the details on how to set up tags, <a title=\"Overcoming Your SEO Challenges\" href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/overcoming-your-seo-challenges\" target=\"_blank\">download Overcoming Your SEO Challenges</a>.<span class=\"hs-cta-wrapper\" id=\"hs-cta-wrapper-54ec7dd0-6466-4e7a-88a6-403f4b9bbf18\"><span class=\"hs-cta-node hs-cta-54ec7dd0-6466-4e7a-88a6-403f4b9bbf18\" id=\"hs-cta-54ec7dd0-6466-4e7a-88a6-403f4b9bbf18\">\n<!--[if lte IE 8]></span></span></p>\n\n<div id=\"hs-cta-ie-element\"></div>\n< ![endif]-->\n<a href=\"http://cta-redirect.hubspot.com/cta/redirect/308833/54ec7dd0-6466-4e7a-88a6-403f4b9bbf18\"><img class=\"hs-cta-img aligncenter\" id=\"hs-cta-img-54ec7dd0-6466-4e7a-88a6-403f4b9bbf18\" style=\"border-width: 0px;\" alt=\"\" src=\"https://no-cache.hubspot.com/cta/default/308833/54ec7dd0-6466-4e7a-88a6-403f4b9bbf18.png\" width=\"470\" height=\"217\" /></a>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">photo credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/stuckincustoms/6756753669/\">Stuck in Customs</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.0/\">cc</a></p>','4 Ways to Win Snippet Space in Search','','publish','open','open','','4-ways-win-snippet-space-search','','','2014-02-06 16:59:51','2014-02-06 21:59:51','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2775',0,'post','',1);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2824,1,'2014-02-14 16:22:39','2014-02-14 21:22:39','<h2>Kill or Keep Sentiment Analysis?</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sentiment analysis, or opinion mining, is an interesting tactic in digital marketing. I say “interesting” because sentiment analysis is proving to be a hot bed for discussion among marketers and analysts alike. On one side of the spectrum, marketers are dismantling sentiment analysis’s worth, calling for more quantitative data (tracking and coding) rather than qualitative data. This article takes a look at what sentiment analysis is, the positives and negatives to using this tactic, and how your business can find your sentiment analysis happy place.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Even a <a href=\"http://hbr.org/2014/01/what-marketers-misunderstand-about-online-reviews/ar/1\">Harvard Marketing professor</a> is refuting the value of sentiment analysis, specifically stating, “Instead of measuring individual consumers’ preferences, satisfaction, and loyalty, marketers should redirect resources to the systematic tracking, coding, and quantifying of information from review sites, user forums, and other social media.”</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">On the flip side, advertisers and more content-friendly marketers are advocating for the value that sentiment analysis brings to the table. Their argument states that sentiment analysis provides marketers the opportunity to listen (in real-time) to customer feedback, identify trends in customer base, and fix problems with customers.</p>\n\n<h2>Both Sides of the Spectrum</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">So, what exactly is sentiment analysis and where do we (Ingenex Digital Marketing) stand? To answer the latter, we’ll need to explore the former first.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sentiment analysis is a super cool <a title=\"Natural Language processing\" href=\"http://http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_language_processing\" target=\"_blank\">Natural Language processing</a> computation that combines with analytics to gauge how a customer feels about a product or brand. In other words, it’s analyzing not how many “Likes” a Facebook page has, but the comments and dialogue people are producing anywhere in Facebook. I should note, sentiment analysis is not localized to only Facebook, but to all social media.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Within the programming, content is given a score based on the way the words relate to content. So, sentiment analysis takes a specific word (like your brand name), scans social media for that word, then rates the tweet, post, or comment’s content as positive, negative, or neutral.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sounds great, huh? It is! But, then it also isn’t. You see, sentiment analysis will always have a degree of ambiguity. As amazing as the programming is, a computer will never be able to pick up on human sarcasm, innuendos, or humor. Because after all, language is deeply rooted in culture.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">At least for the time being, sentiment analysis requires human input. Since language is so subjective to it’s cultural surroundings, an employee will have to monitor and make judgment calls on the program\'s assessment of positive or negative sentiment. And as we all know, an employee (or staff if the brand is large enough) costs considerable time and money. And that’s a large negative.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Despite the cost, we have found sentiment analysis does provide us with opportunities to listen to customers—in real time. The “real time” aspect is important to us because it allows us to quickly identify trends with our customers and identify problems or dissatisfaction. This knowledge lets us improve our customer relations, understanding and overall strategy. <a href=\"https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?via=ingenex&amp;related=ingenex&amp;source=webclient&amp;text=Sentiment+analysis+improves+customer+relations+scope+and+overall+strategy%20http://bit.ly/NLDauF\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"Tweet This\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/bird_blue_32.png\" width=\"23\" height=\"18\" /></a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">So, to answer the question above, yes, we do conduct sentiment analysis. However, it serves as a meaningful <em>part</em> to our overall content strategy, not our main focus.</p>\n\n<h2>But Is It for You?</h2>\nSentiment analysis isn’t for every agency or brand. Smaller companies may not benefit from it like a large global brand would. However, it’s important to not discredit sentiment analysis as a valuable tactic. I don’t think it’s wise of the Harvard professor to completely dismantle this monitoring tool, as for some companies it’s an invaluable tool that allows them to better engage with their customers.\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It\'s all about finding your digital strategy, or for that matter, your sentiment analysis happy place. At the end of the day, it’s about engaging with your customers. Sentiment analysis may not be for everyone, but if it helps you build a better connection, it might be worth making it apart of your strategy.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">What do you think? Do you think semantic analysis is a valuable monitoring tool?</p>\n If you want to <a title=\"Brand Monitoring\" href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/services/brand-monitoring/\">learn more about brand monitoring and sentiment analysis</a>, give us a call.','Finding Your Sentiment Analysis Happy Place','','publish','open','open','','finding-sentiment-analysis-happy-place','','','2014-02-14 16:22:39','2014-02-14 21:22:39','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2824',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2853,1,'2014-02-21 09:30:21','2014-02-21 14:30:21','<p dir=\"ltr\">There seems to be a new type of humor sweeping the digital marketing landscape. For the second time in a month, mainstream companies have taken to using intentionally incorrect content to stir interest from the public and media. From JC Penney’s Superbowl ‘drunk tweeting’ to Groupon’s President\'s Day misnomer campaign, intentional content mistakes are popping up all over. The fact that this type of humor is being used by large, well-known companies begs us to ask, is this good way to draw attention to a brand?</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">From a digital marketer and business owner’s perspective, I’m not sure it’s the best way to build and engage an audience. If an advertising campaign jeopardizes the credibility of the organization, I don’t think it’s worth it. And when I say credibility, I am referring to more than just the customer’s trust in the company; I am referring to a company’s products, customer service, moral values and long-term goals. It’s important to look at credibility as a large range of elements that work together to make up the company.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Let’s take a look at two of the latest instances of companies using this type of humor in a marketing strategy.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Both companies, JC Penney and Groupon used incorrect content in a humorous way to create buzz about their brand. Let’s compare and contrast how each company used humor.</p>\n\n<h2>#tweetingwithmittens</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">JC Penney took to Twitter with a pair of mittens during the 2014 Superbowl, creating tweets with less than perfect grammar and spelling. See JC Penney tweet below.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" alt=\"\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/cfE_ijLXwpS_ZtI2Or6UelAdJDuSWqE5EGbrkUYBYpbK-sytIMu-Hay2XZkQNgW_m69BPdIlGEsn3NG3qfNwdqqPH-Ng47VrlqB0U6omJG3kPLK0TCDCxkE3ZQ\" width=\"624px;\" height=\"177px;\" /></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Notice almost every word is spelled incorrectly, as well as the amount of attention it received on Twitter. The response from Tweeters was less than positive, one tweeter responded by saying “Go home @jcpenney, you’re drunk.” Even Kia Motors of North America responded asking, “Hey @jcpenney need a designated driver?” Responses from across the internet ranged from drunk tweeting to thinking the company was hacked. That night, JC Penney explained their poor grammar with a picture and the hashtag #tweetingwithmittens.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Eventually,  JC Penney spokeswoman Kate Coultas replied saying they wanted “create our own narrative” among TV ads and social media. And they certainly did. The stats on JC Penney\'s Superbowl stunt: “We gained over 10,000 followers last night, received over 40,000 @jcpenney mentions and 1,800 mentions of our hashtag #tweetingwithmittens.”</p>\nNo doubt the #tweetingwithmittens campaign created buzz for JC Penney, but is it the kind of buzz the company overall wants or even needs?\n\nDrunk tweeting (always a no-no) or a hacked account are both \'bad.\' Not the kind of exposure you\'re looking for as a brand. I think what was <em>so</em> off-putting about JC Penney’s Super Bowl tweets was that their specific type of humor used wasn’t inline with their overall image.\n<h2>President Alexander Hamilton…?</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Groupon launched a campaign over President’s Day weekend, giving customers $10 off any $40 purchase from a local business. Groupon’s <a href=\"https://www.groupon.com/press%20\" target=\"_blank\">official website</a> said they launched this campaign in honor of President Alexander Hamilton, the face of the $10 dollar bill, and “undeniably one of our greatest presidents and most widely recognized for establishing the country\'s financial system.”</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Only problem is that Hamilton was never the President of the United States.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Needless to say, many people took to Twitter to correct Groupon’s misnomer, while also calling the company “idiots” and “idiotic.”</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A Groupon spokesperson responded saying their President’s Day promotion was intentional and made to be “different that was in line with our brand and sense of humor,” according to the <a href=\"http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/breaking/chi-groupon-honors-alexander-hamilton-on-presidents-day-20140217,0,1239710.story\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Chicago Tribune</em> article</a> (reported earlier by <em>Mashable</em>).</p>\nThe spokesperson also noted that many of their quick customer’s appreciated the President’s Day gaffe, adding that the campaign did exactly what they intended.\n<h2>Is This Type of Humor Worth the Laugh?</h2>\nThere is no doubt humor in a marketing strategy is good. It injects a much-needed energy and a human element into a digital space. It creates for memorable and sharable fun. Humor is one of the easiest ways to get people talking and engaged in your brand. It’s also one of the easiest ways to make content go viral.\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, using humor in a marketing strategy is delicate thing; it will only work if your audience understands and appreciates the kind of humor intended. Brands like Volkswagen, Taco Bell and Old Spice do this exceptionally well. Without this consideration, the joke can get lost in translation. We see this happen in the JC Penney #tweetingwithmittens campaign.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Those tweets were a departure from their other advertising and marketing materials, and they didn’t meet their audience’s expectations of their brand.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This brings up the need for consistency in any marketing strategy. It’s imperative that the voice and tone of your content remain consistent throughout all marketing mediums <a href=\"https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?via=ingenex&amp;related=ingenex&amp;source=webclient&amp;text=It\'s+imperative+voice+of+content+remain+consistent+in+all+marketing+mediums%20http://http://bit.ly/MEwvl3\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"Tweet This\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/bird_blue_32.png\" width=\"23\" height=\"18\" /></a>. Any deviation from the norm can lead to customer confusion, dissatisfaction and a hit to your credibility.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Groupon customers may have been less confused by the intentional presidential misnomer, especially if users are familiar with Groupon’s social media presence. Groupon has a relatively laid-back, quirky voice throughout social media. They’ve even taken to retweeting the fake (and silly) Twitter account of President Hamilton, or @PrezHamilton, adding another humorous layer in the President’s Day campaign. Notice the silly @PrezHamilton retweet below:</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" alt=\"\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/BE4-WM6dIwxdnm_dW-SHNHCVxpi8k1tReSXOwbQdFXLmkqihkEByaR8Ai886Bmn22T816u3t5x-NprXC2T5XBiv5D7SB1BjEenlWZiqdzUBcB_rYERbFzaKp6w\" width=\"624px;\" height=\"213px;\" /></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Was Groupon’s attempt at humor successful? That’s hard to say. There was some resistance to the joke and a potential loss of credibility with customers. This joke, too, could be lost in translation by some.  However, it did seemed much quieter than JC Penney’s humorous attempt. For one, this type of humor is consistent with the Groupon brand. From their digital presence to the language on their mobile and website applications, the overall tone of the campaign quasi remained inline with their other marketing materials and social media presence. I should note that I\'m not condoning their campaign, I’m just pointing out the importance of consistency.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Like I said before, humor can be a great way to engage with your customers, but it is a tricky thing to do correctly. It requires timing, consistency and a deep understanding of your audience. It\'s important to understand that not every brand needs to create silly content just for the sake of being funny.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Err on the side of caution. If a tweet or email seems funny to you but may not sit well with a portion of your customer base, it’s always better to leave it out.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The most important thing you can do is find the voice that resonates with your audience. Once you do, keep it consistent throughout all your marketing channels. This will help you create that well-rounded, credible brand your customers can trust.</p>\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/31878512@N06/4704140020/\">Neal.</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','Humor in a Marketing Strategy','','publish','open','open','','humor-content-strategy','','','2014-02-21 09:30:21','2014-02-21 14:30:21','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2853',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2886,1,'2014-02-27 06:01:44','2014-02-27 11:01:44','<p dir=\"ltr\">In the <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/humor-content-strategy/\">last blog post</a>, I wrote about how companies are using humorous campaigns to create a buzz about about their brand. As I mentioned, it’s not a great idea to launch a campaign for the sake of exposure, especially if the content isn’t consistent with current and past content.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">I\'d like to discuss the importance of having a consistent brand voice. Consistency is a word we talk about a lot in the digital marketing industry, particularly with brands and content marketing. In those areas, consistency refers to the overall voice of a brand.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Voice refers to the tone, grammar and appearance of the content—so, if you’re attempting to build a brand that engages with a targeted audience, you’ll need to find a voice that is consistent in these areas to do so successfully.</p>\n\n<h2>Tone</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Adria Saracino, Lead Content Strategist at Distilled, “Tone is not what you say, but <a href=\"https://www.distilled.net/blog/are-you-being-heard-find-your-brands-voice-this-weeks-distilledlive-video/%20\">how you say it</a>.” Establishing your brand’s tone is an integral part to building a marketing presence. It allows you to differentiate yourself from competitors and put your own unique stamp on your product or service. For example, if you’d like your brand to come off as friendly and quirky, you might elect to use words like “groovy” or “awesome” in short, conversational sentences.</p>\nBut before choosing a tone for your brand, always think about your audience—always<strong>.</strong> <strong>Finding your brand’s tone shouldn’t be about what you want, but what your audience expects.</strong>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Your audience is your customer. So be sure to think like your customer. Ask yourself, “What are my customer’s expectations for my service?” “What kind of relationship do they want to have with my product?” Once you’ve identified their expectations, choose a tone that fits those expectations.</p>\n\n<h2>Grammar</h2>\nI hate to sound like your third grade teacher, but I cannot stress enough the importance of correct spelling and punctuation. Correct grammar is essential for establishing brand credibility. Not every sentence has to be comprised of traditional syntax (as you can see, we don’t always follow that format either), but there is no room for careless errors in content.\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Nothing discredits a brand like glaring spelling mistakes. Content that consistently has correct spelling and grammar shows customers that the brand has 1) attention to detail and 2) investment in the brand. It’s also one of the easiest ways to establish authority.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">So don’t forget to dot your i’s, cross your t’s and know when to use \"you\'re\" instead of \"your.\" Every bit counts.</p>\n\n<h2>Appearance</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">From packaging to social media, the appearance of the brand should remain consistent throughout all channels. Keep in mind the tone you chose to represent your brand.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Let’s use the quirky, friendly tone we talked about above. It would make sense to choose a design scheme that fits that quirky, fun persona. Colors that are bright, unexpected, and accompanied by script or serif fonts would align well with our chosen tone.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Typography, colors and layout add another powerful layer to your brand’s overall voice. Keep appearances of web and print content inline with tone.</p>\n\n<h2>How to Keep your Voice Consistent</h2>\n<ul>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Establish Governance: If the brand’s voice is dependent on a large team or even just a couple of individuals, it’s important to set up some guidelines for how key decisions about the content will be made. Establishing governance is as simple as creating a document that quickly outlines individual responsibilities and expectations. Governance will ensure the content’s voice is consistent, understood, and carried out correctly in all areas involved.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Follow a Schedule: A schedule sets the foundation for consistency. A schedule will not only make the content creator’s life easier, but it will also satisfy your audience’s expectations of when and where content will be created by your brand.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Adjust as Needed: This may seem like a stark contradiction from consistency, but it’s important to remember that content is never static because your customers are never static. As your customer’s language changes, so should yours. For example, if an important term in your audience\'s lexicon is replaced, be sure to make the switch, too. Change with your audience’s expectations. <strong>Remain consistent by remaining current.</strong></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you think about the most recognizable brands today, you’ll notice they have a powerful, distinctive voice. Their voice separates them from competitors and allows them to engage with their customers. Their success isn’t dumb luck; successful brand voices derive from careful research and consideration of audience expectations.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">From there, a brand’s voice connects with customers because of consistency in simple things like tone, grammar and appearance. Finding and maintaining your brand’s voice doesn’t have to be difficult—it just has to be consistent with your customer\'s expectations and effectively executed across your media channels.</p>\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/howardlake/5540462170/\">HowardLake</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.0/\">cc</a>','Finding and Maintaining a Brand\'s Voice','','publish','open','open','','importance-consistent-brand-voice','','','2014-02-27 06:01:44','2014-02-27 11:01:44','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2886',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2906,1,'2014-03-05 14:24:07','2014-03-05 19:24:07','In a world where endless amounts of content and information are available at any moment, it\'s easy to get lost in the content marketing race. Every person and every company is pushing content—but that doesn’t mean all content is created equal. Not all content is necessarily valuable or even relevant to its target community.\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The point of creating great content for your customers, industry and community is to promote thought, conversation and engagement, and I think we forget that far too often. Here are 4 guidelines you can use to create more engaging content.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>1. Check current content.</strong> Easier said than done, I’ll admit. This step takes a lot of research and understanding of your customers. However, it’s the most valuable step you can take before creating any new content.</p>\nA good starting point is to look at the last 2 months of content you’ve created, but be careful to not overwhelm yourself. Look at specific analytics of your site, such as <a href=\"http://www.forbes.com/sites/johnrampton/2014/03/04/5-things-to-keep-your-content-marketing-efforts-in-check/\" target=\"_blank\">exit pages</a> and <a href=\"http://www.forbes.com/sites/johnrampton/2014/03/04/5-things-to-keep-your-content-marketing-efforts-in-check/\" target=\"_blank\">average time spent on a page</a> to better understand a user’s behavior. You’ll be able to make better future content knowing how your customers interact with current content.\n\n<strong>2. Whittle down media.</strong> When it comes to content syndication, quality trumps quantity. If you’re currently posting content across 6 social media channels, but you only see quality engagement in 3, it might be a good idea to cut your losses and invest in the channels that already show interest and following. Downsizing will give you more time to analyze current content, find customer insights, nurture leads and expand your customer base in an already invested community.\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>3. Variety is the spice of life.</strong> Keep your content interesting and fresh by using different ways to show data and info. For example, a simple infographic may help illustrate a technical subject better than a lengthy report.</p>\nDocumenting industry-related events that you or your company attends through Twitter or Instagram is an easy way draw interest. Accompany the image with a blog post detailing your experience, what you learned, etc.\n\n<strong>4.</strong> <strong>Stop looking to “<a href=\"http://www.forbes.com/sites/gregsatell/2014/02/22/how-to-do-content-marketing-right/\" target=\"_blank\">grab</a>” attention, start looking to “<a href=\"http://www.forbes.com/sites/gregsatell/2014/02/22/how-to-do-content-marketing-right/\" target=\"_blank\">hold</a>” attention.</strong> Catchy headlines are important. However, to better engage with customers, you don’t want to be a one-stop-shop for information. Be a resource in your industry. Be a resource your customers will want to come back to.\n\nWe\'d love to hear what you think. What guidelines do you use create engagement?\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/marcwathieu/2980385784/\">Marc Wathieu</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/2.0/\">cc</a>','4 Guidelines to Create Engaging Content','','publish','open','open','','4-guidelines-create-engaging-content','','','2014-03-05 14:24:07','2014-03-05 19:24:07','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2906',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2917,1,'2014-03-11 16:21:23','2014-03-11 20:21:23','<p dir=\"ltr\">Every digital marketer knows the importance of a quality landing page. After all, landing pages aide in converting a higher percentage of your visitors into leads. All good landing pages contain the appropriate brevity, simplicity, trackability, social shareability and a thank you page.</p>\nWhile landing pages are the bread and butter of lead conversion, the thank you page is a vital piece to a successful landing page campaign, as well as a vital place to nurture and convert leads in general. We’re here to tell you that your thank you page shouldn’t be an afterthought. Here’s why and how you can turn yours into lean, mean lead-converting machines.\n<h2>The Thank You Page</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The thank you page is the immediate feedback after a customer has completed siging up or filling out the landing page. First and foremost, make sure to say clearly “thank you!” somewhere on the page.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The thank you page should provide immediate feedback that reassures your customer that any further action (forms) are not required. The last you want your customer to do is worry that they didn’t fill out the form completely.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you’re offering a download of a whitepaper or video, give customers clear access to download or view the offered content. Always try to have the downloaded content open in a new tab.If a consultation is involved, reassure customers they will be receiving a call or email shortly. Thank you pages allow you to neatly tie up any loose ends by fulfilling customers expectations.</p>\n\n<h2>Include Social Sharing</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Your customer has actually downloaded your content! Awesome. Our work here is done, right? Not so fast. If a customer downloaded or signed up for something, the customer must find it interesting or useful.  What might be interesting or useful to them, might be interesting or useful to their friends, community and professionals in their industry.</p>\nFor example, if a parent downloads a free workbook that helps their child’s math skills, the parent might want to share with other parents they know. Just like the landing page, make the thank you page social.  This is where having the downloaded content open in a separate tab comes in handy. Keeping the thank you page with share buttons and downloading content in separate tabs increases the likelihood of a person willing to share. That way, customers won’t have to navigate from thank you page to downloaded content then back to thank you page to share.\n<p dir=\"ltr\">One great little tip for social sharing is to customize the “Tweet This” message. Customizing the message can ensure the tweet from customer is not just a share, but a recommendation.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Make sure that your share buttons link to your landing page, not your thank-you page–otherwise your viewers will have access to your content without filling out your form and you’ll be missing out on valuable lead generation.</p>\n\n<h2>Include a CTA</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Adding a call-to-action (CTA) to a thank you page is a necessary step to nurture leads. Unlike the landing page, you should enable your site’s navigation. This encourages customers to explore your site and learn more about your company. Based on the content your customer downloaded, you can also introduce relevant articles or material they might find useful.</p>\nCTA copy and graphic should be direct, friendly and brief. Successful CTA buttons use strong phrases with action verbs like “subscribe” or “connect” to clearly communicate the desired action.  For example, CTA’s like “Connect with on Facebook” or “Subscribe to our blog” work well.\n<p dir=\"ltr\">So, there you have it. Don’t let the thank you page become an afterthought. Use it with landing pages as an easy and simple way to grow and nurture leads.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For more help on constructing thank you and landing pages, <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/optimizing-landing-pages\" target=\"_blank\">download our landing page guide, Optimizing Landing Pages</a>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"hs-cta-wrapper\" id=\"hs-cta-wrapper-92d07c9f-ee70-4b86-8429-4d6c1621ad46\"><span class=\"hs-cta-node hs-cta-92d07c9f-ee70-4b86-8429-4d6c1621ad46\" id=\"hs-cta-92d07c9f-ee70-4b86-8429-4d6c1621ad46\"> <a href=\"http://cta-redirect.hubspot.com/cta/redirect/308833/92d07c9f-ee70-4b86-8429-4d6c1621ad46\"><img class=\"hs-cta-img aligncenter\" id=\"hs-cta-img-92d07c9f-ee70-4b86-8429-4d6c1621ad46\" style=\"border-width: 0px;\" alt=\"Optimizing Landing Pages button\" src=\"https://no-cache.hubspot.com/cta/default/308833/92d07c9f-ee70-4b86-8429-4d6c1621ad46.png\" width=\"500\" height=\"280\" /></a></span></span> <!-- end HubSpot Call-to-Action Code --></p>\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/theilluminated/5386099858/\">Jon Ashcroft</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','Thank You Pages are Not Afterthoughts','','publish','open','open','','thank-pages-afterthoughts','','','2014-03-11 16:21:23','2014-03-11 20:21:23','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2917',0,'post','',2);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2940,1,'2014-03-14 12:31:33','2014-03-14 16:31:33','You know the saying, “timing is everything.” It still applies to the realm of inbound marketing, especially when referring to landing pages. In the <a href=\"http://bit.ly/OlPUYl\" target=\"_blank\">last post</a>, I talked about the thank you page as a legitimate place for lead generation, and I didn’t pay much attention landing pages.\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In this post, I\'m giving homage to the landing page, particularly to the importance of timing. Timing, in this case, affects the number of leads which affects the number of sales. If you have your landing page timing down, you’re more likely to secure leads.</p>\n\n<h2>Landing Page Basics</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Let’s briefly examine what a landing page is and what it does. The physical landing page is the exact page with the offer and the form customers must complete to get it the offered content. Without a specific form or information field, it\'s not a landing page.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Landing pages allow site visitors to download offers or sign up for things like free trials and demos. Other content like white papers, ebooks and technical reports are also offered through landing pages.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to copyblogger.com, the goal of the “copy and design of a landing page is to <a href=\"http://www.copyblogger.com/landing-pages/\" target=\"_blank\">get the prospect to take your desired action</a>.” Designing a landing page that\'s tailored to your audience and offer is imperative to its overall success. No landing page should be exactly the same, since very little campaigns and offers are exactly the same.</p>\n\n<h2>Landing Page Timing</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It\'s important to note when I refer to timing, I\'m referring to the follow-up message sent after the customer has filled the landing page form. For example, let’s say you created a brilliantly tailored landing page perfectly fitted for your target audience. A customer then fills out the form. Is the landing page process over? Not yet.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Aside from <a href=\"http://bit.ly/OlPUYl\" target=\"_blank\">building a brilliantly optimized thank you page</a>, establishing contact with the customer is the next vital step to nurturing the lead. Here\'s why:</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>78% of sales that start with a web inquiry get won by the first company that responds.</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If that stat doesn\'t encourage a follow-up message to your customer, I\'m not sure what does. As the age of a lead increases, the chances of a customer responding decreases. You can see why timing is so important when securing a lead.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For the follow-up, we suggest a short, friendly email message. The message should be appropriate to the campaign and the customer’s interests and needs. It’s also good practice to include a CTA that suggests relevant material and/or product exploration. Be swift in time and direct in content.</p>\n\n<h2>Lead Nurturing</h2>\nLead nurturing can’t happen without good timing. Establishing quick contact with customers not only helps build a rapport, but is statistically proven to generate leads.\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you’d like to learn how to build more effective landing pages, check out our guide <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/optimizing-landing-pages\" target=\"_blank\">Optimizing Landing Pages</a>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"hs-cta-wrapper\" id=\"hs-cta-wrapper-92d07c9f-ee70-4b86-8429-4d6c1621ad46\"><span class=\"hs-cta-node hs-cta-92d07c9f-ee70-4b86-8429-4d6c1621ad46\" id=\"hs-cta-92d07c9f-ee70-4b86-8429-4d6c1621ad46\"> <a href=\"http://cta-redirect.hubspot.com/cta/redirect/308833/92d07c9f-ee70-4b86-8429-4d6c1621ad46\"><img class=\"hs-cta-img aligncenter\" id=\"hs-cta-img-92d07c9f-ee70-4b86-8429-4d6c1621ad46\" style=\"border-width: 0px;\" alt=\"\" src=\"https://no-cache.hubspot.com/cta/default/308833/92d07c9f-ee70-4b86-8429-4d6c1621ad46.png\" width=\"500\" height=\"280\" /></a></span> </span>\n<!-- end HubSpot Call-to-Action Code --></p>','Landing Page Timing','','publish','open','open','','landing-page-timing','','','2014-03-14 12:31:33','2014-03-14 16:31:33','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2940',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2952,1,'2014-03-20 16:23:55','2014-03-20 20:23:55','Closed loop marketing is logical marketing. It provides valuable insights into customer behaviors and trends. It provides us with more tangibility than a simple marketing persona can give (although those are still important). It provides great detail to marketers. And it has a valuable component other marketing strategies don’t; a logical database design and tracking URL’s.\n\nOne very important aspect of closed loop marketing is connecting lead information to visitor sessions. This is, however, also one of trickiest parts to closed loop marketing.\n\nConnecting lead information to visitor sessions means putting both into one database. This is extremely important. If you don’t connect lead information to visitor session you will have two separate databases; the first being an anonymous visitor history and the second being abstract visitor history. Together, they are amazingly handy, but separate they are amazingly useless.\n\nSo, what are the benefits to this logical database and tracking URL system, otherwise known as closed loop marketing? Closed loop marketing allows marketers to observe the three W’s: who, where, and when their marketing efforts are producing the most (and least) revenue.\n<h2>1. Who</h2>\nIn closed loop marketing, when a user <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/landing-page-timing/\" target=\"_blank\">fills out a landing page form</a>, their information is sent directly to the site’s database. Common information like name, company and (most importantly) email are now available to you. And as we know, <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/your-business-needs-send-emails/\" target=\"_blank\">email marketing</a> is a great way to establish a connection with customers.\n<h2>2. Where</h2>\nClosed loop marketing also makes it easy to see where customers are spending time on the site. Using the data collected, you’ll be able to identify and follow a customer’s on-site activities, providing insight on last conversion event and user pathways. This real-time data is invaluable to a marketing strategy, as it clearly illustrates a customer\'s needs and challenges while maneuvering through forms and pages. We can use this data to make more informed decisions and adjustments to your strategy.\n\nClosed loop marketing also allows you to see which channels are driving customers to specific sites and forms. This data becomes available through creating a tracking URL. The tracking URL shows where (social media, email, blog) marketing efforts most (or least!) effective. From there, more tweaks to the strategy may be necessary. Whether that means cutting losses with one platform or expanding into a new channel, more informed changes can be made to the strategy.\n<h2>3. When</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Now that we have the “where,” we can focus on the “when.” Taking the newly adjusted channels, it’s smart to look at exactly when customers are interacting. Take another look at the data from the tracking URL. You’ll be able to identify when your links are getting the most engagement. Again, make adjustments to strategy based on customer data.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Every decision and adjustment in a closed loop marketing strategy is based on real customer data. Benefits include knowing exactly who, where and when your marketing is the most successful. And when it comes to logic, what’s more logical than knowing your customer through actual, insightful data? I digress.</p>\nIf you’d like to know more about how closed loop marketing works, check out our e-book <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/closed-loop-marketing\" target=\"_blank\">Intro to Closed Loop Marketing</a>.\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"hs-cta-wrapper\" id=\"hs-cta-wrapper-ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216\"><span class=\"hs-cta-node hs-cta-ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216\" id=\"hs-cta-ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216\"> <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/closed-loop-marketing\"><img class=\"hs-cta-img aligncenter\" id=\"hs-cta-img-ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216\" style=\"border-width: 0px;\" alt=\"\" src=\"https://no-cache.hubspot.com/cta/default/308833/ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216.png\" width=\"501\" height=\"286\" /></a>\n</span>photo credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/clarkmaxwell/5428436437/\">clarkmaxwell</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/2.0/\">cc</a></span></p>','3 Benefits of Closed Loop Marketing','','publish','open','open','','3-benefits-closed-loop-marketing','','','2014-03-20 16:23:55','2014-03-20 20:23:55','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2952',0,'post','',2);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2964,1,'2014-03-25 15:18:43','2014-03-25 19:18:43','<p dir=\"ltr\">The benefits of using a tracking URL are obvious. Tracking your linkage is one of the smartest and most pivotal parts of any marketing strategy. Tracking linkage is also an essential piece of any closed loop marketing strategy (and other marketing strategies as well!).</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In my <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/3-benefits-closed-loop-marketing/\" target=\"_blank\">last blog post</a>, I mentioned that tracking URLs provide insight on which social media channels are driving customers to your site and forms. Because they are so important, I want to show you how to create a tracking URL. Hopefully you will be able to incorporate them into your strategy, or learn a valuable new method if you’re already tracking.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">First, here are the tools you will need to create a tracking URL:</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A published piece of content and it’s live URL link</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://support.google.com/analytics/answer/1033867?hl=en\" target=\"_blank\">Google URL Builder</a> (free resource)</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://bitly.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Bitly</a> Account (free resource)</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Step 1</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Create content that is sharable. If you’re not sure what counts as “sharable,” check out our tips on <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/4-guidelines-create-engaging-content/\" target=\"_blank\">creating engaging content</a>. Use your website as the central hub for content, then syndicate through social media sites. Especially in closed loop marketing, social media shouldn’t be the final destination for your customer—you should always aim to bring your audience back to your site. Redirecting viewers back to the website encourages browsing and exploration.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Back to content. Create content that your audience will find useful. Blog posts, infographics, and guides are all great places to start.</p>\n\n<h2>Step 2</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">After you’ve published content to your site and before you publish to social media, it’s time create a tracking URL. It’s extremely important to create a unique URL for each platform you are promoting to. So, even though you’re posting similar content from the same campaign/content source, you’ll want to create different URL’s for each social media source, so that you can track where your click throughs are originating. Copy the published URL of your content. See Image 1.0.</p>\n<img class=\"aligncenter\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2014-03-21 at 12.16.04 PM.png\" src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/ni16qX6d3zDYDQ4LoqExkSqNdgrd8SmH-fqIUyAGw4bFrb04uBsB-aoLfQuGADpohoVghB4S_4h0NFIsjpbLfWjnnfib0sy_UeJyP83vbF-00DXDBHKpgpmyZOsmJw\" width=\"614px;\" height=\"35px;\" />\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: center;\">Image 1.0</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: left;\">Paste the URL into the first text box of the Google URL Builder. It will be located directly under “Step 1: Enter the URL of your website.”</p>\n\n<h2>Step 3</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Fill out the remaining fields, Campaign Source, Campaign Medium and Campaign Name.</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Campaign Source: This is the actual platform you’re syndicating content to. Examples are facebook.com, twitter.com, and plus.google.com</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Campaign Medium: This is your content type. Examples are CPC, banner ads, email, and referral. NOTE: Referral includes all social media platforms.</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Campaign Name: This is the unifying name for the campaign - it’ll appear as an identifier in your analytics tracking. This could also be the campaign’s slogan or term. Try to keep this under 3 words.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">TIP: Enter all Google URL builder content in lowercase. This will keep your URL’s consistent.</p>\n\n<h2>Step 4</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Click Submit. This will generate a URL directly below. Highlight and copy generated URL. See Image 2.0.</p>\n<img class=\"aligncenter\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2014-03-21 at 1.14.20 PM.png\" src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/ChcBeeqQz2nWfoPfAaf2F1NKjwYnBp6fUFDAbAqeJMugg5vM4BiO5pHDl5ezC76Y9pzPKXlNMyUWsUw3TX3p3GTAMDGpm62MLfCzVaDlYvdsfPDGHkRoSbL5an84QQ\" width=\"624px;\" height=\"129px;\" />\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: center;\">Image 2.0</p>\n\n<h2 style=\"text-align: left;\">Step 5</h2>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Open <a href=\"https://bitly.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Bitly</a> and paste the copied URL into the very top text box. Immediately after you paste, a small window will pop up. Let\'s edit the given tracking URL name.</p>\nBecause we’re making very specific URL’s for each source, we want to include which platform is being tracked for each URL. Keep the given title then add “platform” and “Tracking URL.” An example of the edited name is located below in Image 3.0.\n<img class=\"aligncenter\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2014-03-21 at 1.48.33 PM.png\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/MURPyew6zBsClnZnzgAf6pVupoaoAGysspWIRIWeuTs1ZFwORMid4WL15DdSeo_l53TmuCLzcttj4VlKjIIksOVDBauQvcrpE-x2w4XMqfB0rjr5D7ySZmv3pBCgJw\" width=\"518px;\" height=\"195px;\" />\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: center;\">Image 3.0</p>\n&nbsp;\n\nClick save and close the window.\n<h2>Step 6</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Voila—you just created a new tracking link! Now you can copy the new edited bitly link and use it for specified platform. You’ll be able to return to bitly for stats on when and where users selected your link.</p>\nWant more information on tracking URL’s and closed loop marketing? We’ve got you covered. Check out our handy ebook guide, <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/closed-loop-marketing\" target=\"_blank\">Intro to Closed Loop Marketing.</a>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span class=\"hs-cta-wrapper\" id=\"hs-cta-wrapper-ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216\"><span class=\"hs-cta-node hs-cta-ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216\" id=\"hs-cta-ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216\"> <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/closed-loop-marketing\"><img class=\"hs-cta-img aligncenter\" id=\"hs-cta-img-ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216\" style=\"border-width: 0px;\" alt=\"\" src=\"https://no-cache.hubspot.com/cta/default/308833/ee70f976-f410-4a69-aac1-995aace97216.png\" width=\"501\" height=\"286\" /></a></span></span></p>\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/shinyredtype/5692770225/\">shiny red type</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/2.0/\">cc</a>','How to Create a Tracking URL','','publish','open','open','','create-tracking-url','','','2014-03-25 15:18:43','2014-03-25 19:18:43','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2964',0,'post','',2);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2970,1,'2014-03-28 11:54:47','2014-03-28 15:54:47','<p dir=\"ltr\">In a recent content marketing article, I made the point that <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/importance-consistent-brand-voice/\" target=\"_blank\">effective content does not consist of what the marketer wants, but what the customer needs</a>. This principle also applies to landing pages. So before you hit “publish,” answer these 5 questions for more effective landing pages.</p>\n\n<h2>1. Is your form clear enough?</h2>\nThink about the language your target customer uses on a daily basis. Will they relate to the tone and vocabulary your form is using? Is your headline direct and understandable? Is there a way to make the copy more concise? When it comes to landing pages, we want to avoid any and all ambiguity.\n<h2>2. Is your form asking for the right information?</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Are you asking your customer for too much information? Too little? Identify what you need from your customer and choose your form fields based on the data your really want to gather about them. Eliminate anything unnecessary, and try to limit your form to 5 fields or less - you don’t want to risk losing a lead because your form is too long!</p>\n\n<h2>3. Is your design appropriate?</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">An eye-catching design for your landing page is awesome - if you have the time and skill to create a masterpiece, more power to you. However, it’s important to remember not to go overboard. You don’t want a design that’s distracting. When in doubt, keep the design simple, clean and designed for maximum usability.</p>\n\n<h2>4. Are your buttons actionable?</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Think about the copy on your buttons. Do they prompt (not nudge) your customer to take an action? For a higher click-through rate, create copy that is demonstrative and clear. Button copy should never leave your customers second-guessing. Use high-quality, clear verbage, not frothy phrases. It’s also helpful to add some color or a different typeface to define the buttons.</p>\n\n<h2>5. Does your page layout make sense?</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Once again, think about your target customer’s expectations for the page. Most people read from left to right, with a heightened focus on the top-left area of the page. However, maybe your target customer reads text differently, based on culture or background. Other elements to double-check are locations of image and form. Is the image distracting from the form? What would your customer notice first?</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To nurture more leads, you need to think more like your customers. Use language and formatting that resonates with them. For a total landing page checklist, be sure download our ebook on <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/optimizing-landing-pages\" target=\"_blank\">Optimizing Landing Pages</a>.</p>\n<!--[if lte IE 8]>\n<div id=\"hs-cta-ie-element\"></div>\n< ![endif]-->\n\n<a href=\"http://cta-redirect.hubspot.com/cta/redirect/308833/92d07c9f-ee70-4b86-8429-4d6c1621ad46\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" id=\"hs-cta-img-92d07c9f-ee70-4b86-8429-4d6c1621ad46\" style=\"border-width: 0px;\" alt=\"\" src=\"https://no-cache.hubspot.com/cta/default/308833/92d07c9f-ee70-4b86-8429-4d6c1621ad46.png\" /></a>\n\n<!-- end HubSpot Call-to-Action Code -->\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/eleaf/2536358399/\">Eleaf</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>\n','Questions to Ask Before Publishing A Landing Page','','publish','open','open','','5-questions-ask-publishing-landing-page','','','2014-03-28 11:54:47','2014-03-28 15:54:47','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2970',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2989,1,'2014-04-01 16:01:06','2014-04-01 20:01:06','<p dir=\"ltr\">Thinking about redesigning your website? Hold your horses! Whether done in-house or by an agency, a successful site redesign takes a lot of time, organization, and most importantly, planning. Take some time to consider logistics and usability before you dive into design schemes and logos.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Fortunately, we’re here to help with the first step in your website redesign. The first step requires some tedious note-taking, lists and analysis of your current site (Type-A personalities, rejoice!).</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If this sounds like a content audit, that’s because it is—but it’s pivotal part in the redesign process. Trust me. Without it, you won’t be able to set concrete, specific goals for your new site (plus, your new site will be chaos—and who has time for that, right?).</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For <strong>Step 1: BENCHMARK YOUR CURRENT METRIC</strong>, here are the specific areas of your current site to peruse:</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Number of visits/visitors/unique visitors</strong></p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Bounce rate</strong></p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Time on site</strong></p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Current SEO rankings for important keywords</strong></p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Domain authority</strong></p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Number of new leads/form submissions</strong></p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Total amount of sales generated</strong></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\nIf you’re not able to access this info, I recommend using <a href=\"http://www.google.com/analytics/\" target=\"_blank\">Google Analytics</a>, which is free for any website. You’ll want to collect some initial tracking statistics before you start to work on a website redesign, so that you have a baseline you can use to compare the performance of your old and new websites.\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Document and detail your findings into a shared spreadsheet, granting access to the rest of your redesign team. Be sure to make note of any unusual findings. Talk with your team about what you find. What worked? What didn’t work? What will you include in your redesign?</p>\nFor some, this may be the most tedious part of the whole process, but it’s one of most important. So before you pick out the perfect color scheme, be sure to benchmark your current metrics.\n\nFor the rest of the essential steps to a successful website redesign, download our <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/10-step-redesign-checklist\" target=\"_blank\">10-Step Checklist for Your Next Website Design</a>.\n\n<span class=\"hs-cta-wrapper\" id=\"hs-cta-wrapper-c8a87c89-3606-4616-9ad4-7f6681f8c3f8\"><span class=\"hs-cta-node hs-cta-c8a87c89-3606-4616-9ad4-7f6681f8c3f8\" id=\"hs-cta-c8a87c89-3606-4616-9ad4-7f6681f8c3f8\"> <!--[if lte IE 8]>\n<div id=\"hs-cta-ie-element\"></div>\n< ![endif]-->\n<a href=\"http://cta-redirect.hubspot.com/cta/redirect/308833/c8a87c89-3606-4616-9ad4-7f6681f8c3f8\"><img class=\"hs-cta-img aligncenter\" id=\"hs-cta-img-c8a87c89-3606-4616-9ad4-7f6681f8c3f8\" style=\"border-width: 0px;\" alt=\"\" src=\"https://no-cache.hubspot.com/cta/default/308833/c8a87c89-3606-4616-9ad4-7f6681f8c3f8.png\" /></a></span>\n</span>\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/nhoulihan/3560996918/\">InAweofGod\'sCreation</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','First Step in Website Redesign','','publish','open','open','','first-step-website-redesign','','','2014-04-01 16:01:06','2014-04-01 20:01:06','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2989',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (2998,1,'2014-04-08 13:42:26','2014-04-08 17:42:26','<p dir=\"ltr\">Moving is a stressful process. Whether you’re moving to a new house or moving your old website to a new one, there are a handful of things you’ll want to do to protect your most valuable assets.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">And when I say assets, I mean your old website’s valuable SEO rankings.</p>\nIn a website redesign, you want to be able to take your most viewed/searched content to your new site, without losing any SEO value. But with new URLs and information architecture, that task can seem daunting. So how do you protect your SEO during a site move?\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Fortunately, there is a way to transfer your old content to your new site, without losing any precious SEO value. Optimize your new site for search - here are the steps to take:</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>1. Find and document your most searched content.</strong> Your most searched content is extremely valuable to your new site - it’s what your customers have connected with and what’s generated leads. Determine your most valuable pages based on the following analytics:</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">highest traffic</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">inbound links</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">keyword rankings</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>2. Create a 301 redirect strategy.</strong> A 301 redirect commands search engines, like Google, to <a href=\"http://www.practicalecommerce.com/articles/63034-For-Redesigns-Protect-SEO-with-301-Redirect-Strategy-\">transfer link authority</a> and trust from an old URL to the new one. In other words, even though the URL is new and different, it will still redirect to your page because the content is the same or relevant. According to <a href=\"http://www.practicalecommerce.com/articles/63034-For-Redesigns-Protect-SEO-with-301-Redirect-Strategy-\">practicalecommerce.com</a>, a strong 301 redirect strategy can save up to “85 percent of the link authority that the current site has earned over its lifetime.”\n\nWithout a 301 redirect strategy, new site URLs start with an SEO ranking of zero.\n\n<strong>3. Focus on the SEO of your new content. For each site page, pick 1 to 2 keywords to optimize for.</strong> There are plenty of free keyword tools available, but<a href=\"http://adwords.google.com/keywordplanner\"> Google Keyword Planner</a> through Google Adwords is always a good option.\n<p dir=\"ltr\">You can increase your SEO prevalence by optimizing header tags (&lt;h2&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;, &lt;h3&gt;&lt;/h3&gt; and &lt;h4&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;) and optimizing meta or title tags. For a full list of SEO on-page tactics, check out our post on<a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/4-ways-win-snippet-space-search/\"> optimizing SERP rankings</a>.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A new site can make a huge, positive impact for a company. But if your customers can’t find your site, you can’t increase leads, downloads or sales.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Make your move less stressful! Protect your site’s assets and valuable SEO content. For more tips on ways to make your site redesign less stressful, download our ebook <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/10-step-redesign-checklist\">10-Step Checklist for Your Next Website Design</a>.</p>\n<!--[if lte IE 8]>\n<div id=\"hs-cta-ie-element\"></div>\n< ![endif]-->\n\n<a href=\"http://cta-redirect.hubspot.com/cta/redirect/308833/2a232222-342f-4d7b-8e3a-4d32c7ba7eca\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" id=\"hs-cta-img-2a232222-342f-4d7b-8e3a-4d32c7ba7eca\" style=\"border-width: 0px;\" alt=\"\" src=\"https://no-cache.hubspot.com/cta/default/308833/2a232222-342f-4d7b-8e3a-4d32c7ba7eca.png\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/nathanoliverphotography/7736032314/\">Nathan O\'Nions</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','Protect Your SEO During Site Move','','publish','open','open','','protect-seo-site-move','','','2014-04-08 13:42:26','2014-04-08 17:42:26','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=2998',0,'post','',1);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3004,1,'2014-04-11 12:28:17','2014-04-11 16:28:17','<p dir=\"ltr\">Did you know that, on average, marketers redesign their website <a href=\"http://www.slideshare.net/HubSpot/7-reasons-your-website-redesign-wont-be-as-painful-as-you-think-slide-share\" target=\"_blank\">every 18-24 months</a>? They’re a pretty iterative bunch!</p>\nAs I have mentioned before, redesigning a website can make a large and positive impact on a  company’s overall performance. However, if done impulsively, a redesign can also cost a company lots of time, money and productivity.\n<h2>What are your reasons to redesign?</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you’re considering a redesign because “it’s been awhile,” “competition just updated” or you want your site to “look more modern,” don’t redesign - these reasons aren’t strong enough. Without measurable justification, chaos will ensue.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, the following are legitimate reasons a company should redesign:</p>\n<strong>1. Improve Usability</strong>\n\nA good website gets a user to his desired destination with few clicks and no confusion. If your company has been lucky enough to receive feedback (or complaints) from customers on confusing design and usability, it’s time to redesign.\n\nIf you haven\'t received feedback, you can conduct simple usability tests in which you observe users (people not familiar with your site) using your site. Without giving the any user assistance, ask the users to find a specific page. Document their pathway. This provides invaluable data on how customers interact with your site.\n\nIf the user’s actions take him to an undesired location on your site, time to redesign for a more user-friendly website.\n\n<strong>2. Social Media Integration</strong>\n\nIf social media is part of your marketing strategy, but your site doesn’t work in conjunction with social platforms, consider a redesign. This is especially true if the site houses blog content, as you’ll want to utilize social media for message syndication.\n\n<strong>3. Your Target Audience Changed</strong>\n\nAfter some research and new developments, your company has decided to target a different or more specific audience. Your current site’s design and layout may not be aligned with the new audience’s expectations of your site. Create new personas for the new audience. Redesign according to those personas and the new audience’s expectations.\n\n<strong>4. New Products or Services</strong>\n\nIf the company has introduced a completely new set of products or services, you may want to consider a completely new marketing strategy. A rebranding effort is a much larger undertaking than a redesign. If this scenario applies to your company, understand that your new initiative requires more research, time and planning than a redesign.\n\nHowever, if the company is only adding more products or services, a redesign could be a good idea in order to for a seamless integration. You want any new (and future) product additions to be easily added into your site.  If your site makes adding new content difficult, it’s a good idea to redesign the information architecture of the site.\n\n<strong>5. Content Overload</strong>\n\nA content audit revealed your site has information overload - meaning that a smorgasbord of redundant pages, various navigation options and broken links are taking up more space than actual usable content. You know the drill, time to redesign.\n<p dir=\"ltr\">And as they say, “if it’s not broke, don’t fix it.” If you’re considering a redesign, make sure your reasons are justifiable and measurable.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For more tips on the website redesign process, download our ebook <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/10-step-redesign-checklist\" target=\"_blank\">10-Step Checklist for Your Next Website Design</a>.</p>\n<!--[if lte IE 8]>\n<div id=\"hs-cta-ie-element\"></div>\n< ![endif]-->\n\n<a href=\"http://cta-redirect.hubspot.com/cta/redirect/308833/2a232222-342f-4d7b-8e3a-4d32c7ba7eca\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" id=\"hs-cta-img-2a232222-342f-4d7b-8e3a-4d32c7ba7eca\" style=\"border-width: 0px;\" alt=\"\" src=\"https://no-cache.hubspot.com/cta/default/308833/2a232222-342f-4d7b-8e3a-4d32c7ba7eca.png\" /></a>\n\n<script charset=\"utf-8\" type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"https://js.hscta.net/cta/current.js\"></script><script type=\"text/javascript\">// < ![CDATA[\n// < ![CDATA[\n// < ![CDATA[\n// < ![CDATA[\n// < ![CDATA[\n// < ![CDATA[\n// < ![CDATA[ hbspt.cta.load(308833, \'2a232222-342f-4d7b-8e3a-4d32c7ba7eca\');\n// ]]></script>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<!-- end HubSpot Call-to-Action Code -->\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/sybrenstuvel/2468506922/\">Sybren A. Stüvel</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/2.0/\">cc</a>','5 Reasons to Redesign a Website','','publish','open','open','','5-reasons-redesign-website','','','2014-04-11 12:28:17','2014-04-11 16:28:17','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3004',0,'post','',1);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3015,1,'2014-04-15 16:11:51','2014-04-15 20:11:51','<p dir=\"ltr\">It’s been an exciting past couple of weeks for Twitter. From being the <a href=\"http://www.cnn.com/2014/04/09/justice/pennsylvania-school-stabbing/index.html?hpt=hp_t1\" target=\"_blank\">first place to report</a> the Pennsylvania school violence, to acquiring the social data service Gnip, Twitter is proving, yet again, that it is the place for news and information.</p>\nAnother recent breakthrough for Twitter came in the form of a case study. The case study reported very optimistic findings for Twitter Ads, otherwise known as Promoted Tweets. The case study found that, in terms of lead generation, Twitter Ads did better than other social media channel ads, including Facebook. So should marketers be asking, “Could Twitter Ads become more effective than Facebook Ads?”\n<h2>Twitter Ad Case Study</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The case study, done by dating service HowAboutWe, shows that Twitter Ads generated more leads than other social media channel paid advertising. The case study was conducted in the fourth quarter of 2013, pulling data from Twitter’s geo-and-interest tagging targeting.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The case study revealed that leads from Twitter were “<a href=\"http://mashable.com/2014/04/15/twitter-improves-for-advertisers/\" target=\"_blank\">20% more likely to convert</a> paying subscribers than other channels where ads were also present.” It also found that leads are “20% more likely to convert to paying subscribers than the rest of the brand\'s traffic.”</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">So, is Twitter a better platform for advertising than Facebook? We can’t answer that for sure,  but it’s definitely now competing with Facebook. It’s important to remember that paid advertising success greatly depends on the target audience. However, it’s also important to note that if done for the right audience, Twitter ads can greatly impact a brand’s connection to a targeted audience.</p>\n\n<h2>How Twitter Ads Work</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Twitter ads became more effective after the platform introduced <a href=\"https://blog.twitter.com/2013/more-relevant-ads-with-tailored-audiences\" target=\"_blank\">Tailored Audience Advertising</a> in December 2013. Like Facebook’s Custom Audiences, Tailored Audience Advertising targets the right people with the right content. Tailored Audience Advertising works when brands creates specific messages suited for a specific sector of their audience. The brands then show Twitter their target audience’s browser cookie ID’s. Through an ad partner, Twitter takes the specific audience browser cookie ID\'s and shows the audience the appropriate tweet. And voilà, a Promoted Tweet has been born.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">While Facebook measures views and clicks, Twitter measures favorites, retweets and replies. Twitter’s measurements alone give marketers and better view of audience engagement.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">HowAboutWe CEO Brian Schechter recently said \"Twitter has definitely reached a level of maturity where we can rely on it.” While he also noted that there was room for improvement, HowAboutWe’s case study is just the first of many to acknowledge the capability of Twitter Ads.</p>\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/hectoralejandro/4408178188/\">hectorir</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','Twitter Ads More Effective Than Facebook Ads?','','publish','open','open','','twitter-ads-effective-facebook-ads','','','2014-04-15 16:11:51','2014-04-15 20:11:51','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3015',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3020,1,'2014-04-17 12:05:12','2014-04-17 16:05:12','<p dir=\"ltr\">“We don’t have a choice on whether we do social media, the choice is how well we do it,” says Erik Qualman in his latest Youtube video called #Socialnomics 2014.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.socialnomics.net/about-erik-qualman/\" target=\"_blank\">Qualman</a>, an author, speaker and Michigan State University graduate, provides an eye-opening view on the major impact social media has on today’s business and culture with his new video.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Take a few minutes to watch his <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zxpa4dNVd3c&amp;feature=youtube_gdata\" target=\"_blank\">video</a> and better understand the current and future social media landscape.</p>\n<iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/zxpa4dNVd3c\" height=\"315\" width=\"560\" allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\"></iframe>','Socialnomics 2014','','publish','open','open','','socialnomics-2014','','','2014-04-17 12:05:12','2014-04-17 16:05:12','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3020',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3047,1,'2014-04-22 16:12:30','2014-04-22 20:12:30','We all know about the importance of keywords in online content - you need people to find your content! (people need to know that the page they’re clicking on addresses their needs!) There’s no doubt, keyword research and selection are an important aspect of your on-page SEO. But what about off-page SEO? What is it, and how can you use it to make your content more findable?\n\nTo answer the latter, you can do a lot of things. But first, let’s talk about what off-page SEO is.\n\nOff-page SEO is a set of techniques that can be used to “<a href=\"http://www.reliablesoft.net/what-is-off-page-seo/\" target=\"_blank\">improve</a> the position of a web site in the search engine results page (SERPs).” The most important aspect of off-page SEO is the ability to gain online authority. Meaning, off-page SEO tactics can help your site gain a quality reputation with search engines.\n\nWhat exactly are some off-page SEO tactics I can use? Glad you asked! Below is a list of smart off-page SEO tactics you can implement immediately:\n\n<b>1. Link Building</b>\n\nLinks should not be the only tactic employed in your off-page SEO strategy - I repeat, <i>should not</i>. Google does not like this and can actually punish your website for this strategy. Proper link building is tricky, and I could dedicate an entire post to link building, but I won’t now. For the meantime, remember to use links sparingly and only link to credible sources.\n\n<b>2. Developing Compelling Content</b>\n\nPublishing content that your audience finds useful, helpful and relevant builds online authority by itself. If you’re already doing that, good for you - keep up the good work! When it comes to content creation, the goal is not to create what <i>you</i> want, but what your customer wants. Think about what your ideal customer would find useful. Maybe it’s a video how-to or a technical whitepaper. Whatever it is, if your customer finds it useful they will share with others, and that’s what you want.\n\n<b>3. Engaging in Co-Marketing</b>\n\nSpeaking of sharing, here’s where networking comes into play. Find influencers in your industry and reach out to them with your content. Cultivate relationships with other companies and share your content. The more eyes on your content, the better.\n\n<b>4. Utilizing Social Media</b>\n\nSocial media can be a mixed bag to some marketers. They use it as another way to push out their message and content - but that’s wrong. Very wrong. Look at social media as a way to share your messages with others in your industry. Don’t push or shout content, share your messages and stories.\n\n<b>5. Using PR Thoughtfully</b>\n\nThe press release game has changed. Links are no longer allowed in a press release, but that doesn’t mean the PR is dead. Distribute the PR to bloggers, influencers and social media leaders as well as traditional news sources. Including keywords (no links, though!) is a good idea, too.\n\nKeywords are important, but there are plenty of small things you can do off-page to make your content findable.\n\nIf you’d like more help on SEO, be sure to download our free e-book <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/overcoming-your-seo-challenges\" target=\"_blank\">Overcoming Your SEO Challenges</a>.\n\n<span id=\"hs-cta-wrapper-54ec7dd0-6466-4e7a-88a6-403f4b9bbf18\" class=\"hs-cta-wrapper\"><span id=\"hs-cta-54ec7dd0-6466-4e7a-88a6-403f4b9bbf18\" class=\"hs-cta-node hs-cta-54ec7dd0-6466-4e7a-88a6-403f4b9bbf18\"> <!-- [if lte IE 8]>\n<div id=\"hs-cta-ie-element\"></div>\n< ![endif]-->\n<a href=\"http://cta-redirect.hubspot.com/cta/redirect/308833/54ec7dd0-6466-4e7a-88a6-403f4b9bbf18\"><img id=\"hs-cta-img-54ec7dd0-6466-4e7a-88a6-403f4b9bbf18\" class=\"hs-cta-img aligncenter\" style=\"border-width: 0px;\" src=\"https://no-cache.hubspot.com/cta/default/308833/54ec7dd0-6466-4e7a-88a6-403f4b9bbf18.png\" alt=\"\" /></a></span> </span>\n<!-- end HubSpot Call-to-Action Code -->\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/sevendead/5650065458/\">Dave Edens</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/2.0/\">cc</a>','5 Off-Page SEO Tactics','','publish','open','open','','5-page-seo-tactics','','','2014-04-22 16:12:30','2014-04-22 20:12:30','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3047',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3060,1,'2014-04-29 16:52:45','2014-04-29 20:52:45','There are countless marketing strategies available today, all promising to generate more leads and produce more sales. A majority of them rely on a push methodology—where pushing outbound offers and content are the name of the game. Unfortunately, that’s where some marketing strategies go wrong.\n\nWe believe the most effective way to generate leads, and drive sales, is to foster a long-term relationship with the customer.\n\nIntroducing inbound marketing. What makes inbound marketing different than other strategies? For one, it’s not the annoying, cold-calling, disruptive traditional marketing scheme that so many people are used to (and loathe). Rather than pushing sales, inbound pulls in the prospect in by offering valuable content in exchange for a relationship.\n<h2>It’s not a hard sale.</h2>\nIt may seem odd that a marketing strategy incorporates the phrase “eventually buying.” But, where other marketing strategies ask for sales immediately after making contact, inbound marketing relies on a growing relationship between the business and it’s customer.\n\nBy producing fresh, relevant content designed with customers in mind, inbound marketing seeks to be a resource for customers. We do this in order to establish and maintain a long-term relationship with customers, ensuring referrals and secondary sales.\n<h2>It’s where the customer and business relationship begins.</h2>\nIn an inbound marketing strategy, the business does not approach the customer first. Rather, if the customer shows an interest in your business, “they are starting the relationship, making it easier to for them to <a href=\"http://blog.hubspot.com/marketing/beginner-inbound-lead-generation-guide-ht\">want to buy from you down the line</a>.”\n<h2>It’s effective.</h2>\nInbound marketing is great at generating leads because it utilizes the customer’s natural interest in the product/service to cultivate a lasting relationship. It converts the right visitors into leads, and then into returning customers—without using any obnoxious sales pitches.\n\nThe most effective inbound marketers look at their strategy as an opportunity to be a resource from their customers. We know it sounds unorthodox, but if you look at marketing as building a relationship - not just making sales - it makes a whole lot of sense.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/means_of_production/7916467366/\">Means-of-Production</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/2.0/\">cc</a>','What Makes Inbound Marketing Different—And Effective','','publish','open','open','','makes-inbound-marketing-different-effective','','','2014-04-29 16:52:45','2014-04-29 20:52:45','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3060',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3066,1,'2014-05-06 13:02:31','2014-05-06 17:02:31','Sometimes it can be hard to keep an objective view of your efforts when you’re in the thick of things, especially when it comes to your current marketing strategy.\n\nIf you’re feeling a little bogged down by endless writing, scheduling, managing and monitoring of everything from social media content to landing page conversions, it might be time to take a step back and look at your marketing efforts with a fresh pair of eyes.\n\nTo help you take the temperature of your digital marketing strategy, we have just the quiz for you. Our handy-dandy <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/marketing-assessment/\" target=\"_blank\">Marketing Assessment</a> calculates an accurate score of your current marketing efforts based on your answers.\n\nIf you’re still not convinced you need to gauge your current marketing efforts, here are 3 more reasons to take the Marketing Assessment.\n\n<b>1. New Strategy</b>\n\nYou’ve adopted a quasi digital marketing strategy. You feel some things are going great, but other strategic aspects leave you in a bit of haze. The assessment will help you pinpoint areas of improvement as well as areas of success.\n\n<b>2. New Audience</b>\n\nIf your current strategy widened or narrowed your target audience, it’s vital to take a step back and see if you’re making those valuable connections.\n\n<b>3. Losing and Gaining Leads</b>\n\nBoth scenarios call for analysis and reflection. If you’re losing leads, an assessment of your current strategy is most definitely in order. If you’re gaining leads, the assessment can help you better understand exactly what’s working. Plus, there are always areas that could use improvement, so taking a quick assessment can’t hurt your current efforts.\n\nConvinced now? Go ahead and take a look at your marketing strategy with a fresh pair of eyes with our <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/marketing-assessment/\" target=\"_blank\">Marketing Assessment</a>.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/wwworks/1431384410/\">woodleywonderworks</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','Your Strategy Needs a Fresh Pair of Eyes and a Marketing Assessment','','publish','open','open','','assess-marketing-strategy-fresh-pair-eyes','','','2014-05-06 13:02:31','2014-05-06 17:02:31','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3066',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3074,1,'2014-05-08 16:25:15','2014-05-08 20:25:15','By now, you know that attracting leads is one of the essential goals of any online marketing strategy, but sometimes it’s hard to convince those leads to become customers. Let’s go through the 4 essential steps for converting leads into customers in inbound marketing.\n<h2>1. Attract</h2>\nIt’s not just about attracting visitors to your site - it’s about attracting the <i>right</i> visitors to your site. Inbound uses fresh blog content, interactive social media, researched keywords and well-designed website pages to attract the right customers. All of these tools are created with the target “dream customer” in mind. Before creating any content for your “dream customer,” be sure to create detailed buyer personas. Buyer personas are fictional characters of a targeted audience that include details from everything from age, gender and occupation to hopes, dreams and pain points. Hint: A more detailed buyer persona will help you create better content.\n\nIn inbound, content should never be created because of what you (the owner) wants, but rather based on what the customer will find useful.\n<h2>2. Convert</h2>\nAfter you’ve attracted the right visitors, you need to convert them into leads. In order to do so, you’ll need to collect the visitor’s contact information such as name, location, place of work, and most importantly, an email address.\n\nHowever, most people aren’t going around giving their contact information to just anyone. There must be something the visitor finds useful to download/read/view in exchange for their information. Useful content could be a free ebook, infographic, video, whitepaper, etc.\n\nYou will actually gather their contact information through tools like CTA buttons, appropriately placed landing pages, simple forms and a contact database (a handy place to store all that visitor contact information). (Check out one of our <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/30-lead-gen-tips\" target=\"_blank\">ebook landing pages</a> to see how all of those pieces seamlessly fit together.)\n<h2>3. Close</h2>\nBy attracting and converting visitors, you’re already communicating with visitors. Now you need to close - and, by close, I mean turn those leads into customers. Inbound uses a series of marketing tools to accomplish this. These include segmenting leads into categories, or <a href=\"http://blog.hubspot.com/blog/tabid/6307/bid/31279/How-to-Score-Your-Leads-So-Sales-Works-the-Hottest-Prospects.aspx\" target=\"_blank\">lead scoring</a>; weekly emails to leads that provide relevant and valuable information, while building a trusting relationship; and detailed closed-loop reports that show you how well marketing and sales are working together. (See our <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/3-benefits-closed-loop-marketing/\" target=\"_blank\">closed-loop marketing post</a> for more info on how this system works.)\n<h2>4. Delight</h2>\nSo you’ve attracted, converted and successfully closed a customer, but your work isn’t done yet! The inbound methodology prides itself on continuing to be a resource to customers, regardless of whether they are a long-standing customer or a brand new visitor to the site.\n\nThe goal is to continue a mutually beneficial relationship with customers by sharing valuable content through emails, newsletters, videos, blog posts etc., engaging via social media and delighting customers with resources and news prevalent in their industry. By doing all of this, the hope is that your content will be so useful to your customers that they will want to promote your brand to others.\n\nLike I mentioned in a recent post, inbound marketing <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/makes-inbound-marketing-different-effective/\" target=\"_blank\">does not interrupt people</a>, but rather, connects to customers by providing valuable information that pertains to their life. And it can all be done in 4 easy steps.\n\nWhat are your thoughts on inbound marketing? Do you practice a similar methodology? Love to hear your thoughts below!\n\nImage provided by <a href=\"http://www.hubspot.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Hubspot Partners</a>','How To: Converting Leads Into Customers','','publish','open','open','','converting-leads-customers','','','2014-05-08 16:25:15','2014-05-08 20:25:15','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3074',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3081,1,'2014-05-13 15:23:10','2014-05-13 19:23:10','It’s a strange question, I know. With millions of social media messages being published daily, it’s easy to tweet and post without any thought or justification. To supplement our recent <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/marketing-assessment/\" target=\"_blank\">marketing assessment quiz</a>, I wanted to create a simple questionnaire that can help determine whether you’re using social media correctly.\n\n<b>1. How many channels do you have?</b> Sometimes with social media, less is more. It’s more important to establish a visible presence on social media channels that your specific audience uses, rather than being visible on all of them. Eliminating unnecessary channels will help you create better content for ones your audience does use.\n\n<b>2. How much are you posting?</b> Like channels, the amount of social media your brand publishes should be based on audience. If your audience uses Twitter heavily, you would be doing your brand a disservice by only tweeting once a day. Post and publish social media content according to your audience standards and the specific social media channel. Keep in mind that each social media channel has different rates of decay, so the amount of content can vary greatly between each channel.\n\n<b>3. Is your brand voice consistent?</b> If you have a team, or even just a couple of different people managing your social media, it’s imperative to make sure everyone uses consistent style, tone, and grammar (check out this article on <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/importance-consistent-brand-voice/\" target=\"_blank\">finding and maintaining a brand voice</a> if you’re not sure where to start). You want your brand voice to have one resounding voice - so, if you haven\'t had a brand voice meeting yet, be sure to get together with your group to go over brand voice expectations and guidelines. Go one step further and create a brand voice style guide that everyone can refer to.\n\n<b>4. Are you monitoring your audience?</b> Social media monitoring is a beast all it’s own. However, no matter how small your team or budget, it’s still very possible to monitor all your social media platforms with relative ease. One easy way to monitor your social media audience is to create custom tracking links. If you’re promoting blog content through social media, use custom tracking links to easily identify where and when your social media audience is engaging with your content. Directions on creating custom tracking links can be found <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/create-tracking-url/\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>.\n\n<b>5. Is your social media content varied?</b> Variety is the spice of life. Keep your audience interested by publishing content that is diverse and fresh. Things like photos, infographics or videos are great and easy ways to add interest to otherwise static content. Don’t be afraid to get a little creative. For more tips and tricks on creating more engaging content, check out <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/4-guidelines-create-engaging-content/\" target=\"_blank\">this blog post</a>.\n\n<b>6. Are you interacting with your audience?</b> These days, the internet is buzzing about “engaging with your audience.” Most of the time, articles and blogs are just talking about creating engaging content. However, we often forget about the power of actually interacting with the audience. If someone criticizes your product or if you’re lucky enough to get a glowing review, take the time to resolve the issue or thank them for the kind words. Remember, social media gives businesses the opportunity to talk to real people, so be sure to treat them that way.\n\nThere you have it. Hopefully by answering these questions, you’ll be able to gauge your current social media efforts and make some changes to improve.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/mkhmarketing/8539048913/\">mkhmarketing</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','Are You Using Social Media Correctly?','','publish','open','open','','using-social-media-correctly','','','2014-05-13 15:23:10','2014-05-13 19:23:10','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3081',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3087,1,'2014-05-16 14:45:04','2014-05-16 18:45:04','Google is known for connecting people to information. However, since May of 2012, Google has made a push to connect people to more than just information, but rather, knowledge. Introducing Google’s Knowledge Graph. It not only appears different but also represents Google’s groundbreaking push to a semantic web.) Since search is such an important aspect to digital marketing, what does the Knowledge Graph mean for marketers?\n<h2>A Quick Example</h2>\nBefore getting into the digital marketing implications of the Knowledge Graph, let’s look at what Google’s Knowledge Graph is. As an example, I searched “golden retriever” in the Google Search bar. Here are my results - note that the Google Knowledge Graph is circled in red.\n\n<a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/knowledge_graph.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-3088 aligncenter\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/knowledge_graph-300x154.jpg\" alt=\"knowledge graph example\" width=\"386\" height=\"198\" /></a>\n\nAs you can see, all the information on golden retrievers is neatly bundled into a perfect little package, presenting the most relevant and useful information for me to quickly digest. My search results from the Knowledge Graph were not only quick, but also easily accessible. Touche, Google Knowledge Graph. However, upon further review, you’ll notice a glaring problem for marketers.\n\nIn the image directly below, notice the red oval that highlights the second search result. This search result is the link to the Golden Retriever Page of the American Kennel Club website, a widely-known and respected dog breed organization.\n\n<a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/knowledge_graph_2.jpg\"><img class=\" wp-image-3089 aligncenter\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/knowledge_graph_2-300x154.jpg\" alt=\"knowledge graph 2\" width=\"408\" height=\"209\" /></a>\n\nSo, instead of getting your information from the AKC website, you’re actually getting information from Google’s Knowledge Graph (which, by the way, doesn’t even link to AKC but to Wikipedia instead).\n\nThis poses a problem for marketers. As a marketer, the goal is the get the searcher/user to click your content. Although your content is credible and reliable (like the AKC for instance), it is still difficult to compete with the extremely convenient and accessible Google Knowledge Graph.\n<h2>Threats to Marketing</h2>\nBesides acquiring fewer clicks from searchers, what other threats does Google’s Knowledge Graph pose to marketers?\n<ul>\n	<li>Loss of credibility and traffic if the links inside the Knowledge Graph don’t link to your site</li>\n	<li>Loss in revenue from paid advertising</li>\n	<li>Loss in revenue from onsite advertising</li>\n</ul>\nThis article isn’t meant to scare you or make you feel like all past SEO efforts are lost. On the contrary, it’s important to be informed of the ever-evolving Google Search world. Many <a href=\"http://searchengineland.com/knowledge-graph-mean-content-strategy-business-model-186736\">SEO experts</a> believe that Google’s Knowledge Graph will have the greatest impact on publishers. For all other website owners, it’s important to (at least) think about how Google’s Knowledge Graph could change your search engine results.\n<h2>How to Work With It</h2>\nRemember that Google and the Google Knowledge Graph rank sites based on credibility and authority. If your site produces quality content using audience-based keywords, Google will favor that strategy. Here are some other ways to be Knowledge Graph ready:\n<ul>\n	<li>Optimize your company’s Google+ Page</li>\n	<li>Display customer reviews on your website</li>\n	<li>Optimize your titles and meta descriptions</li>\n	<li>Optimize video content for search (Google Knowledge Graph has not yet indexed video content. Use with caution - if you’re going to make a video, make sure it’s valuable content!)</li>\n</ul>\nMarketers are still in the early stages of creating a relationship with the Google Knowledge Graph. Currently, some aspects create an oil-and-water type of relationship with marketing. Yet, future additions and advancements to the Knowledge Graph could create a match-made in heaven.\n\nAlthough the future is still a bit fuzzy, it’s important for you, as a marketer, to be cognizant of it’s current effects and the ways to work with it.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/edsweeney/6346198056/\">Navicore</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','Google Knowledge Graph and Marketing: Oil and Water or Match-Made in Heaven?','','publish','open','open','','google-knowledge-graph-marketing-oil-water-match-made-heaven','','','2014-05-16 14:45:04','2014-05-16 18:45:04','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3087',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3096,1,'2014-05-20 15:07:52','2014-05-20 19:07:52','New to lead generation? No problem. If you’re currently creating quality content for your audience on your website, well, you’re already halfway there! Lead generation doesn’t have to be difficult. You just have to take a couple extra steps in order to generate those leads.\n\nHere are 4 quick tips to increase leads using your blog and landing pages.\n<h2>Blog Post Tips</h2>\n<strong>1. Add CTA’s at the end of blog posts.</strong> As a modern marketer, you know getting a site visitor’s email address is like finding a golden nugget. Their email address gives you an amazing opportunity to cultivate a relationship and ultimately build a returning customer. Pure gold. But, how do you get an email address?\n\nOne easy way to acquire that golden nugget is through a CTA (Call-To-Action). A CTA is an image or line of text that prompts your visitors, leads, and customers to take action,” as defined by <a href=\"http://blog.hubspot.com/marketing/what-is-call-to-action-faqs-ht\" target=\"_blank\">Hubspot</a>. A CTA can lead to anything! Think things like blog subscriptions, blog comments, ebook downloads, an invite to a party, etc.\n\nWhatever the action, CTA’s usually send the visitor to a landing page with a form that retrieves their email address (aka the golden nugget). They can be placed anywhere, but since we’re talking specifically about a blog visitor, be sure to stick it at the end of blog post.\n\n<strong>2. Make it sharable.</strong> Since you’ve already created content that your audience will find awesome, be sure to include social media buttons so your audience can share the awesome information on their social networks.\n<h2>Landing Page Tips</h2>\n<strong>1. Create a fun, simple landing page form.</strong> As a digital marketer, you know landing pages play a pivotal role in lead generation. So, it makes sense to create a landing page and landing page form that is well-designed and well-written (you’ve already created awesome content for the blog, why stop now?).\n\nIn the form, always ask for the visitor’s name and email - those are givens. Depending on your audience, you can also be a little creative with the form. For instance, if you have movie blog, you can add a funny question to the form about which Martin Scorsese film swears the most or what is the best sci-fi movie of all time. Keep the question short and tailored to your audience’s interest.\n\nAlong with a little creativity, your landing page form should be short and direct. Generally, the landing page form should contain less than 5 fields. It’s important to remember, filling out a landing page form is an inconvenience to the visitor. Making the experience a little less annoying (and possibly bringing a smile to their face - maybe?) is another way to connect with the visitor and generate a lead.\n\n<strong>2. Make it sharable.</strong> The same principle applies to blog posts as it does to landing pages. If your visitor just downloaded your handy ebook, be sure to add social sharable buttons to encourage their own sharing. Once their friends see it, they can download the ebook and fill out their own form. And voila, a new lead is generated!\n\nNew to marketing and need a way to gauge your marketing efforts? Take our <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/marketing-assessment/\" target=\"_blank\">Marketing Assessment</a> to see how your current strategy is holding up.\n\n<span id=\"hs-cta-wrapper-2b0f5abe-59f9-4069-bfa5-9c4da268e737\" class=\"hs-cta-wrapper\"><span id=\"hs-cta-2b0f5abe-59f9-4069-bfa5-9c4da268e737\" class=\"hs-cta-node hs-cta-2b0f5abe-59f9-4069-bfa5-9c4da268e737\"> <a href=\"http://cta-redirect.hubspot.com/cta/redirect/308833/2b0f5abe-59f9-4069-bfa5-9c4da268e737\"><img id=\"hs-cta-img-2b0f5abe-59f9-4069-bfa5-9c4da268e737\" class=\"hs-cta-img aligncenter\" style=\"border-width: 0px;\" src=\"https://no-cache.hubspot.com/cta/default/308833/2b0f5abe-59f9-4069-bfa5-9c4da268e737.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"455\" height=\"213\" /></a></span></span>\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/means_of_production/7916469928/\">Means-of-Production</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/2.0/\">cc</a>','If You\'re New to Lead Generation, Read This','','publish','open','open','','youre-new-lead-generation-read','','','2014-05-20 15:07:52','2014-05-20 19:07:52','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3096',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3105,1,'2014-05-23 11:48:32','2014-05-23 15:48:32','If you’ve watched any TV in the last 3 years, you’ve probably noticed a small sticker on the bottom on your screen packed with hashtags and little blue birds. Yes, social media has even infiltrated your favorite TV show. It’s called social TV, and it’s not only proving that social media is here to stay, but that real-time marketing is boosting customer engagement and ratings.\n\nSo, how do real time marketing (RTM) and social TV connect? RTM is a sector of <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real-time_marketing\" target=\"_blank\">inbound marketing</a>, which relies on interacting with customers at the most relevant and pivotal time, not interrupting randomly like traditional marketing strategies. Social TV is one of the latest forms of RTM, using the specific time the viewer (customer) engages with the show (brand) to develop a meaningful relationship and drive sales.\n\nBut, Social TV is a particularly interesting RTM method because it is driving a behavior. One could argue that watching television is an involuntary social  behavior. We have consumed so much television in our lives (on average, we spend <a href=\"http://www.statisticbrain.com/television-watching-statistics/\" target=\"_blank\">9 YEARS</a> watching over a lifetime) that it’s become a very normal daily occurrence. However, when TV programs started asking viewers to tweet their thoughts about the show, the act of watching TV became much more interactive and voluntary. Statistics have shown that social TV is increasing engagement and ratings (aka sales).\n\nThe graph below by <a href=\"http://www.nielsen.com/us/en/newswire/2013/the-follow-back--understanding-the-two-way-causal-influence-betw.html\" target=\"_blank\">Nielsen Social,</a> a leader in social TV measurement, depicts a recent finding from a study that analyzed the relationship between Twitter and tv ratings. Nielsen Social found that the relationship between Twitter and TV ratings is mutually beneficial, calling it a “two-way causal influence between broadcast TV tune-in for a program  and the Twitter conversation around that program.” Notice the 29% increase in TV ratings caused by increase in volume of tweets.\n<p style=\"text-align: left\"><a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/neilson_follow_back.png\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-3106\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/neilson_follow_back-300x283.png\" alt=\"Nielsen Social Graph\" width=\"300\" height=\"283\" /></a></p>\n<em>(Source: Nielsen Social)</em>\n\nHowever “casual” this relationship may be, one thing is for sure, social media isn’t going anywhere, but rather getting more real by the minute.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/alvi2047/3688993279/\">@alviseni</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/2.0/\">cc</a>','TV: Getting More Social and Real By The Minute','','publish','open','open','','tv-getting-social-real-minute','','','2014-05-23 11:48:32','2014-05-23 15:48:32','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3105',0,'post','',2);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3111,1,'2014-05-27 16:10:53','2014-05-27 20:10:53','This upcoming June 2nd - June 6th 2014 marks <a href=\"http://www.inboundmarketingweek.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Inbound Marketing Week</a>. This is a legitimate global event, hosted by the inbound marketing god, Hubspot. Inbound and digital marketers from all over the world will gather in places like Chicago, Austin and London to talk about past inbound events, discuss the latest trends, and shape the future of inbound. Brilliant.\n\nHere at Ingenex, we think inbound marketing is genius - so in honor of this great week, I wanted to write a blog post on our best inbound marketing tips, tricks and tidbits.\n\n<b>1. Know your audience.</b> Inbound relies on supplying the customer with useful and relevant content based on their buyer personas. The more you know your audience, the better and more meaningful your content will be.\n\n<b>2. Information is the currency of inbound.</b> When collecting visitor’s contact information, be sure to collect name, location, place of work, and most importantly, an email address.\n\n<b>3. Focus on quality, not quantity. </b>It’s not about attracting any and all visitors to your site; it’s about attracting the right visitors to your site.\n\n<b>4. Track, track, track. Did we mention you should track?</b> Knowing where and when customers reach your content is extremely important. It allows you to fine-tune ways to successfully contact your audience as well as rid of the ineffective platforms. Here’s our step-by-step guide on creating <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/create-tracking-url/\" target=\"_blank\">custom tracking URL’s</a>.\n\n<b>5. Don’t forget about search engines.</b> SEO plays a large role in inbound - but it doesn’t have to be as complicated as it sounds. At the very least, keep it simple by researching and using keywords.\n\n<b>6. Closing the sale means building trust.</b> Weekly targeted emails sent to leads are the perfect opportunity to provide relevant and helpful information, so that you can build a relationship and seal the deal.\n\n<b>7. Evergreen content is very important.</b> Evergreen content should be quality content that can withstand the test of time. Content marketers know the importance of having this stuff on speed dial, as it’s content their audience can always connect with. So, instead of a blog post on Twitter trends, think about an ebook on social media methodologies. Yes, it may take more effort to create, but you can also reuse and repurpose the content as needed.\n\n<b>8. Landing pages are your best friend - so treat them that way.</b> Landing pages should include a simple design, clear form (5 fields or less), an enticing CTA button and social sharing buttons.\n\n<b>9. Quit thinking about yourself.</b> Content creation should be based on your audience’s needs and wants, not yours.\n\n<b>10. If you’re not inbound, you’re out(bound).</b> The goal of inbound marketing is not to be pushy or intrusive - just the opposite, in fact. Inbound marketers seek to be a trusted resource for their customers to come back to.\n\nWant to find out how these tips apply to your own business? Take our FREE (and fun!) <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/marketing-assessment/\" target=\"_blank\">digital marketing assessment</a>. And for more information on Inbound Marketing Week events, check out the official itinerary <a href=\"http://www.inboundmarketingweek.org/events\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>. Be sure the follow the hashtag #InboundMarketingWeek for tips, tricks, and conversations from us and other top inbound marketers\n\n<span id=\"hs-cta-wrapper-2b0f5abe-59f9-4069-bfa5-9c4da268e737\" class=\"hs-cta-wrapper\"><span id=\"hs-cta-2b0f5abe-59f9-4069-bfa5-9c4da268e737\" class=\"hs-cta-node hs-cta-2b0f5abe-59f9-4069-bfa5-9c4da268e737\">\n<a href=\"http://cta-redirect.hubspot.com/cta/redirect/308833/2b0f5abe-59f9-4069-bfa5-9c4da268e737\"><img id=\"hs-cta-img-2b0f5abe-59f9-4069-bfa5-9c4da268e737\" class=\"hs-cta-img\" style=\"border-width: 0px\" src=\"https://no-cache.hubspot.com/cta/default/308833/2b0f5abe-59f9-4069-bfa5-9c4da268e737.png\" alt=\"\" /></a>\n</span>\n</span>\n<!-- end HubSpot Call-to-Action Code -->\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/78855484@N03/7223384344/\">ganderssen1</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','#InboundMarketingWeek: Our Top Inbound Marketing Tips','','publish','open','open','','inboundmarketingweek-top-inbound-tips-tricks','','','2014-05-27 16:10:53','2014-05-27 20:10:53','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3111',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3120,1,'2014-06-03 09:57:36','2014-06-03 13:57:36','Some lessons in life just stick - like always saying “please” and “thank you,” or remembering to wait at least 20 minutes before drinking a McDonald’s coffee.\n\nYou know what else stuck with me? The CRAP design principles. Even without the memorable acronym, these are useful standards for all design work.\n\nAs a writer and a (poor-man’s) designer, I was taught in college to look at any piece of content with the CRAP principles in mind. If you’re like me and spend most of your day online, you begin to notice patterns and trends among websites and brands.\n\nSo, I thought I would write about all the latest web design trends and see how they apply to CRAP principles. My professors would be so proud.\n<h2>“C” is for Contrast.</h2>\nOne major web design trend is using contrasting typefaces. Designers are using fonts like script and slab together to create an interesting, unique feel to their type.\n\nTraditionally, designers were told to keep script or slab fonts to a minimum, but many websites are ignoring that old standby.\n\n<a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/Screen-Shot-2014-05-30-at-12.04.08-PM.png\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-3126 size-large\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/Screen-Shot-2014-05-30-at-12.04.08-PM-1024x465.png\" alt=\"brooklyn soap company\" width=\"604\" height=\"274\" /></a>\n\n<i>(Source: http://bklynsoap.com/)</i>\n<h2>“R” is for Repetition.</h2>\nRepetition is what is responsible for creating the whole feel of brand. Repeating elements across a web page signals a unified, cohesive feel to the user. A consistently placed logo across a website or using the same fonts for all heading tags are just some examples of repetition in web design.\n\nLately, I’ve noticed companies being more creative with the placements of their logos. Placing logos in the center or on the right allows the rest of the design become more fluid and eye-catching in nature. While center and right side logo placement may not be a huge trend, it’s still interesting to see designers deviate from the norm.\n\n<a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/Screen-Shot-2014-05-30-at-11.39.23-AM.png\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-3127 size-large\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/Screen-Shot-2014-05-30-at-11.39.23-AM-1024x555.png\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2014-05-30 at 11.39.23 AM\" width=\"604\" height=\"327\" /></a>\n\n<i>(Source: </i><a href=\"http://bgmedia.com/bgi2004/index.html\" target=\"_blank\"><i>http://bgmedia.com/bgi2004/index.html</i></a><i>)</i>\n<h2>“A” is for Alignment.</h2>\nAlignment in design is also known as the grouping or “chunking” of information. Alignment plays a major role in giving the web page a sense of order and intent.\n\nThe latest trend in alignment in web design is the full-page layout. In a full-page layout, the left and right sidebars are removed. This layout has been very popular for website homepages as it gives the front page a punchier feel. Removing the left and right sidebars makes the user focus solely on the content in the center of the page. You can see how this design would be particularly helpful to websites that are image-heavy.\n\n<a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/Screen-Shot-2014-05-30-at-11.26.56-AM.png\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-3128 size-large\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/Screen-Shot-2014-05-30-at-11.26.56-AM-1024x546.png\" alt=\"alignment\" width=\"604\" height=\"322\" /></a>\n\n<i>(Source: http://skidmorestudio.com/</i><i>)</i>\n<h2>“P” is for Proximity.</h2>\nLike alignment, proximity also focuses on the grouping and arrangement of elements. By grouping like items together, you tell the user that those elements are inherently similar or, by the same token, different if placed farther apart.\n\nA major trend I’ve seen as of late is the addition of <a href=\"http://blog.teamtreehouse.com/white-space-in-web-design-what-it-is-and-why-you-should-use-it\" target=\"_blank\">white space</a>. Web designs are continuing to pursue minimalism, and white space plays a major role in the design transition. If used correctly, white space can “improve readability and usability,” according to web designers at treehouse.com.\n\nKeep in mind that white space doesn’t necessarily have to be the color white! In fact, you can substitute any color, but there must be an abundance of blank space occupying the web page used to aggregate or disaggregate elements.\n\n<a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/Screen-Shot-2014-05-30-at-11.46.25-AM.png\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-3129 size-large\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/Screen-Shot-2014-05-30-at-11.46.25-AM-1024x548.png\" alt=\"white space\" width=\"604\" height=\"323\" /></a>\n\n<i>(Source: </i><a href=\"http://www.beatboxacademy.ca/\" target=\"_blank\"><i>http://www.beatboxacademy.ca/</i></a><i>)</i>\n\nHave you noticed any other emerging web design trends? Next time you’re on an interesting looking site, make note of the way designers challenge the CRAP principles. You might just discover the latest trend!\n\nAnd speaking of web design, if you’re designing or redesigning a website, be sure to check out our <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/10-step-redesign-checklist\" target=\"_blank\">10 Step Checklist for website design</a>.\n<div id=\"hs-cta-ie-element\"></div>\n<a href=\"http://cta-redirect.hubspot.com/cta/redirect/308833/c8a87c89-3606-4616-9ad4-7f6681f8c3f8\"><img id=\"hs-cta-img-c8a87c89-3606-4616-9ad4-7f6681f8c3f8\" class=\"hs-cta-img aligncenter\" style=\"border-width: 0px\" src=\"https://no-cache.hubspot.com/cta/default/308833/c8a87c89-3606-4616-9ad4-7f6681f8c3f8.png\" alt=\"\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<!-- end HubSpot Call-to-Action Code -->','CRAP Principles in Latest Web Design','','publish','open','open','','crap-principles-latest-web-design','','','2014-06-03 09:57:36','2014-06-03 13:57:36','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3120',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3139,1,'2014-06-10 16:15:05','2014-06-10 20:15:05','What are PPC and Google Adwords? How can they help my business? If you’ve found yourself asking these questions, you’re in luck. This blog post is dedicated to teaching you all about how PPC Advertising and Google Adwords work, and how they can impact a marketing strategy.\n<h2>Important Distinctions</h2>\nFirst and foremost, PPC and Google Adwords are not different things. Google Adwords is a “flavor” of PPC Advertising. Or you can think of PPC as the main topic, and of Google Adwords as a subtopic of PPC. Whichever way you see it, know that PPC and Google Adwords are actually related to each other. PPC is the internet advertising model and Google Adwords is a type of PPC Provider.\n\nSecond, PPC Advertising and Google Adwords are not to be confused with SEO. Whereas SEO relies on organic search tactics to appear at the top of a search engine results page (SERP), PPC Advertising and Google Adwords are types of paid search. Paid search is one of most effective ways to acquire new customers.\n<h2>PPC Basics</h2>\nPPC, or pay per click, is an <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pay_per_click\" target=\"_blank\">internet advertising model</a> that is used to direct traffic to websites. Advertisers, or website owners, pay a fee every time their ad is clicked by a searcher. Advertisers or website owners specify ad placement, but they pay only when their ad is clicked.]\n\nHere is the formula to calculate PPC:\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">Ad Cost ($)</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">PPC = _________________________</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">Ad Clicks (#)</p>\nPPC uses real-time bidding. For example, if a searcher sees your ad, at that moment you have the opportunity to connect with the searcher by bidding on keywords against competitors that are also gunning for that keyword. The higher the bid, the better the chances of the searcher selecting your content.\n\nThe real-time bidding aspect of PPC also provides immediate feedback to website owners on how effective the advertisement was.\n\nPPC Advertising is based on keyword selection. Keyword research is imperative for a successful PPC campaign.\n<h2>Google AdWords Basics</h2>\nLike I mentioned before, Google Adwords is a PPC Provider. Other PPC Providers include Bing and Yahoo!. However, the <a href=\"http://searchengineland.com/strong-start-paid-search-grew-25-percent-q1-mobile-shot-135-percent-yoy-covario-188617\" target=\"_blank\">most widely used</a> PPC Provider is Google Adwords.\n\nHistorically, the Google Ads (which are now called Sponsored Links), were highlighted in yellow. Now, Google makes the Sponsored Links appear very similar to an organic search listing. I have outlined the Google Sponsored Links in red below.\n\n<a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/google_ad.jpg\"><img class=\"size-large wp-image-3145 aligncenter\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/google_ad-1024x553.jpg\" alt=\"google ads\" width=\"604\" height=\"326\" /></a>\n\nNotice how much space Google Sponsored Links take up. When a searcher clicks the ad, the website owner pays the current cost per click (CPC). The CPC is then deducted from the overall budget.\n\nAs a type of PPC Advertising, the goal of a Google Adwords campaign is to get your content in front of Google searchers who are searching for related content.\n<h2>Benefits of Using PPC Advertising</h2>\nSo, besides positioning your content in a more desirable location on the SERP, what are the other benefits of PPC Advertising? According to <a href=\"http://searchengineland.com/paid-search-spend-rises-8-percent-q1-mobile-shows-signs-maturing-report-188043\" target=\"_blank\">searchengineland.com</a>, in Q1 of 2014, paid search clicks “increased 5 percent and click-through-rates (CTR) were up 23 percent year over year (YoY).” The CTR figure is particularly encouraging for PPC campaigns, as it shows people are increasingly selecting paid search ads.\n\nHowever, not all PPC ad campaigns are successful. Like most marketing strategies, it depends on your target audience, budget and keyword selection. Chances of success, however, do increase with the help of a search strategist or marketing professional (to which I might add, we have a very skilled search strategist on staff). That professional can assist you in areas like keyword research, ad copy and strategic bidding.\n\nIf you’re interested in learning about what paid search can do for your company, feel free to contact us <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/#contact\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>!\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/kpereira/4264458679/\">kevinpereira</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.0/\">cc</a>','What are PPC and Google Adwords?','','publish','open','open','','ppc-google-adwords','','','2014-06-10 16:15:05','2014-06-10 20:15:05','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3139',0,'post','',2);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3155,1,'2014-06-12 09:00:19','2014-06-12 13:00:19','Just the other day I was talking to my mother when she proudly announced that she “got off Facebook.” I immediately exclaimed, “Why?” as if she just told me she was about to cut off her right arm. She replied, “It was making me feel bad about myself, and I don’t want to feel like that.”\n\nI immediately knew what she was talking about. In the age where <a href=\"http://www.pewinternet.org/fact-sheets/social-networking-fact-sheet/\" target=\"_blank\">73% of adults</a> use social media sites and <a href=\"http://www.pewinternet.org/fact-sheets/social-networking-fact-sheet/\" target=\"_blank\">85% of moms use Facebook</a>, social media was making my mother feel insecure. And as a hard-working mother of three, she should not feel like that. As someone who spends a lot of time on social media, I’ve noticed it has slowly grown from a networking tool to a place of self indulgence.\n\nAs a content and social media manager, I have a love-hate relationship with social media. I see how it gives companies the opportunity to connect with their customers, build relationships, and improve their company. But, I also see the “darker” side of social media.\n\nSocial media gives us this amazing ability to curate content; the ability to shape, build and form a completely new identity. Think about it - you show the world only what you want the world to see. That’s some amazing power. But with great power, comes great responsibility (sorry, I had to).\n\nMore often than not, people and companies take this opportunity to build a <i>perfect</i> profile. Instead of sharing awesome and diversified news, social media becomes a place to post daily self-absorbed personal updates. Social media has shifted from a place to share information about “we” and “us”, to “me.” I am not arguing that companies, brands and people should share sad or disheartening news - rather, they should share content that builds a unique identity and fosters a community.\n\nIt’s time to take control and shift the focus of social media back to its original purpose: giving people and companies a voice and engaging with people that you wouldn’t have met otherwise. So, in order to do that, here are my top 6 ways to avoid social self indulgence:\n\n<b>1. Say “Thank you!”</b> Not for every Retweet, Like or Favorite - but if someone goes out of their way to compliment an article, a design, your services, etc., use the opportunity to start a conversation. It will show the person that your company is grateful for the feedback and that you really do care about your customers.\n\n<b>2. Engage.</b> Duh! This is the whole point of social media. Ask questions, share content that your audience can use. If you perused an article that you really enjoyed, write a quick comment. Although this is technically outside of social media’s territory, engaging with fellow industry professional fosters a digital community.\n\n<b>3. Timing is everything.</b> Happy news is always great to see, but when it becomes an everyday occurrence, your content loses freshness and authenticity. Even worse, some people might view your company as annoying and unfollow you.\n\n<b>4. Understand your social media intent.</b> If you’re tweeting purely for Retweets and Likes, stop. Write like a person. You’re trying to connect with your audience. Write like you’re having a conversation with them. If you writing to get your numbers up, you’re bound to fail.\n\n<b>5. Show some personality.</b> While it’s important to share your company’s content, it’s also important to inject personality into your social content. This goes beyond using conversational language; it could mean giving your audience a behind the scenes look at the office, engaging with your company’s employees and community.\n\n<b>6. Listen to what you’re audience is saying.</b> In order to join your audience’s social media conversation, you must listen first. Monitor your audience’s social conversations. This will give you insight on what’s happening in your industry/community, helping you create and curate better, more relevant content.\n\nCall me a romantic or an idealist, but this is one social media manager hoping for a change.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/helga/3215253362/\">Helga Weber</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nd/2.0/\">cc</a>','How to Avoid Social Self Indulgence','','publish','open','open','','avoid-social-self-indulgence','','','2014-06-12 09:00:19','2014-06-12 13:00:19','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3155',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3163,1,'2014-06-20 11:17:36','2014-06-20 15:17:36','Some things are just meant to be simple. S\'mores are one of those things. Three simple ingredients create a recipe for delicious success. The same philosophy goes for increasing traffic to your blog. And if you’re looking to do just that, well, I have the infographic for you.\n\nJust like a s’more, increasing traffic to your blog doesn’t have to be complicated. Use these three tips and you’re bound to generate s’more interest and s’more leads.\n\n<a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/smore.jpg\"><img class=\"size-large wp-image-3164 aligncenter\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/smore-1024x642.jpg\" alt=\"S\'more\" width=\"604\" height=\"378\" /></a>\n<h2>1. The Graham Cracker = The Research</h2>\nTo me, research is like the graham cracker of the s’more sandwich. Often underrated and undervalued, research provides the foundation for any successful blog post. Without thorough research, your blog is likely to end up one sticky mess. Here are some elements you should include in your research:\n<ul>\n	<li>Clearly define the overarching goal for your blog. This will help you create cleaner, more detailed-oriented posts that people will actually connect with.</li>\n	<li>Know your competitors and industry standards. Conducting a competitive review is an extremely helpful research tactic. This will allow you to set more realistic standards and benchmarks for your future blog posts.</li>\n	<li>Last but not least, know your customers. The more you understand your customers, the more specific and engaging your blog posts will be.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>2. The Marshmallow = The Content</h2>\nContent, much like the marshmallow of a s’more, provides the substance. And just like the marshmallow, content is easy to under or overdo. You want to publish the right type content to the right people at the right time. Here are some tips so you don’t torch your blog content.\n<ul>\n	<li>Create content based on your audience needs, not on what you want.</li>\n	<li>Write content that is varied in nature - it doesn’t always have to be in written form!</li>\n	<li>Create content that your customers will see as a valuable resource.</li>\n	<li>Include CTA’s in blog posts. Hint: CTA’s are a proven way to keep people engaging with your brand. Think of them as an invitation to learn more about more useful topics.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>3. The Chocolate Bar = The SEO</h2>\nSEO is equivalent to the chocolate “<a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/HERSHEYS/posts/10150214419968304\" target=\"_blank\">pip</a>” on the s’more sandwich. And similar to the chocolate pip, SEO takes your post from average to amazing. Here are some blogging SEO tips to keep in mind:\n<ul>\n	<li>Research your long and short tail keywords.</li>\n	<li>Include keywords in header, page text, URL, and meta description (if possible).</li>\n</ul>\nLooking for s’more tips? Download our <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/30-lead-gen-tips\" target=\"_blank\">30 greatest Tips and Tricks ebook</a>.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/katewares/7727157120/\">KateWares</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/2.0/\">cc</a>\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/brandoncripps/1469171950/\">brandoncripps</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.0/\">cc</a>','Want S’more Page Visits? 3 Tips to Increase Blog Traffic','','publish','open','open','','want-smore-page-visits-3-tips-increase-blog-traffic','','','2014-06-20 11:17:36','2014-06-20 15:17:36','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3163',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3171,1,'2014-06-25 10:21:45','2014-06-25 14:21:45','Landing Pages, schmanding pages? Right? WRONG.\n\nThe landing page is a critical window of opportunity for lead generation - meaning that this is the one isolated place to convince a site visitor to sign up for your stuff…aka potentially become a customer! HUGE DEAL.\n\nRemember, landing pages are the “<a href=\"http://blog.hubspot.com/marketing/7-landing-page-design-tips\" target=\"_blank\">hub of your lead generation efforts.</a>” In fact, companies can see a “<a href=\"http://blog.hubspot.com/marketing/7-landing-page-design-tips\" target=\"_blank\">55% increase in leads</a>” when they up their landing pages from 10 to 15, according to <a href=\"http://offers.hubspot.com/marketing-benchmarks-from-7000-businesses?__hstc=20629287.4de294f25cf171ef8eb41c2e50ffdee4.1389735170385.1403287240780.1403290880292.30&amp;__hssc=20629287.4.1403290880292&amp;__hsfp=61287647\" target=\"_blank\">Hubspot’s 2012 Marketing Benchmarks Report</a>. And if you’re doing any inbound marketing, you need to create solid landing pages.\n\nHowever, if you only have a little bit of inbound knowledge, it’s hard to understand what the landing page actually does for a business. That’s where this blog post comes in.\n\nI’m here to give you some landing page help and assurance. Landing pages require specific elements in order to be successful. Keep in mind that landing pages are inherently different from other pages on a website; they are there to elicit visitor action, so they look and behave differently.\n\nThe image below is a screenshot of <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/30-lead-gen-tips\" target=\"_blank\">our most successful landing page</a> to date. I will use this example to explain the key elements of successful landing page. “Successful” in this case means highest conversion rate. So, here are the 6 vital elements of a successful landing page. Ready? Okay!\n\n<a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/Screen-Shot-2014-06-20-at-3.38.15-PM.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-3172\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/Screen-Shot-2014-06-20-at-3.38.15-PM.png\" alt=\"landing page example\" width=\"746\" height=\"627\" /></a>\n<h2>1. Avoid any visual distractions.</h2>\nYou will notice that in the Ingenex example above the navigation is gone. This is done in order to eliminate any other site browsing and help the viewer focus solely on the task at hand—downloading the offered content.\n\nGraphics of any kind can also be considered visual distractions. Notice that our landing page has one, <b>small</b> graphic. The image of the tablet does not distract from the surrounding content, but rather satisfies the user’s expectations of what the downloaded content could look like on their table. While some graphics can enhance a landing page, more often than not, they distract from the main purpose of the landing page. So play it safe - leave the nav bar out and graphics to a minimum.\n<h2>2. Keep the form fields short.</h2>\nRemember, filling out a landing page form is not the most exciting process. That’s why it’s important to keep the amount of fields to a minimum but still be able to collect the information you want to glean from your audience. We recommend using no more than 5.\n<h2>3. Brevity is essential.</h2>\nMost site visitors are scanning or “foraging” for information. Keep the copy to a minimum. The image below is a close up of our copy. Notice that it’s short, sweet and to the point. The bullet points clearly explain the offer, which in turn, allows the users to quickly consume the information and move on to the action.\n\n<a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/Screen-Shot-2014-06-20-at-4.10.52-PM.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-3173\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/Screen-Shot-2014-06-20-at-4.10.52-PM.png\" alt=\"bulleted list example\" width=\"539\" height=\"260\" /></a>\n<h2>4. Make the CTA pop!</h2>\nThis is a highly important and often underused suggestion. You want the visitor to complete one action, and that’s download your content. Place visual emphasis on this action by creating a CTA that contrasts from the other content. And as always, keep the CTA copy short and actionable.\n\n<a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/cta_example.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-3174\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/cta_example.jpg\" alt=\"cta example\" width=\"746\" height=\"627\" /></a>\n<h2>5. Keep audience demographic mind for design.</h2>\nReally consider your audience demographic. No two landing pages should be the same. Each should be created with a certain audience in mind, as each offered piece of content will be different.\n<h2>6. Keep your layout simple.</h2>\nHave you noticed a trend yet? Along with the copy, design and graphics, the layout of your landing page should also be simple. Landing pages are not the places to try out the latest web design layout. The best landing pages consist of clear, simple and minimal layouts.\n\nLanding pages don’t have to be difficult. However, they do need to follow a specific formula in order to elicit user action.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/yannickgar/5573449717/\">YannGarPhoto (Where are the stats??)</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.0/\">cc</a>','Landing Page Help','','publish','open','open','','landing-page-help','','','2014-06-25 10:21:45','2014-06-25 14:21:45','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3171',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3181,1,'2014-07-02 12:38:51','2014-07-02 16:38:51','Downtown Ann Arbor was filled with people this past Saturday (June 28, 2014) for Think Local First’s second annual Washtenaw Indie Awards street party. Located in front of our office, we had a blast attending and sponsoring the event to celebrate achievements of small businesses in our area over the past year.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.thinklocalfirst.net/\" target=\"_blank\">Think Local First</a> is an Ann Arbor based organization that promotes local businesses and creating a healthy, sustainable community for people to live. Supporting our own Ann Arbor community is so important to us, which is why sponsoring the event was a no-brainer. As a small digital marketing agency, we understand the importance of supporting other small businesses. It\'s a great way for us to build relationships and help out our community.\n\nOur own Derek Mehraban presented the Big Leap Award, honoring a business who \"took the leap\" and successfully developed a new business idea and solution.\n\nWe enjoyed the excellent live music and food from local restaurants—but, it was especially great spending the evening with people who share a passion for cultivating a strong, connected community—definitely a great way to spend our Saturday night!\n\n[gallery ids=\"3191,3190,3189,3188,3187,3186\"]','Ingenex Team Sponsors Think Local First and Washtenaw Indie Awards ','','publish','open','open','','ingenex-team-sponsors-think-local-first-washtenaw-indie-awards-street-party','','','2014-07-02 12:38:51','2014-07-02 16:38:51','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3181',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3198,1,'2014-07-08 11:53:55','2014-07-08 15:53:55','<h2>1. Programming Languages</h2>\nAt the very least, every digital marketer should be very comfortable with basic HTML and CSS. HTML and CSS provide the physical structure and design to a web page. Both of these markup languages allow you create basic documents like blog posts and landing pages, which are essential to a digital marketing strategy.\n\nIf you want to be a digital marketing superstar, try becoming familiar with PHP and MySQL. Why PHP? PHP is a general purpose scripting language and is used to create dynamic web pages. MySQL, or Structured Query Language, is an open-source database management system that is often used in conjunction with PHP to store and retrieve data. Both are often implemented into HTML pages, transforming a web page from static to dynamic.\n\nWhy would a marketer need to know such technical information? Understanding these languages and databases will help you synthesize big data, but it will also make more efficient, saving your company time and money (something your boss will love).\n\nFor example, Annie Cushing, owner and operator of analytics blog <a href=\"http://www.annielytics.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Annielytics.com</a>, says learning SQL helped her serve her clients better. Her overall efficiency improved, stating, “You’ll be able to query data then import into an Excel spreadsheet,” which saved her company time and money.\n\nLearning programming languages like PHP and SQL allows any digital marketer to build powerful and impressive dashboards right into Excel, without the hassle of waiting on an analytics or web development team.\n<h2>2. Analytics</h2>\nSpeaking of analytics, every digital marketer should be well-versed in this category. “Analytics” as a word, has lost it’s lingual command with the growth of the digital marketing. A majority of the time it\'s paired with soft stats like page views, number of newsletter subscribers, followers on social media, and visits to the site. Forget those.\n\n<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytics\" target=\"_blank\">Wikipedia</a> describes analytics as an “extensive use of math and statistics” and the “discovery of meaningful patterns in data.” If you want to be a successful digital marketer, you need to look at <i>who</i> is coming to your site, <i>what</i> channels are driving buying customers, <i>what</i> conversions are growing your customer relationships, and the lifetime value of your customers.\n\nBeing able to maneuver through these types of quality stats will lead to more tailored campaigns and serve as guide for future marketing decisions. As Neil Patel, founder of KISSMetrics would say, “Measure what matters.”\n<h2>3. Storytelling</h2>\nSo much of digital marketing today involves creating quality content. With that comes knowing how to truly connect with your target audience. Using your skills in programming languages and analytics, you can then begin to craft campaigns and stories that will resonate honestly with people.\n\nIn my experience as a digital marketer, data from analytics shows conversion rates of  site visitors to customers are higher when the content driving the visitors is centered around a story. What do I mean by story? It doesn\'t mean creating fairy tales or fables: It means using your brand’s unique voice in a unique and creative fashion. Whether that means creating a video, a helpful blog post, or a Pinterest board, it all should align with your audience’s statistics and preferences. To be a successful digital marketer, you need to be able to be creative and dynamic with how you present your content.\n\nSo there you have it, 3 things every digital marketer should know. What digital marketing skill is essential to you? Comment below!\n\nPhoto by <a href=\"http://www.mumolabs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Rayi Christian W</a>','3 Things Every Digital Marketer Should Know','','publish','open','open','','3-things-every-digital-marketer-know','','','2014-07-08 11:53:55','2014-07-08 15:53:55','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3198',0,'post','',1);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3204,1,'2014-07-10 18:47:04','2014-07-10 22:47:04','The Internet has changed many things, including the how companies and interact with their customers. Before I divulge into my series on lead generation, it’s very important to understand how the Internet has changed customer behavior. Let’s take a look back at the customer before and after the Internet.\n<h2>1. Marketing Inquiry</h2>\n<em>Before</em>: The relationship between a company and a customer started with a company inquiry. Companies reached out to consumers through mass, non-targeted sales pitches. These pitches included cold-calls, blast emails, and direct mail. This proved to be an ineffective way to contact and connect with potential customers.\n\n<em>After</em>: Through a variety of marketing channels (digital and physical), customers are the first to inquire about a relationship with a company.\n<h2>2. Marketing Information</h2>\n<em>Before</em>: Consumers have limited access to company product or service information. Often the only information available is the information given by companies.\n\n<em>After</em>: With the advent of the Internet, customers have access to a wealth of information. From online reviews to a company’s social media page, customers can now make extremely informed decisions prior to any purchasing.\n<h2>3. Marketing Tactics</h2>\n<em>Before</em>: Like I mentioned before, companies used a one-time blasts to target audiences. This tactic put all of the business power in sales, with marketing focusing on only the creative work.\n\n<em>After</em>:<em> </em>Today it’s about building and continuing a relationship with customers through delightful and amazing content. The power of business has shifted to marketing. Now more than ever, marketing and sales need to align in order to grow a sustainable relationship with a customer.\n<h2>4. Marketing Metrics</h2>\n<em>Before</em>: Data on marketing and sales efforts were gathered by third party organizations, like Nielsen.\n\n<em>After</em>: With the Internet comes the opportunity for businesses to track and quantify customer interactions, behavior, and transactions. Companies no longer need to go through a third party to gather customer data.\n<h2>5. Marketing Decision-Making</h2>\n<em>Before</em>: CEOs and marketing execs simply relied on intuition for all decision making.\n\n<em>After</em>: CEOs and marketing execs can now make informed decisions based on customer data gathered from their own analytics.\n\nSo, with so much of a consumer behavioral change, it’s only right that our marketing and sales strategies change, too. Introducing lead generation: The process of capturing interest in a product or service for the sole purpose of creating an effective sales channel. Stay tuned for future posts on how exactly lead generation works!\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/42931449@N07/6088751332/\">photosteve101</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','How The Internet Changed Your Customers: Before and After','','publish','open','open','','internet-changed-customers','','','2014-07-10 18:47:04','2014-07-10 22:47:04','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3204',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3213,1,'2014-07-15 14:21:56','2014-07-15 18:21:56','<h2>What Is Lead Generation?</h2>\nFirst, let’s answer what a lead is. A lead is a person who has expressed some interest in a company’s product or service.\n\nAs mentioned in the <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/internet-changed-customers/\" target=\"_blank\">part one of this series</a>, long gone are the days of a companies starting the relationship with the customer (aka cold calls, blast emails). Today, for example, a person will be surfing the web and come across a slideshow, eBook or something else they find interesting and useful. In exchange for that content, the person will give the company their personal information. Through this digital transaction, the person has become a lead.\n\nThis process is called lead generation. The exchange of valuable digital content for consumer information might sound familiar - very familiar.\n\nThat’s because lead generation is a segment of inbound marketing. More specifically, it falls within the second stage of inbound marketing, or the conversion of a site visitor to a lead (a lead your sales team can actually use).\n<h2>Why Is It Important?</h2>\nAnother way to think of lead generation is to think of it like collecting valuable information. Extremely valuable information. Information like a site visitor’s first and last name, email address, and company gleaned when they:\n<ul>\n	<li>Fill out forms for downloaded content</li>\n	<li>Share contact information for a coupon</li>\n	<li>Subscribe to an RSS feed or email list</li>\n</ul>\nInbound marketers collect and use this information to nurture that lead. Because the person has already showed some natural interest in a company’s product or service, this makes that person a more qualified lead than traditional, outbound leads.\n\nInstead of a shot in the dark, companies that use lead generation data are already a step ahead. In fact, according to the <a href=\"http://www.hingemarketing.com/about/hinge_research_institute\" target=\"_blank\">Hinge Research Institute</a>, 60 percent  of their leads online are twice as more profitable than those generating less than 20 percent of their leads online.\n\nAlong with higher conversion rates, lead generation can also be an very cost-effective solution because it focuses on aligning both sales and marketing teams—virtually closing any communication gaps (a common pitfall of many organizations).\n\nHopefully, I have answered the questions posed above. Stay tuned for our final segment on lead generation. In the meantime, for more information of lead generation, download our handy ebook, <a href=\"http://go.ingenexdigital.com/30-lead-gen-tips\" target=\"_blank\">The 30 Greatest Lead Generation Tips, Tricks and Ideas</a>.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/gerardstolk/6587076433/\">Gerard Stolk (vers le santiago)</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/2.0/\">cc</a>','What Is Lead Generation and Why Is It Important?','','publish','open','open','','lead-generation-important','','','2014-07-15 14:21:56','2014-07-15 18:21:56','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3213',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3217,1,'2014-07-23 10:32:43','2014-07-23 14:32:43','As a social media manager, I hear from people all the time that their company “needs a Facebook page” or “needs a Twitter presence.” Sure, I understand their want of being digitally relevant, but these people often underestimate the workload needed to execute a social media strategy effectively. A major part of the social media strategy that is far too overlooked and undervalued is social media monitoring strategy, a.k.a. who, when, what and how you’ll actually be responding to your social media interactions.\n\nSo, if your company is currently active on any social media, you’ll want to include these listening objectives in your overall strategy.\n<h2>Who</h2>\nWho will be monitoring your your social media? Depending on the amount of engagement your company receives, it’s imperative to delegate monitoring responsibilities to one person or a select team immediately. Establishing distinct monitoring roles and responsibilities will make responding to all social media inquiries a smooth operation.\n\nYou will also want to think about other teams that may play a role in your social media responses. For example, let’s say your company sells video-editing software. Will your monitoring team also answer technological or troubleshooting questions? Or will you need the full-time or part-time support from someone in IT or customer service? It’s important to think of all the possible ways your audience will use social media to interact with you.\n<h2>When</h2>\nWhen will you be monitoring? Will your monitoring efforts include nights and weekends? Or will they be during work hours only? Does your monitoring person or team have the freedom to respond via their personal cell phone or only through a company desktop?\n<h2>What</h2>\nWhat kind of content will you respond to? Social media gives people the ability to say, ask, or interact with companies in an extremely direct way. You need to be able to handle any good, bad, or ugly digital situation with grace and dignity.\n\nIn my experience, it’s extremely helpful  to approach crisis response management in a situational sense. Create and discuss likely social media scenarios with your team. Ask, “How will we respond if a customer says this?” No situation is off-limits. It is social media, afterall. The more discussion, the better prepared you will be.\n\nIf possible, try to treat each response to a criticism or mishap as a way to fix or rebuild a relationship. Social media gives you the opportunity to fix relationships with customers immediately, so take the opportunity and plan for every situation.\n<h2>How</h2>\nHow or in what tone will you respond? This question is especially important to social media monitoring teams. If more than one person is handling the monitoring, there must be an established style guide. The style guide includes the brand’s tone, grammatical usage and style of writing. Each person monitoring must absolutely adhere to their brand’s style guide in order to achieve a unified, seamless digital presence. The same voice must carry out in every digital interaction with customers.\n\nWhile there’s no one-size-fits-all approach to a monitoring strategy, these objectives are a great place to start if you don’t already have a monitoring strategy in place. I encourage you to sit down with your team or even just one other person and go through these objectives. Not only will your responses sharpen, but your overall strategy will significantly improve.\n\nDo you have any more social media monitoring suggestions? Comment below!\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/barefootadrianne/13222230715/\">Adrianne Behning Photography</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/2.0/\">cc</a>','The Importance of a Social Media Monitoring Strategy','','publish','open','open','','importance-social-media-monitoring-strategy','','','2014-07-23 10:32:43','2014-07-23 14:32:43','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3217',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3225,1,'2014-07-24 14:33:43','2014-07-24 18:33:43','Finally, we are to the point where I can show you how to start generating leads using your website. Three cheers!\n\nWell, not so fast. Here are the essential elements you are going to need to start generating leads:\n\n<h2>1. Landing Page</h2>\n\nFirst thing’s first: You’re going to need a solid landing page. For instructions and tips on making a dynamite landing page, check out these blog posts <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/landing-page-help/%20\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>, <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/5-questions-ask-publishing-landing-page/\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>, and <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/landing-page-timing/\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>. The landing page is the place where all the lead capturing magic happens.\n\n<h2>2. Forms</h2>\n\nForms are a very important element found on the landing page. Forms are the little boxes where leads fill out their personal information. When creating a form, we suggest using no more than four form fields. Ask for first name, last name, email address, and other information your company will find useful.\n\n<h2>3. Offer</h2>\n\nThe offer is attractive, irresistible content that your lead will download in exchange for their personal information. Offered content will depend on what your audience finds useful and interesting. Some examples of offered content are:\n<ul>\n	<li>Webinars</li>\n	<li>eBooks</li>\n	<li>Whitepapers</li>\n	<li>Infographics</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>4. Call-to-Action </h2>\n\nA call-to-action, or CTA, is the final required component of a landing page. A CTA can be an image, message, or button that asks the lead to download the offered content. A popular CTA you might see around the web is an interactive ‘Download!’ button.\n\nLike I mentioned in part two of this series, a lead is a person. You acquire the lead by attracting the person with pieces of content in exchange for their contact information. When creating a landing page, keep your audience in mind with every element.\n\nNow, with your <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/internet-changed-customers/\">knowledge of the digital consumer</a>, <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/lead-generation-important/\" target=\"_blank\">what lead generation is</a> and how to use it into your website, you’re ready to generate leads. Hip hip hooray! Hip hip hooray! Hip hip...you get the gist.\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/79136832@N06/8371468784/\">lookingforgoodpics</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','Part Three: How to Use Lead Generation for Your Business','','publish','open','open','','part-three-use-lead-generation-business','','','2014-07-24 14:33:43','2014-07-24 18:33:43','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3225',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3230,1,'2014-08-06 11:34:33','2014-08-06 15:34:33','Let’s face it. Pictures are fun to look at. That’s why Pinterest is one of the five most popular and widely-used social media platforms on the Web.\n\nPinterest is also a very effective marketing tool, garnering <a href=\"http://venturebeat.com/2012/04/09/pinterest-drives-more-revenue-per-click-than-twitter-or-facebook/#jTDeSZy2YJB157wc.99%20\" target=\"_blank\">four times more revenue per click than Twitter and 27 percent more than Facebook</a>.\n\nYou may be thinking, <i>But Pinterest is only for clothes, food, and home decor.</i> Wrong.\n\nIt is not just for retail.\n\nTo prove to you that all companies (including B2Bs) can use Pinterest to garner brand interest and ultimately more sales, I’ve rounded up four unique brands that are killing it there.\n<h2><strong>1. <a href=\"http://www.pinterest.com/subaru/\" target=\"_blank\">Subaru</a></strong></h2>\nI must admit, I have a soft spot for Subaru. Although I don’t own any of their models, I do always look forward to its <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/user/Subaru\" target=\"_blank\">canine commercials</a>. Subaru’s Pinterest page is effective because every board seamlessly comes together to shape its ideal buyer persona: someone who enjoys the great outdoors, cares for animals, lives a healthy lifestyle and gives back to their community.\n\nSubaru has also used Pinterest to increase customer engagement. One of its boards, called Fan Photo Fridays, asks Subaru owners to email an amazing personal picture of their Subaru. The best picture will be added to the Fan Photo Fridays board and used as Subaru’s Facebook cover photo for a week. Subaru’s Pinterest strategy is particularly unique as it’s allowing owners to take pride in their cars and ultimately invest in the Subaru community.\n<h2><strong>2. <a href=\"http://www.pinterest.com/generalelectric/\" target=\"_blank\">GE</a></strong></h2>\nWho knew machines could be so beautiful? General Electric is making industrial machinery into works of art. And with over 22,000 followers on Pinterest, it seems I’m not the only one who thinks these massive, sprawling pictures of machine vs. nature are super cool.\n\nI was particularly drawn to the way GE used the location element on Pinterest. On its Around the World board, GE used Foursquare pictures and location information to create an interactive map of all its factory locations. It’s a brilliant way to display its global presence.\n<h2><strong>3. <a href=\"http://www.pinterest.com/hubspot/\">Hubspot</a></strong></h2>\n“We also like to have some fun,” reads HubSpot’s Pinterest page description. HubSpot is an inbound marketing software that helps other companies attract and land sales leads— a true B2B company. Very little of HubSpot’s Pinterest content is dedicated to marketing principles and theories. HubSpot’s Pinterest page gives viewers a feel for the witty, quirky young professionals that work there.\n\nIn fact, seven of their 36 boards depict HubSpot culture or behind-the-scenes action. Showcasing company culture is a great way to sway potential customers into buying your product or service.\n<h2><strong>4. <a href=\"http://www.pinterest.com/drakeuniversity/\">Drake University</a></strong></h2>\nDrake University’s use of Pinterest is genius. All other colleges take note. Drake’s boards range from exploring Des Moines, to dorm room decor, to tips for finding a job after graduation. Each is speaking to a slightly different persona, but all manage to speak to a current or future Drake University student. They strike a meaningful balance of being helpful and fun to look at—exactly what Pinterest was made for.\n\nYou’ll notice, there is no one right way to use Pinterest. Whether you’d like to use it to show company culture or as a space for helpful information, Pinterest is a great platform to get creative!\n\nphoto credit: <a href=\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/mkhmarketing/8542140973/\">mkhmarketing</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','How Pinteresting...Using Pinterest for All Businesses','','publish','open','open','','pinteresting-using-pinterest-businesses','','','2014-08-06 11:34:33','2014-08-06 15:34:33','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3230',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3239,1,'2014-08-13 14:24:40','2014-08-13 18:24:40','Now that you’re convinced Pinterest could be a great addition to your social media marketing strategy, I want to give you some pin-spiring tips. More specifically, here are my top Pinterest do\'s:\r\n\r\n<strong>Do...</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>1. Have a specific Pinterest strategy. </strong>Why are you on Pinterest? Are you using it as another information outlet for your audience or are you <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/pinteresting-using-pinterest-businesses/\" target=\"_blank\">showcasing company culture</a>? Refer back to your overarching social media content strategy and find out how Pinterest fits in the mix.\r\n\r\n<b>2. Get creative with board titles.</b> How many times have you seen “Quotes” as a title for, well, quotes?\r\n\r\n<b>3. Curate other content. </b>The beauty of Pinterest is that it’s a wealth of beautiful, helpful information. Pick content that helps build your brand’s identity or showcases your cultural perspective. Pro tip: Curating content from partnering brands is a great way to showcase your connections within the community or industry.\r\n\r\n<b>4. Use individual boards to connect with individual </b><a href=\"http://blog.hubspot.com/blog/tabid/6307/bid/33491/Everything-Marketers-Need-to-Research-Create-Detailed-Buyer-Personas-Template.aspx\" target=\"_blank\"><b>buyer personas</b></a><b>.</b> Pinterest allows you to neatly compartmentalize information in perfect little packages called boards. Take advantage of the information architecture and use each board to appeal to a specific audience or persona.\r\n\r\n<b>5. Share your own content—sparingly.</b> The keyword in the prior sentence is <i>share</i>; Pinterest is not a social media site dedicated to self-promotion. If you are going to share your content, make sure it contains the following elements:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Your best visual content (no stock photos, please)</li>\r\n	<li>A short description</li>\r\n	<li>A tracking link</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nHope this serves as some pin-spiration! Stay tuned to check out my top Pinterest strategy don\'ts.\r\n\r\nphoto credit: <a href=\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/striatic/2135057566/\">striatic</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','Pinterest For Business Do’s','','publish','open','open','','pinterest-business-dos','','','2014-09-04 16:17:50','2014-09-04 16:17:50','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3239',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3244,1,'2014-08-15 11:12:11','2014-08-15 15:12:11','If you’re in the beginning stages of creating a Pinterest strategy or you already use Pinterest for your business, keep in mind the following on what <i>not</i> to do. (This is the second part of my Pinterest for Business Do’s and Dont’s. If you haven’t read my list for Do\'s, get the pin-spiring list <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/pinterest-business-dos/\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>.)\r\n\r\n<b>Don’t…</b>\r\n\r\n<b>1. Start the Pinterest strategy and then abandon it.</b> If you really want your Pinterest presence to have an impact, carve out time for content creation and curation and stick with it. Budgeting a specific Pinterest time once a week will help your content stay on track and organized.\r\n\r\n<b>2. Pin only your content</b>. Like I mentioned in <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/pinterest-business-dos/\" target=\"_blank\">Pinterest Do’s</a>, Pinterest is a place for discovery and sharing. Along with your content, curate other content that can help build your company’s unique identity.\r\n\r\n<b>3. Pin all your pins at once.</b> It’s visually jarring (and annoying) for followers to see a company’s pins dominate their homepage at one time. Pin throughout the week to keep your content fresh and viewed by many people as possible.\r\n\r\n<b>4. Use lots of copy.</b> Remember, Pinterest users are primarily looking at the picture, not the copy underneath. Keep all copy short and descriptive.\r\n\r\n<b>5. Be afraid to get creative.</b> Unlike other social media platforms, Pinterest gives businesses the flexibility to inject a little more personality into their digital presence. So, go ahead, make a board dedicated to cat memes: The pin board is your oyster.\r\n\r\nAre there any suggestions you have for what to do or not to do on Pinterest as a business? Comment below!\r\n\r\nphoto credit: <a href=\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/striatic/2191130107/\">striatic</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','Pinterest for Business Don\'ts','','publish','open','open','','pinterest-business-donts','','','2014-09-05 15:15:34','2014-09-05 15:15:34','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3244',0,'post','',2);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3249,1,'2014-08-20 15:17:20','2014-08-20 19:17:20','The good ol’ retweet. One of the magical elements of Twitter that allows you to seamlessly share content from anywhere and anyone. However, is there such a thing as retweet etiquette?\r\n\r\nAs Twitter has evolved from a simple microblogging platform to a place for breaking news, so has the retweet. In fact, considering all mobile, Web, and third party platforms there are multiple ways to retweet. But, which retweet, or RT, is acceptable to use today?\r\n\r\nGlad you asked. Below, I dissect the most common and current forms of the retweet, the pros and cons to using each format, and which retweet styles you should use.\r\n<h2>1. Simple retweet</h2>\r\nAccording to the official <a href=\"https://support.twitter.com/articles/77606-faqs-about-retweets-rt\" target=\"_blank\">Twitter Support page</a>, the plain ol’ retweets are “distinguished by the retweet icon,” which looks like a tiny green square with juxtaposing arrows. The picture below is an example of one of our simple retweets.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/Screen-Shot-2014-08-19-at-1.55.33-PM.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-3253\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/Screen-Shot-2014-08-19-at-1.55.33-PM.png\" alt=\"simple retweet\" width=\"589\" height=\"446\" /></a>\r\n\r\nPro: The simple retweet gives your Twitter profile content and visual variety. As a brand, it’s important to show that you care about other content, not just your own. It can also serve as an endorsement to another brand by giving full credit to the original author. Not to mention that some things on the Internet are just so awesome they should be just be simply retweeted.\r\n\r\nCon: The simple retweet does not include your avatar, so you’re given little visual credit. Your followers will see the original author’s tweet in their stream, so if they favorite or retweet it there is no way to track their engagement.\r\n<h2>2. Manual RT with commentary</h2>\r\nThis type of retweet contains your comment, RT, the original author’s @username, and the original tweet. This is considered the “old school” type of retweet, as tweeters have to manually input the RT abbreviation. The image below is an example of the manual Retweet with commentary.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/Screen-Shot-2014-08-20-at-12.15.18-PM.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-3254\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/Screen-Shot-2014-08-20-at-12.15.18-PM.png\" alt=\"manual retweet with commentary\" width=\"641\" height=\"323\" /></a>\r\n\r\nPro: The manual RT with commentary is the favored format of manual retweets by journalists and brands (other format is without commentary which we will get to later). It’s favored because the commentary provides insight and direction to followers about the tweet’s content. Along with being more conversational, the manual retweet with commentary allows you to keep your avatar, gaining audience recognition. This also allows you to view, track, and engage in any attached conversation.\r\n\r\nCon: Unfortunately, Twitter on your desktop doesn’t support this format. Only mobile app and some third party applications give you the option to quote the tweet and add your own commentary and RT abbreviation. Another con to the manual RT with commentary is that it often pushes the 140 character limit, so try be brief and wise with your commentary.\r\n<h2>3. Manual RT without commentary</h2>\r\nThe RT without commentary follows the format of the RT with commentary but excludes personal commentary (duh!).\r\n\r\nPro: Because you’re manually retweeting, your avatar will be viewed by your followers. Again, this visually gives credit to your brand; however, it questions social media ethics.\r\n\r\nCon: It’s a retweet style that is hated by most journalists as it serves little purpose beyond self-promotion. (In fact, there is a very funny and insightful Buzzfeed article on people’s general’s hatred of the manual RT without commentary. You can read it <a href=\"http://www.buzzfeed.com/katienotopoulos/the-latest-twitter-trend-manual-retweet-shaming#2o2lzde\">here</a>.)  It borders on plagiarism, allowing you to claim someone else’s tweet as your own.\r\n\r\nAs a social media manager, I suggest to refrain from the use of manually retweeting others work without providing any insight. It’s just not in good taste.\r\n\r\nIt’s important to keep on top of social media nuances, especially in terms of etiquette. So, if you want to show your brand in the best light, stay away from the manual retweet without commentary.\r\n\r\nphoto credit: <a href=\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/rosauraochoa/3330891783/\">Rosaura Ochoa</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\">cc</a>','Twitter Etiquette and Retweet Styles ','','publish','open','open','','many-retweet-styles-one-use','','','2014-09-04 16:16:21','2014-09-04 16:16:21','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3249',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `sandbox_posts` VALUES (3258,1,'2014-08-27 14:57:50','2014-08-27 18:57:50','I love email marketing. I love it because it\'s not only effective (it offers some of the highest ROIs out of all digital communications platforms), but it gives marketers the opportunity to personally connect with specific customers. If you need more convincing on why your company should be sending emails, read this post <a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/your-business-needs-send-emails/\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>.\r\n\r\nIt may sound strange, but email marketing is like an art form. A specific, yet very basic set of elements are needed to get your audience to open, read, and act on your email.\r\n\r\nThe graph listed directly below, Email Benchmarks by <em>Yesmail</em>, depicts email industry standards. Check to see if your click-through rates are on par with your industry\'s standards.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/email-benchmarks-yesmail-020614.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-3265\" src=\"http://ingenexdigital.com/media/email-benchmarks-yesmail-020614.jpg\" alt=\"email benchmarks by Yesmail\" width=\"628\" height=\"340\" /></a>\r\n\r\nIf you’re finding your email click-through rate is on the lower side, or you’re just getting started with email marketing, here are the basic elements needed for a successful marketing email.\r\n<h2>Catchy Subject Line</h2>\r\nAn eye-catching, actionable subject line is must for a successful email. You want to pull the readers in, but still leave something to be desired. Good subject lines speak directly to an audience’s needs, pain points, and emotions. I don’t buy into the hype that subject lines should be a certain character length - good subject lines will get the reader to open the email regardless.\r\n\r\nWriting tip: Like my first content manager told me, if you’re not satisfied with the first subject line, keep writing (in rapid fire style, nonetheless) until you create something that sticks.\r\n<h2>Design and Copy Fit for Skimming</h2>\r\nIt’s no secret that we skim-read and speed-read everything. Emails are no exception. Depending on the nature of the content, the email could be relatively short or newsletter long. In either case, you’ll want to use headings, bullet points, bolded words, and images to break up the information into digestible chunks. Using visual breaks will get the reader the information he needs, and be just the descriptive nudge he needs to download or click your offered content.\r\n<h2>Informal Language and Tone</h2>\r\nWould you rather read an email from a friend or bank? My guess is friend. Why? Because no one likes reading emails from dry, boring companies. But, your company doesn’t have to read as dry or boring. In fact, while I create email campaigns, I try to write as if I’m writing to a close friend or colleague.\r\n\r\nDon’t be afraid to use contractions, direct “you” statements, direct “I” statements, or a humourous tone. However, don’t go overboard.\r\n\r\nWriting tip: If your email’s language feels a little too casual or avant garde, it probably is. If you have to question it, don’t send it. Get a second opinion or play it safe and keep drafting.\r\n<h2>Segmented Contact Lists</h2>\r\nYour total audience can often be chunked into smaller groups. For example, say there’s a coterie of 10 leads and all seem very interested in your service. You know this because they all have consistently clicked your emails in the last three months. You can then create an email designed specifically for that group to nudge them into contacting you.\r\n\r\nOn the flip side, you wouldn’t want to send that specific email to your entire contact list as that information is irrelevant to all contacts, and you run the risk of unsubscription.\r\n\r\nSegmenting your contact list will not only help you get to know your audience, but create more defined, tailored messages.\r\n\r\nWhile no email needs to look or sound the same, they should always incorporate these specific elements. What are your tips for a successful email marketing campaign? Comment below!\r\n\r\nphoto credit: <a href=\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/houbi/4652382662/\">houbi</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/2.0/\">cc</a>','Elements of a Successful Email Marketing Campaign','','publish','open','open','','elements-successful-email-marketing-campaign','','','2014-09-04 16:15:43','2014-09-04 16:15:43','',0,'http://ingenexdigital.com/?p=3258',0,'post','',0);
